<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Rutskoi starts crusade to remove Yeltsin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Former Vice-President Alexander Rutskoi launched a crusade at the weekend to
remove President Boris Yeltsin and widen Russia to the boundaries of the old
Soviet Union, Reuter reports from Moscow.
Marking his return to the political fray, Mr Rutskoi proclaimed an end to
any compromise with the man who, in his eyes, sought to humiliate him in the
struggle that ended in bloodshed last October.
Mr Rutskoi scored a political triumph in winning re-election as head of the
renamed Russian Social Democratic People's Party, which appeared in October
to have turned against him. Few in its ranks backed him publicly after he
led an armed rebellion against Mr Yeltsin in the name of the parliament the
president had summarily dissolved.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
