<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Obituary: Goria, Italy's youngest prime minister, dies at 50
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Giovanni Goria, 50, who served briefly as post-war Italy's youngest prime
minister and was the first major politician to stand trial in the country's
massive corruption scandal, died at the weekend.
Mr Goria, whose coalition governed from July 1987 to March 1988, died at his
home in Asti in north-eastern Italy from a lung tumour which had
deteriorated in the past month.
The Christian Democratic party he joined in 1960 changed its name to the
Popular Party earlier this year before the March elections in which they
were punished for the corruption scandal which also touched Mr Goria.
He studied economics, entered parliament in 1976 and often described himself
as 'an accountant turned politician'. He became one of the youngest
Christian Democrats to told key posts, serving as treasury minister in
several coalitions.
In a message to Mr Goria's widow, Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi praised
his 'generous, passionate and long political commitment'.
Last February Mr Goria became the first major politician to stand trial on
charges resulting from Italy's seemingly endless corruption investigations.
He denied accusations that he agreed to a cut of a L7bn (Pounds 2.92m) bribe
to be paid by companies given a contract to build a hospital in his home
town.
Work on the L230bn hospital was stopped by the scandal and the alleged
kickback was never handed over to Mr Goria or his 10 co-defendants.
The trial, which embittered Mr Goria as his health failed, is still in
progress.
Mr Goria was the surprise choice to form the country's 47th government since
the second world war after the collapse of a coalition headed by Mr Bettino
Craxi in 1987.
</TEXT>
