<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Shadow cabinet splits three ways over leadership: Brown
starts his campaign to head Labour with appeal to socialist values
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, SWANSEA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The shadow cabinet was last night divided between three candidates for the
party's leadership as Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, launched his claim
with an appeal to traditional socialist values.
Mr Brown, delivering the keynote speech at Labour's annual Welsh conference
in Swansea, sought to shore up his standing on the left of the party with a
strong appeal to 'enduring' socialist values, and fierce attacks on the City
of London, privatisation and means-testing for pensions.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, will launch his candidacy in a speech
tomorrow, as unofficial campaigning accelerates after the burial of Mr John
Smith, former leader.
Friends of Mr Blair, the party's leading modernist, said he would also seek
to increase his appeal to the left with an 'inclusive and radical' campaign
platform to combine Labour's traditional values with modern policies.
Mr Blair has strong support in the shadow cabinet, but backing is flowing to
Mr Robin Cook, the shadow trade and industry secretary, who is strongly
supported on the left of the party. Mr Brown is running third.
Mr John Prescott, the traditionalist shadow employment secretary, appears to
have no firm shadow cabinet support, although support for him is emerging
among trade union leaders.
Mr John Edmonds, leader of the GMB general union, praised Mr Brown and Mr
Prescott for their commitment to Labour's policy of full employment. Senior
Labour officials say there is no doubt that Mr Prescott will be endorsed by
other union leaders if he chooses to stand.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, the acting leader, also appears to be without support
among her senior colleagues. Mrs Beckett has not decided whether to stand,
but is expected to continue as deputy leader.
Shadow ministers are refusing to endorse candidates publicly, in accordance
with a shadow cabinet ban on campaigning until after the European parliament
elections on June 9. However, Mr Blair is believed to have the support of Mr
Jack Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, Mrs Ann Taylor (education), Mr
Jack Straw (local government), and Ms Mo Mowlam (national heritage), who is
expected to act as campaign manager.
Mr Brown is thought to be backed by Mr Tom Clarke (development), Mr Donald
Dewar (social security) and Mr George Robertson (Scotland). However, Mr
Dewar and Mr Robertson would back Mr Blair if Mr Brown stood aside. Mr David
Clark (defence) is said to be undecided between Mr Blair and Mr Brown.
Mr Cook is believed to have the support of Mr Frank Dobson (transport), Ms
Joan Lestor (children) and Mr Michael Meacher (open government). Mr David
Blunkett (health) and Mr Chris Smith (environmental protection) are said to
be undecided between Mr Cook and Mr Blair. Mr Ron Davies (Wales) is also
thought to favour Mr Cook.
The level of support for Mr Cook is likely to hamper efforts by Mr Blair's
camp to persuade him to withdraw from the race and offer his support to the
shadow home secretary. Mr Cook has not decided whether to accept a formal
nomination for the leadership, but he is under strong pressure not to
withdraw.
Labour's ruling national executive committee will decide on Wednesday to
ignore leftwing calls for an autumn election and accept formal nominations
for a four or five-week cam-paign starting immediately after the June
European elections.
Senior shadow ministers say there is a growing belief that at least three
candidates will stand, forcing the party to use a preferential voting system
for the first time in a leadership election.
