<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Heseltine plans bar on regional pricing at Royal Mail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to draw up legally binding contracts to prevent a
privatised Royal Mail from introducing regional price differentials.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, has told Tory MPs that
the green paper on the Post Office will contain the proposed contracts
guaranteeing a uniform tariff at an affordable price.
But the possibility of BT introducing regional phone pricing has swollen the
ranks of Tory backbenchers worried that Mr Heseltine's plan to float 51 per
cent of the Royal Mail and Parcelforce could lead to a similar development
in mail services.
A number of Tory MPs regarded as 'Post Office sceptics', rather than
outright opponents of flotation, have warned they would vote against
privatisation unless Mr Heseltine gave 'cast iron guarantees' preventing
regional pricing.
Mr Richard Alexander, MP for Newark, said: 'If there was any suggestion of
regional pricing when it come to the Post Office - even if it was a few
years ahead - I would be opposed to privatisation.'
Another Tory MP privately said the possibility of regional pricing by BT may
force the government to amend or even drop its plan to sell a majority stake
in Royal Mail and Parcelforce.
He said many of his colleagues were very concerned that BT last week flagged
regional phone pricing as an option after the introduction of a new charging
system next year.
Although BT claims to have no immediate plans to introduce regional pricing,
the option is attractive as the company confronts stronger competition from
rival operators.
Mercury, BT's main long-distance competitor, already engages in regional
pricing. It is running a promotion in the Cardiff region offering
residential customers a third off standard long-distance Mercury tariffs.
Some BT executives fear that its ability to compete will be limited unless
it can react in like manner.
Mr Robert Hicks, MP for Cornwall South East, said: 'This is the slippery
slope. There are genuine worries being expressed about the effects of
privatisation, not for reasons of dogma but simply as a consequence of the
introduction of regional price differentials.'
At the time of gas privatisation assurances were given that price
differentials on a regional basis would not happen, although the government
recently agreed that remote regions could be charged more. Assurances were
also given at BT's privatisation that national tariffs would remain intact.
Union alleges sell-off plot, Page 9
</TEXT>
