<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Southern Yemen declares new state
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC WATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Southern Yemeni leaders early this morning announced that they were seceding
from united Yemen and declared a separate state, four years after North and
South Yemen united.
The announcement was made by Yemeni Vice President Ali Salem al-Baidh, the
country's southern leader. He said general elections would be held a year
from now.
The move was a slap in the face for the north which only hours before had
announced a three day ceasefire starting today to mark the Moslem feast of
Eid.
Earlier however North Yemeni military forces had stepped up their attacks on
Aden, firing two missiles into the port city and shelling a vital military
base 60 km to the north. Southern officials said one missile hit Aden's
airport, while the other was shot down over the harbour. No deaths or
injuries were reported in the attack. The missile attack broke northern
promises made last week not to bomb southern cities.
Northern troops also kept up pressure on the southern military base at
al-Anad, 60 km north of Aden, shelling the base overnight. Southern forces
were said to be counter-attacking with prolonged air attacks and ground
bombardment.
As the civil war entered its third week Western observers said al-Anad was a
vital defensive position for the south. Journalists approached to within 3
km of the camp yesterday but were prevented by heavy artillery fire from
getting closer to the battle.
Northern forces are also reported to be massing at Zinjibar, about 60 km
east of Aden. But western observers say southern defences have already
repulsed several northern drives from that direction.
</TEXT>
