<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Hawks &amp; Handsaws: The road to insanity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
On Wednesday I hurled myself out of London and down the motorway to Solsbury
Hill, overlooking the village of Swainswick, very close to Bath. Solsbury
Hill was the site of an Iron Age fort, and is a place of great beauty. But
now it is being raped by a bypass scheme which will stand, unless work is
halted, as a monument to the madness of John Major's doomed government.
It had been several months since I last broke free of London, so I was
stunned by what I saw as I steered my car westward.
England, it was clear, is being sundered by two colliding forces: the death
throes of the Tories and the first black waves of PMT (pre-millennial
tension).
There were peculiar sights everywhere. In some localities there were floods.
Whole villages were drowned. Survivors clutched church steeples. But after a
few miles the land would turn to desert, as though gripped by drought. In
places, mahogany forests flourished, or stands of bamboo; in others,
stretching to the horizon, was a tundra of ice-age flowers, speckled and
malevolent. The sky kept changing colour, from pearl to sulphur to scarlet,
and was filled with unusual birds: cockatoos, flamingos and the largest of
the albatrosses.
On those village greens not drowned by floods, the villagers were building
straw figures with hideously-painted faces - Major, Heseltine, Clarke - or
else they were building arks, or what you might call coracles, enormously
bigger than usual, and floating them down rivers, packed with their
possessions, and with household pets. In some places I glimpsed bands of
archaic homo sapiens, 6 1/2 ft tall, rudimentarily dressed, or even
archaically nude, skulking past coppices or emerging from earth mounds.
As a result of all this, I reached Swainswick, near Bath, in a state of some
terror. But my brain swiftly cleared the moment I saw Solsbury Hill and
understood what the fuss over the bypass is about. It is about insanity:
about carving a two-mile stretch of dual-carriageway, together with sound
barriers, bridges and a roundabout, through the trees and water-meadows of a
famously beautiful hill for a tiny gain in convenience for a small number of
people in the villages of Swainswick and Batheaston. The cost of this
desecration is put at Pounds 75m.
This is road-building mania on a completely crazy scale: an indication of
madness among ministers and officials at the Department of Transport, and of
degeneracy and decadence at the core of the Major government. Go to Solsbury
Hill. Walk up it, down it, round it. Examine the rape and vandalism. Ponder
the huge cost. Then join the protest.
At present, the protest is centred on the pale figure of Bel Mooney, a
prominent journalist (and recently-installed fellow of University College,
London) who has a house on Solsbury Hill and who is now on hunger strike -
consuming only water and fruit juice - to protest against the pillage.
Yes, there was a public inquiry, in 1990. Yet when she reflects on the
cynical limitations of that inquiry, says Mooney, she feels outraged by the
acquiescence which allows this destruction in the name of the people.
She told me: 'The bypass is expected to generate extra traffic of about 600
cars daily, but it is a two-mile stretch of dual-carriageway going from
nowhere to nowhere. Bath itself will still be heavily congested. What we
want is for them to halt the building work now, before the trees and
water-meadows are damaged beyond repair and pending a transport review for
the whole of the south-west.
'This story is a dreadful can of worms that needs exposing. I cried the
other day when the diggers tore down some trees. You have no idea until you
see it what a physical assault it is.' The issue of roads and the
environment, she insists, is not local but national.
After talking to Mooney, I walked up and down the hill, chatting to the
people that are rallying to the cause and gathering on Solsbury Hill, before
the concrete mixers start their work. I visited the eco-warriors' camps,
which the wreckers and the robo-cops plan to destroy.
It is not too late. The madness can be stopped. But time is running short.
Unless the roads minister, Robert Key, swiftly gains his wits, he will find
the whole of England over-run by ancient homo sapiens risen from their
graves, clamouring for blood.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
