<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Books: Economists' battleground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX WILKINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THINKING THE UNTHINKABLE by Richard Cockett HarperCollins Pounds 22.95, 390
pages
Some of my best friends were Keynesians, I think. So it is stimulating to
read a book which portrays John Maynard Keynes as the enemy of all sound
policies, a man who sold his intellectual soul for political influence, and
whose followers after his death tried to enslave Britain in the trammels of
the corporatist state.
Richard Cockett tells the story of an epic struggle against the evils of the
Keynesian consensus which grew out of the unemployment in the 1930s in
Britain and lasted until the glorious victory of May 4, 1979 when . . . but
I anticipate. The new regime begins only in the final chapter, entitled 'The
Heroic Age II' and lasts for a mere 23 pages.
Cockett's theme is, rather, the battle of ideas in which the principles of
liberal free-market economics were hammered and sharpened into a political
instrument called Thatcherism. It is an exciting story because it deals, at
one level, with the most important intellectual conflict of the 20th century
 -between the forces for centralised planning and socialist government
controls, against the old liberal tradition of individual freedom,
unfettered markets and minimum government interference.
The danger of Keynes, according to this account, was that he offered an
illusory 'middle way', including the benefits of a managed economy (to end
unemployment), but avoiding the evils of extreme socialism, communism and
fascism. The leading critics, Edwin Cannan, Lionel Robbins and Friedrich von
Hayek (at the London School of Economics) warned even in the late 1930s that
this middle way led on to a slippery slope of increasing government
intervention.
Hayek, pointed out then, and later in his Road to Serfdom (1944), that
governments which pumped money into the economy to create jobs would start a
'collectivist spiral'. It would lead, as another critic, Jacob Viner, put
it, to 'a mad race between the printing presses and the business agents of
the trade unions'.
Were these liberals foretelling the traumas of the British economy 40 years
later, when it was assailed by industrial strife, low growth and inflation?
Cockett thinks so and claims that Keynes was 'running up the white flag on
behalf of capitalism . . .'
After the war, the yearning for a better society was so strong that Keynes's
demand management and William Beveridge's welfare state became an orthodox
faith. The flame of capitalist freedom was kept flickering by an assortment
of pressure groups and by a more substantial band of liberal academics which
Hayek gathered at Mont Pelerin in Switzerland in 1947.
Their ideas were successfully popularised by the Institute of Economic
Affairs (founded in 1955) and later also by the Centre for Policy Studies.
Cockett tells his tale with the rather breathless spirit of a partisan
(adopting the tone of an academic historian). Much of his material, one
suspects, came directly from activists such as that pugnacious polemicist,
Sir Alfred Sherman, former director of the CPS and adviser to Thatcher.
Cockett is consequently much too kind to the counter revolutionaries, some
of whom had some very silly ideas, and were later abandoned by Thatcher, for
understandable reasons.
In this battle of ideas, economists (including those in the Treasury and the
London Business School in the 1970s and 1980s, for example) differed on much
more subtle and pragmatic grounds than Cockett seems to understand. Few
dispute, for example, that Keynes was right that the immediate cause of the
dreadful unemployment during the 1930s was a failure of economic demand,
whatever they say about later Keynesians. And Keynes told Hayek that he
agreed with, and was deeply moved by, most of The Road to Serfdom.
Most free marketeers, including Thatcher, accept that the state must play a
big part in modern economies (and she scarcely reduced the proportion of
national income dispensed by the state). Sensible Keynesians are much
exercised by monetary policy, while monetarists think deeply about aggregate
demand . . .
So Cockett has interestingly described a battle for hearts and minds as seen
by the infantry of the winning side, with scarcely a reference to what the
enemy was saying. We view in bright technicolour what Sherman thought of
Keynes and his snivelling disciples in the Treasury; but what would Keynes
have said about Sherman? Or of Cockett for neglecting this point?
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
