<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Sport: Sampras floats towards his slam - Tennis / John
Barrett looks at the men most likely to win the French Open
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARRETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'He seems to be flying. I have never seen a player play that well against me
. . . and I had the best seat in the house]' Thus spake Boris Becker in Rome
last Sunday, no longer the dominant superman whom Nietzsche would have
admired. The 26-year-old German had just been thrashed 6-1 6-2 6-2 by Pete
Sampras. It was the American's 27th consecutive winning match and his
seventh title of the year, the fifth in succession.
I am glad I was there to witness this virtuoso performance because few men
ever reach the level of perfection Sampras achieved that day. This was a
truly majestic display of controlled aggression on clay from the powerful
22-year-old world No 1 and was achieved without undue help from his serve,
usually his most potent weapon. 'I guess I'll have to work on it before
Paris,' he told me.
As we approach the 1994 French Open, the unofficial world championship on
clay which begins at the enlarged and improved Stade Roland Garros on
Monday, everyone is wondering whether Sampras, already the Wimbledon, US and
Australian champion, can complete a consecutive slam. With the holder, Sergi
Bruguera and the 1991 and 1992 winner, Jim Courier, both in his half,
Sampras was treated harshly by yesterday's draw.
In the entire history of the game only four men have won all four of the
game's great titles and only two have won them all in the same year.
Britain's great champion of the 1930s, Fred Perry, collected his quartet
between 1933 and 1935. Then, in 1938, the red-headed Californian Don Budge,
already the holder of the previous year's Wimbledon and US titles made a
special journey to Australia in quest of that title. Having won it Budge
proceeded to add the French Championship to his growing collection. He was
now the holder of all four major titles, the feat that Sampras is trying to
emulate.
However, it was not until Budge had won a second Wimbledon that year and
arrived in New York to defend his US title that John Kiernan, writing in the
Herald Tribune, suggested that ' . . . if he wins it will be the equivalent
of a bridge player scoring a grand slam in no trumps, doubled and
redoubled.' Budge duly beat Gene Mako in a four-set final. From that moment
the Grand Slam became the holy grail of tennis.
The great Australian left-hander, Rod Laver, equalled the feat as an amateur
in 1962 and repeated it seven years later in the second year of open tennis.
In between, his compatriot Roy Emerson won the first of his two Wimbledon
crowns in 1964 to complete his collection. Eventually Emerson would amass a
record total of 12 Grand Slam singles titles, but he never held all of them
at the same time.
It was Laver whom Sampras most admired when he was growing up in California.
At the suggestion of his first coach, Dr Pete Fischer, Sampras used to watch
tapes of the great man's matches. Unconsciously perhaps, he has inherited
some of Laver's most attractive qualities - modesty, shyness and a sense of
history.
Who might prevent Sampras from emulating his boyhood idol? Until Michael
Chang won the French Open in 1989 as a 17-year-old to become the
youngest-ever men's champion, no American had been successful since Tony
Trabert in 1954 and 1955. Chang's victory ended the hoodoo and paved the way
for Jim Courier's convincing wins in 1991 and 1992 against fellow American
Andre Agassi and Petr Korda of the Czech Republic. Here, we thought, was the
new strong man on clay.
It was a surprise therefore when Courier, a firm favourite to become the
first triple winner since Bjorn Borg (1978-1981), lost in last year's final
to Bruguera of Spain after holding a break of serve in the final set. This
was not the ruthless match player we had come to admire.
That painful loss, and another in the Wimbledon final, seemed to knock the
stuffing out of Courier who lost to the unconsidered Frenchman, Cedric
Pioline in the fourth round at the US Open and finished the year poorly. His
personality seemed to have changed too. He had become grumpy, supercilious
and withdrawn.
After a mediocre start to 1994 and another disappointing loss in Monte Carlo
to the 19-year-old Ukrainian Andrei Medvedev, Courier said: 'There is no
reason for me not to be happy . . . I have a career and a perfect family and
the fact that I lose a tennis match isn't going to change all that . . . I
just want to be happy and get rid of all that excess baggage on my
shoulders. I don't care that much about the rankings. All I want to do is
play my best tennis.' Which might make Jim a more likeable guy, but will rob
him of the intensity that made him such a great competitor. From No 1 in the
world in April last year he has slipped to No 7.
Another strong contender is the holder, Bruguera, in spite of the pressures
of high expectation. He must first deal with the tough Austrian left-hander
Thomas Muster, who won seven titles on clay last year, or the unseeded
Agassi. These two clash in an outstanding second round match.
The No 2 seed, Michael Stich, has a dream draw until Chang looms in the
quarters. The brilliant 20-year-old Russian, Yevgeny Kafelnikov, may reach
the same round at the expense of Cedric Pioline (14) and Stefan Edberg (3)
to test sixth seeded Goran Ivanisevic in the lower half. I do not see
Becker, Martin or Korda having any real chance.
The ladies? Steffi Graf to repeat.
</TEXT>
<XX>
