<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Summer Festivals: Dance takes pride of place
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After many fallow and frightful years, dancing has an honourable place once
more at the Edinburgh Festival, a fact surely not unconnected with the
opening of the new Festival Theatre, which is the desperate old Empire
Theatre re-born, re-furbished, and not before time too.
Mark Morris, who had a great success at last year's jamboree, returns with
his finest creation, L'Allegro, il Penseroso ed il Moderato. It crowds the
stage with memorable dancing, ravishing images. Handel's music will be given
by a distinguished group of soloists and the Scottish Chamber Orchestra. Not
to be missed: performances between August 20 and 22 at the Festival Theatre.
Also not to be missed is the Miami City Ballet, a strong company directed by
Edward Villella. Villella was a tremendous dancer for 20 years with
Balanchine's New York City Ballet, and he has made the Miami ensemble a home
for Balanchine choreography, which is danced with verve and clarity. Three
acts of the sublime Jewels are on view between August 15 and 17; a quadruple
bill on August 19, 20. Performances in the cavernously dour Playhouse.
The festival also presents Merce Cunningham and his dancers with two recent
pieces on August 27, 28 at the Playhouse, while another American
dance-explorer, Lucinda Childs, will be at the Playhouse with two programmes
between August 23 and 25. Canadian choreographer, Jean-Pierre Perreault,
makes his British debut at the King's Theatre between August 20 and 22.
The Holland Festival, Amsterdam, will feature three major dance companies.
Merce Cunningham and his newest piece, Ocean, will be at the Muziektheater
between June 27 and 30. Nederlands Dans Theater is mounting a special
programme of choreographies by Hans van Manen and Jiri Kylian, inspired by
the paintings of Mondrian, at the Muziektheater on June 2, 4, 5, 7. The
Dutch National Ballet shows new works at the Stadsschouwburg, June 25, 26.
The Aldeburgh Festival proposes three evenings by London Contemporary Dance
Theatre comprising new works by Richard Alston to scores by Britten, of
course, and to three movements from Stravinsky's Petrushka, at the Snape
Maltings Concert Hall on June 11, 12, 13.
The Brighton Festival offers several post-modern dance troupes until May 29,
with the admirable Jonathan Burrows showing us his newest creation on May 14
and 15.
On August 5, the Harrogate Festival presents an evening by eleven soloists
from the Stuttgart Ballet in an intriguing repertory of modern
choreographies.
In New York the New York City Ballet celebrates its 100th season with a
tremendous roster of Balanchine works at the State Theater until June 26,
and some novelties from mid-May onwards under the banner of the 'Diamond
project'.
</TEXT>
