<DATE>940521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Summer Festivals: Catch up with culture around the world -
Our critics offer a brief guide to a civilised break at home and abroad
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AIX-EN-PROVENCE
July 15 - 30
Ancien Palais de l'Archeveche, 13100 Aix-en-Provence, France. 33-42 17 34 00
Hard times have reached the South of France. From three operas Aix has had
to reduce to one: a new production of Mozart's Die Zauberflote by its
winning team of recent years, the conductor William Christie and producer
Robert Carsen. An uninspiring selection of concerts will probably not be
enough to tempt regulars back to this delightful town, though the food and
general air of good living might.
ALDEBURGH
June 10 - 26
High Street, Aldeburgh, Suffolk IP15 5AX. Tel 0728-453543
Britten and Stravinsky are the featured composers with a wide range of their
smaller-scale works on offer and a series of Stravinsky on film. The London
Contemporary Dance Theatre visits with a new programme combining the two
composers. The other stage event is Britten's Noye's Fludde. Recitalists
include Russian soprano Galina Gorchakova and pianist Pedja Muzijevic. New
music continues to features prominently with world or UK premieres of works
by Colin Matthews, Magnus Lindberg, Elena Firsova and Jonathan Lloyd
BAD KISSINGEN
June 24 - July 17
Kissinger Sommer, Postfach 2260, D-97672 Bad Kissingen, Germany. Tel
0971-807110 Fax 0971-807191
The attraction of Bad Kissingen is its north Bavarian setting and the
relaxed atmosphere of a former royal spa. The Regentenbau incorporates four
elegant concert halls, and there is also a fin-de-siecle theatre. Among this
year's events are a Schubert recital by Andras Schiff, song recitals by
Edita Gruberova and Wolfgang Holzmair, a Mahler concert with Christa Ludwig
and symphony concerts conducted by Donald Runnicles, Vaclav Neumann and
Vladimir Ashkenazy.
BATH
May 27 - June 12
Linley House, Pierrepoint Place, Bath BA1 1JY. Tel 0225-463362/466411
This is the first festival under the auspices of the Bath Festivals Trust,
launched to raise the profile of Bath as a festivals city. The theme of
'Ancient Echoes' links music of the past with music of the present. Kent
Opera, risen from the ashes, performs Britten's The Prodigal Son. Jonathan
Miller's staging of Bach's St. Matthew Passion gets open-air performances.
The Tallis Scholars, Frans Bruggen and Roger Norrington are among those
performing the music of the past, Gorecki and Nyman the featured
20th-century composers.
BAYREUTH
July 25 - August 28
Kartenburo der Bayreuther Festspiele, Postfach 100262, D-95402 Bayreuth,
Germany. Tel 0921-20221
This year's new Ring brings together arch-radical producer Alfred Kirchner
and arch-conservative conductor James Levine, but its most controversial
feature may turn out to be the designs of German illustrator Rosalie. John
Tomlinson's Wotan and Deborah Polaski's Brunnhilde are carried over from the
Kupfer production, and the new Siegfried is Wolfgang Schmidt. Giuseppe
Sinopoli takes over as conductor of Parsifal. The other revivals are Tristan
und Isolde and Der fliegende Hollander. Unless you are prepared to pay a
heavy black market premium, it is now too late to get hold of tickets.
BREGENZ
July 20 - August 26
Kartenburo der Bregenzer Festspiele, Postfach 311, A-6901 Bregenz, Austria.
Tel 05574-492 0223 Fax 05574-492 0228
The opera festival at the Austrian end of Lake Constance has won an enviable
reputation for artistic boldness, while preserving its appeal for tourist
audiences. David Pountney's spectacular 1993 production of Nabucco is
revived on the lakeside floating stage - counterbalanced in the nearby
indoor theatre by a rare staging of Zandonai's Francesca da Rimini, with
Mara Zampieri in the title role.
BRIGHTON FESTIVAL
Until May 31
The Dome Theatre, 29 New Rd, Brighton BN 1VG. Tel 0273-709709
This year's festival is the last to be directed by Gavin Henderson; 'Kindred
Spirits' and 'Romeo and Juliet' are the themes, featuring some prestigious
international theatre - the Odeon Theatre of Bucharest in Richard III, the
Wayang Wayang Theatre Company from Singapore, and the Wierszalin Theatr
Company from Poland. British theatre includes Cheek by Jowl's Measure for
Measure, the Wrestling School's staging of Howard Barker's Hated Nightfall.
Classical music includes a recital by Teresa Berganza; Mark Elder conducting
a Berlioz concert; and an all-Russian-music programme to close the festival.
Opera Restor'd perform the premiere of a new staging of Dido and Aeneas.
BRUSSELS
Until June 5.
Tel 010-332 223 2300
This festival presents performances, especially of theatre and dance, from
12 countries. Theatre highlights include Theatergroep Hollandia's new
productions of Marguerite Duras's La Musica Deuxieme and Lulu; the Belgian
Groupov's new Penthy 2, based on Kleist's Penthesilea; the Teatro Stabile
from Turin presenting two scripts by Pasolini, Calderon and Affabulazione;
the Romanian National Theatre of Craiova in Phaedra; and the Polish Stary
Teatr Krakow in Thomas Bernhard's Kalkwerk.
CHELTENHAM
July 2 - 17
Box Office, Town Hall, Cheltenham GL50 1QA. Tel: 0242-227976
Cheltenham is marking its golden jubilee year by celebrating 50 years as a
champion of contemporary music. Among the Cheltenham commissions being
revived from the last half-century are works by Maxwell Davies, Rawsthorne,
Maconchy, Lennox Berkeley and Williamson. To show that Cheltenham has a
future as well as a past there is an array of world premieres by Colin
Matthews, Powers, Heath, Bennett, Michael Berkeley, and a major new work by
Thea Musgrave. There is also a complete cycle of the Beethoven string
quartets.
CHELTENHAM LITERARY FESTIVAL
October 7 - 16
Tel 0242 521621
This has established itself as the largest in Europe. This year a new
director, children's writer Humphrey Carpenter, has introduced themed days.
For example, October 9 is Booker Day and introduces some of the short listed
writers, with critics giving their views on the likely winner. The 1894
Booker Prize will also be posthumously announced. Other theme days cover
science; psychology; the British whodunnit (with PD James); old devils of
20th century literature, starring Kingsley Amis; history; and the church in
literature, with Robert Runcie.
Among the writers promised are Alan Bennett, Douglas Adams, Craig Brown,
Susan Hill, Irish Murdoch, Joanna Trollope and Ian McEwan. Ralph Steadman is
Artist in Residence and he will stage the premiere of 'I Leonardo', his
imaginary autobiography of Leonardo.
DRESDEN
Until June 5
Dresdner Musikfestspiele, Postfach 160106, D-01287 Dresden, Germany. Tel
0351-486 6666 Fax 0351-486 6307
With its great traditions and court palaces, Dresden has enormous potential
as a festival centre, but recession and the cost of reunification are
slowing the pace. The new festival director, Michael Hampe, has threaded a
programme around August the Strong, whose accession as Saxon ruler 300 years
ago heralded a golden era in Dresden's artistic life. Visiting baroque
specialists include I Solisti Veneti and Concerto Koln, and there will be a
chance to hear rare choral and operatic works by Telemann, Handel and Hasse.
The Semperoper has Capriccio with Felicity Lott, plus a new production of
The Cunning Little Vixen.
DROTTNINGHOLM
May 26 - September 9
'Forestallningar', Box 27050, 10251 Stockholm. Tel: (0)77-1707070
In this 18th-century working court theatre with original machinery and sets,
the emphasis is on operas from the period of the theatre's birth. This year
opens with the Swedish Royal Opera in Ungdom og galskap (Youth and Folly) by
Edouard Dupuy. Drottningolm's own productions are Haydn's Orlando Paladino
conducted by Nicholas McGegan and a fantasia on the works of Handel called
'Heavenly Handel' with Barbara Bonney and Anne Sofie von Otter among the
visiting singers. Arriving by boat from Stockholm is a delightful extra.
DULWICH
September 24 - October 2
75 Calton Avenue, London SE21 7DF. Tel 081-693 3577
This community festival provides a showcase for local talent, both amateur
and professional. Highlights include Camberwell Pocket Opera's The Marriage
of Figaro, London City Theatre's The Dumb Waiter, a poetry competition, jazz
composition workshops and a sculpture project to enhance Dulwich Railway
station.
EDINBURGH
August 14 - September 3
21, Market St, Edinburgh EHl 1BW. Tel 031-225 5756. Fax 031-226 7669
The 48th Edinburgh International Festival must be the biggest ever. The
opening of the Festival Theatre, which at last gives the Festival a stage
large enough to handle the grandest lyric theatre, also means that director
Brian McMaster has another 24,000 tickets to sell.
Beethoven is the festival composer this year and the first production at the
Festival Theatre is Scottish Opera's Fidelio on August 15. Also appearing
there is the Australian Opera in Britten's A Midsummer Night's Dream, and
those Edinburgh favourites the Mark Morris Dance Group from the US.
All nine Beethoven symphonies will be played, by orchestras from Cleveland,
Stavanger and Hamburg plus the Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment, as
well as all his five piano concertos and many of his string quartets. Among
the musicians involved are Alfred Brendel, Andras Schiff and Piotr
Anderszewski. The other featured composer is Emmanuel Chabrier, a
contemporary of Bizet.
Opera North performs the pantomime-like L'Etoile and the comic opera Le Roi
Malgre Lui, while there is a concert performance of his unfinished opera
Brises. The opening concert at the Usher Hall is the Royal Scottish National
Orchestra with Mahler's 'Symphony of a Thousand', and the closing is Elgar's
'The Dream of Gerontius' with the same orchestra.
Making a return to the festival are directors Peter Stein and Robert Lepage.
Stein presents a Russian cast in Aeschylus' trilogy Oresteia, which will
last 7 1/2 hours, while Lepage gives a world premiere of his new work, The
Seven Streams of the River Ota, the river which runs underneath Hiroshima.
Among the other theatrical works on offer are Goethe's Torquato Tasso, about
the 16th century Italian poet, in an English translation; JM Synge's The
Well of the Saints from the Abbey Theatre of Dublin; and two Shakespeare
plays, Antony and Cleopatra, performed in German by the Berliner Ensemble,
and The Winter's Tale, performed in French by the National Drama Centre of
Orleans. Luc Bondy makes his UK directorial debut with a quintessential
international festival production, The hour we knew nothing of each other, a
play without words by Peter Handke, performed by the Schaubuhne Theatre,
Berlin. Over 30 actors will play more than 400 characters on the vast stage
of the Festival Theatre.
Ticket prices have been changed, making the best seats more expensive but
increasing the number of cheap seats. There will also be Pounds 5 'day
seats' for certain major productions. The Festival still lacks a strong
visual arts programme but the main summer exhibitions organised by the
National Galleries of Scotland, in particular 'Monet to Matisse: landscape
painting in France 1874-1914', will be on show throughout the Festival.
In addition, of course, running concurrently with the Festival, will be the
Edinburgh Fringe, the largest festival in the world and the national
showcase for comedy; the Film Festival; and the Jazz Festival, as well as
the Military Tattoo.
FELDKIRCH
June 13 - 26
Schubertiade Feldkirch, Schubertplatz 1, Postfach 625, A-6803 Feldkirch,
Austria. Tel 05522-38001 Fax 05522-38005
Formerly housed at Hohenems, this rarefied Schubert festival is now
well-established in nearby Feldkirch, where the recital halls are as
handsome as the wooded scenery of eastern Austria. Highlights include Brahms
programmes sung by Brigitte Fassbaender and Anne Sofie von Otter, Schubert
recitals by Cecilia Bartoli and Olaf Bar, and performances of Winterreise
and Die schone Mullerin by Peter Schreier and Andras Schiff.
GREENWICH
June 3 - 12
151 Powis Street, London SE18 6JL. Tel 081-317 8687
Eclectic and imaginative mix of events incorporating music (the Dirty Dozen
Brass band, the Flying Bulgar Klezmer Band, the English Chamber orchestra),
dance (with Yolande Snaith and company), comedy, childrens' events and
fireworks. Excellent for a cultural excursion en famille.
HAMPTON COURT PALACE
June 3 - 15
Hamton Court Palace, East Molesey, Surrey. Tel 071-344 4444
Twelve day extravaganza of music, dance and opera featuring Kiri Te Kanawa,
Montserrat Caballe, Sylvie Guillem and Willard White.
HARROGATE
July 29 - August 12
Royal Baths, Harrogate, North Yorkshire HG1 2RR. Tel 0423-562303. Fax
0423-521264
Harrogate boasts an impressive number of world premiers this year, with new
works by James MacMillan, John McCabe and Allan Charlton. The Stuttgart
Ballet give a rare and exclusive British appearance, Michael Nyman performs
solo and with his band, and Harrogate has its first ever Street Theatre
Festival.
HAY-ON-WYE
Until May 30
Tel 0497-821299. Fax 0497-821066
Most people, even non-readers, have heard of the bookshop at Hay-on-Wye and
of the Hay Festival, an eclectic gathering of writers and entertainers
reading from, talking about or performing their work. This year, there are
100 events ranging from Soweto Jive Music to writing masterclasses through
Indian cinema, mountaineering, Scandinavian poetry and a PEN lecture by
Carlos Fuentes.
Hay means instruction and delight. James Fenton, the new Oxford Professor of
Poetry, gives a reading on Saturday. Other poets participating include
Andrew Motion, Hugo Williams and Paul Muldoon. The final Sunday offers John
Mortimer on murder, Roy Strong on gardens, Fascinating Aida in cabaret and
the Brecon Cathedral Choir in compline.
HOLLAND
June 1 - 30
Netherlands Reservation Centre, Box 404, 2260 AK Leidschendam, The
Netherlands. Tel 070-320 2500 Fax 070-320 2611
This year's Holland Festival centres on opera and music theatre. The most
eye-catching events are rare performances of Chausson's Le Roi Arthus and
Max Brand's Machinist Hopkins, plus the continuation of John Eliot
Gardiner's Mozart cycle with Don Giovanni. Another theme is the idea of
musical realisation - such as Bruno Maderna's version of Monteverdi's
L'Orfeo. The concert programme focuses on young Chinese composers. Other
attractions include theatre productions by Peter Zadek and Peter Brook, and
a tribute to choreographer Merce Cunningham.
HUKVALDY
June 24 - July 3
Janacek in Hukvaldy, c/o Progressive Tours, 12 Porchester Place, London WC2
2BS. Tel 071-262 1676 Fax 071-724 6941
Hukvaldy is a peaceful town in the heart of the north Moravian countryside,
where Czech composer Leos Janacek was born in 1854. The organisers of this
new festival aim to make it a centre of pilgrimage for all who admire
Janacek's music. The Cunning Little Vixen, staged by ENO staff producer
David Sulkin, will be performed in the open-air at Hukvaldy park, while
musicians from the nearby city of Ostrava will give concerts in the medieval
castle.
ISTANBUL
June 15 - July 21
Istanbul International Festival, Yildiz-Besiktas, TR-80746 Istanbul, Turkey.
Tel 212-258 3212 Fax 212-261 8823
Istanbul's arts festival aims to stress the city's historic role as a bridge
between Europe and Asia, but its programme is unashamedly western in origin.
This year's guests include the BBC Symphony Orchestra under Gunther Herbig,
the English Chamber Orchestra under James Judd and Dresden Philharmonic with
soprano Hildegard Behrens. Valery Gergiev conducts the Kirov Opera Orchestra
and Chorus in a series of concerts, and Roland Petit brings his Ballet
National de Marseille.
KREUTH
July 3 - 17
Internationales Oleg-Kagan-Musikfest am Tegernsee, Kurverwaltung Kreuth,
Postfach 5, D-83708 Kreuth, Germany. Tel 08029-1819 Fax 08029-1828
The lakeside setting of Kreuth, a former court spa at the foot of the
Bavarian Alps, makes this one of Europe's most peaceful and intimate
festivals. It was founded five years ago by the late Russian violinist Oleg
Kagan and his cellist wife Natalia Gutman, and is notable for attracting
high-powered virtuosi. This year's programme is headed by Sviatoslav Richter
and Martha Argerich.
KYBURGIADE
August 4 - 10
Internationales Kammermusik-Festival auf Schloss Kyburg, Postfach 408,
CH-8400 Winterthur, Switzerland. Tel 01-251 4044 Fax 01-251 4060
Now in its third year, the Kyburgiade owes its unique atmosphere to the
open-air setting of Kyburg Castle near the Swiss town of Winterthur, and to
the participation of one of Europe's leading young string quartets, the
Carmina Quartet. They are joined by London Baroque, the Hagen Quartet, I
Musici di Roma, pianist Paul Gulda and oboist Hansjorg Schellenberger, in
programmes focusing on Bach, Mozart and Vivaldi.
LA ROQUE D'ANTHERON
July 30 - August 21
Festival de Piano, Chateau de Florans, 13640 La Roque d'Antheron, France.
Tel 4250 5115 Fax 4250 4889
The castle grounds of La Roque d'Antheron, equidistant from Avignon and
Marseille, provide a serene provencal atmosphere for a piano festival of
increasing international renown. You may not find Richter or Pollini here,
but the festival does offer the cream of French pianists, plus other
well-established artists such as Nelson Freire, Deszo Ranki, Stephen Hough
and Elisabeth Leonskaja.
LONDON, THE PROMS
July 15 - September 10
Promenade Concerts Ticket Shop, Royal Albert Hall, London SW7 2AP.
Tel:071-589 8212
The Proms are celebrating their 100th season. The temptation to look back
over a century as Britain's largest music festival has proved irresistible
and this year's programme comprises a survey of the people and ideals that
have made the Proms so successful. Among the great figures of Proms' history
allowed evenings in their tribute are William Glock, Malcolm Sargent and
Henry Wood. The programme of 6 September 1900 is repeated in its entirety,
an amusing historical exercise. The work of the Proms in encouraging new
music is recognised by recalling past premieres by composers such as Maw,
Bliss, Schoenberg and Britten. Among major premieres new this year are
Maxwell Davies's Fifth Symphony and Tavener's The Apocalypse. The visiting
orchestras include the Berlin Philharmonic, the Cleveland Orchestra, the
Dresden Staatskapelle, Los Angeles Philharmonic and Pittsburgh Symphony
Orchestra.
LUCERNE
August 17 - September 10
Internationale Musikfestwochen Luzern, Hirschmattstrasse 13, Postfach,
CH-6002 Lucerne, Switzerland. Tel 041-233080 Fax 041-239464
Under Matthias Bamert, Switzerland's premier festival has taken on an
adventurous slant. Focal points this year are a 70th birthday tribute to
Swiss composer Klaus Huber, whose new piano concerto will be premiered by
Andras Schiff, and a wide-ranging exploration of the way music is
interpreted. Four different performances will be built around Schubert's
Winterreise, including a new opera, augmented by offbeat events breaking all
the rules of traditional concert form. The conventional side to the festival
is as strong as ever, with leading orchestras from Berlin, Vienna,
Amsterdam, Cleveland and Dresden.
MALTA
June 2 - 5
Manoel Theatre, Valletta. Tel 010-356 222618 Fax 356-247 451
This year's festival embraces music, architecture and the Maltese heritage.
Together with concerts by the orchestra Aula Classica Salisburgensis
(performing on period instruments) and The Manoel Theatre Orchestra, there
is an extensive programme of lectures and guided tours of local galleries
and museums.
MONTPELLIER
July 10 - August 4
Festival de Radio France, Le Corun, BP 9214, 34043 Montepellier Cedex 01,
France. Tel 6702 0201
Apart from its setting in southern France, the attraction of Radio France's
annual festival is its selection of rare operas. This year sees concert
performances of Saint-Saens' Etienne Marcel and Montemezzi's L'amore dei tre
re, plus the first-ever staging of Cimarosa's L'Armida immaginaria.
MONTREUX
August 21 - September 23
Festival de Musique Montreux-Vevey, Rue du Theatre 5, Case postale 162,
CH-1820 Montreux 2, Switzerland. Tel 021-963 5450 Fax 021-963 2506
Montreux offers a sultry lakeside setting, and a haphazard collection of
orchestras and soloists from the summer festival circuit. This year's
programme opens with a Pollini recital and ends with Martha Argerich playing
Beethoven. Other visitors include Anne-Sophie Mutter, the Pittsburgh
Symphony under Maazel and the Orchestra of La Scala under Giulini.
MUNICH
July 6 - 31
Festspielkasse der Bayerischen Staatsoper, Maximilianstrasse 11, D-80539
Munich, Germany. Tel 089-221316
Peter Jonas' first Munich Opera Festival opens with Tannhauser - and by
handing the production to David Alden he is clearly aiming to unsettle
Munich's conservative public and critics. Zubin Mehta conducts. The festival
offers a retrospective on Jonas' first year as intendant in Munich,
including Tom Cairns' dire production of Un ballo in maschera and Richard
Jones' Jurassic Park version of Giulio Cesare. Cheryl Studer sings in La
traviata, and Eckehard Mayer's new opera Sansibar can be seen in the
Cuvillies-Theater.
OSLO
August 3 - 13
Oslo Chamber Music Festival, Inkognitogt 33, 0256 Oslo, Norway. Tel 2255
2553 Fax 2255 2554
Founded by Norwegian violinist Arve Tellefsen in 1989, the Oslo Chamber
Music Festival has quickly won a reputation for conviviality and musical
quality. Concerts take place in churches, castles and concert halls around
Oslo, with each year's programme focusing on a different country. This year
is Britain's turn, with music ranging from Byrd and Bridge to David Matthews
and Oliver Knussen. The Nash and Hilliard Ensembles are taking part, while
Truls Mork will play Elgar's Cello Concerto and Yuri Bashmet gives a viola
recital.
PESARO
August 11 - 29.
Via Rossini 37, 61100 Pesaro. Tel: (0)721-33184
This exquisite walled town on the Adriatic was Rossini's birthplace. Each
year it brings together genteel lovers of the Italian maestro's music, who
come to explore some of his lesser-known operas, alongside bucket-and-spade
beach-goers. This year's programme includes productions of L'inganno felice
produced by Graham Vick, Semiramide conducted by Roger Norrington and
L'italiana in Algeri produced by Dario Fo.
SAINT LOUIS
May 21 - June 26
Opera Theater of Saint Louis, PO Box 191910, Saint Louis, Missouri 63119,
USA. Tel 314-961 0171
Saint Louis - one of the world's most pleasurable opera festivals - offers a
characteristically adventurous diet: Colin Graham stages the first US
performance of Bernstein's final revised version of Candide, Andrew Litton
conducts Falstaff, the outstanding young American soprano Patricia Racette
sings the title role in Iphigenie en Tauride, and there is a dusting-off of
Conrad Susa's Black River (1975). Theatre conditions are intimate, and
picnics on the lawns of the Loretto-Hilton Center round off the amiable
atmosphere.
SALZBURG
July 25 - August 31
Kartenburo der Salzburger Festspiele, Postfach 140, A-5010 Salzburg. Tel
0662-846682 Fax 0662-844501
The 1994 festival takes to the sky with the premiere of Stockhausen's
Helicopter Quartet: while the composer controls the sound electronically in
the Mozarteum, members of the Arditti Quartet will play their parts in four
airborne helicopters. Back on terra firma, this year's flagship production
is Don Giovanni, staged by Patrice Chereau and conducted by Daniel
Barenboim, with a cast headed by Ferruccio Furlanetto, Bryn Terfel,
Catherine Malfitano and Cecilia Bartoli. The opera programme otherwise has a
Russian emphasis, with three Stravinsky stagings and a transfer of the
Claudio Abbado/Herbert Wernicke production of Boris Godunov from the Easter
Festival, with Samuel Ramey in the title role. In the concert hall, Nikolaus
Harnoncourt conducts the Chamber Orchestra of Europe in two cycles of
Beethoven symphonies. The drama programme continues to gather strength, with
Shakespeare's Antony and Cleopatra directed by Peter Stein, and Pirandello's
The Mountain Giants directed by Luca Ronconi.
SANTA FE
July 1 - August 27
PO Box 2408, Santa Fe, New Mexico 87504, USA. Tel 505-986 5900 Fax 505-989
7012
The most eye-catching feature is the American premiere of Judith Weir's
Blond Eckbert, less than four months after it was unveiled by ENO. Francesca
Zambello produces this and Il barbiere di Siviglia. This year's other new
productions are Tosca directed by John Copley with Mary Jane Johnson in the
title role, and Entfuhrung directed by Graham Vick. A revival of Goran
Jarvefelt's 1984 production of Intermezzo completes the bill. And the
pleasures of the place itself never pall.
SAVONLINNA
July 6 - 30
Savonlinna Opera Festival, Olavinkatu 35, 57130 Savonlinna, Finland. Tel
057-514700 Fax 057-21866
No-one who visits Finland's premier summer festival can fail to be impressed
by the stone castle courtyard in which it takes place. Poised on the edge of
a lake, Olaf's Castle (Olavinlinna) is one of the world's outstanding
outdoor locations for opera. The 1994 programme is one of the least
distinctive of recent years, with a revival of last year's successful
Macbeth and a visit from the Hungarian National Opera. Perhaps the festival
is husbanding its resources for next year's big splash - a new opera by
Finland's leading composer, Aulis Salinnen.
SCHLESWIG-HOLSTEIN.
June 26 - August 21
Box Office, Postfach 38 40, 24037 Kiel. Telefax 0431-56 91 52
Stretching from Westerland in the North to Hamburg in the South, the
Schleswig-Holstein festival embraces everything from family music days in
country barns to high culture. This year's programme places a special
emphasis on Jewish music. There are visits from the Israel Philharmonic and
Symphony Orchestras, the Jerusalem Symphony Orchestra and young musicians
from Israel. Jewish composers being represented include those banned during
the Nazi era, such as Ullmann, Haas and Klein from the concentration camps,
and Mendelssohn and Mahler. There is also a retrospective of Beethoven.
SPOLETO
June 22 - July 10
Associazione Festival dei Due Mondi, Via Cesare Beccaria 18, 00196 Rome,
Italy. Tel 06-321 0288 Fax 06-320 0747
Spoleto offers a hot, hectic round-the-clock collage of events, spearheaded
by two productions in the Teatro Nuovo - Wozzeck staged by avant-garde
German producer Gunter Kramer, and a Poulenc double-bill pairing his surreal
opera Les mamelles de Tiresias with a reconstruction of Nijinska's original
choreography of Les Biches. There will also be performances by the Martha
Graham Dance Company and Roland Petit's Ballet National de Marseille.
ST MAGNUS
June 17 - 22
Tourist Information Centre, Kirkwall, Orkney, Scotland KW15 1DE. Tel
0856-872856
This lively community festival has enlisted the Seamus Heaney, the BBC
Philharmonic Orchestra, the Chamber Group of Scotland and mezzo Della Jones
for its 1994 activities.
TANGLEWOOD
July 1 - Sep 4
Tanglewood Ticket Office, Symphony Hall, Boston, MA 02115, USA. Tel 617-266
1492. From mid-June: Tanglewood Ticket Office, Tanglewood, Lenox, MA 01240.
Tel 617-931 2000
The Boston Symphony Orchestra's summer home provides a relaxed setting for
concerts in the heart of the Massachusetts countryside. This year sees the
opening of a new concert hall, Tanglewood's first new concert facility for
more than 50 years. A warm-up series of concerts over the Fourth of July
weekend features Wynton Marsalis and Liza Minnelli, followed by the formal
opening on July 7 by the BSO under Seiji Ozawa. Guest conductors include
Bernard Haitink, Mariss Jansons and Andre Previn, while Itzhak Perlman, Ute
Lemper, Thomas Hampson and Hermann Prey are among the soloists.
TORROELLA DE MONTGRI
July 8 - August 26
Festival Internacional de Musica, Apartat 70, C/Codina 28 1r, 17257
Torroella de Montgri, Spain. Tel 072-761098 Fax 072-760648
Torroella de Montgri is a small Catalan town six km from the sea on the
Costa Brava, but it is not primarily a tourist resort. The town-centre is
architecturally typical of the Emporda, the natural surroundings are lovely
and numerous cultural activities take place throughout the year. The summer
music festival mixes Spanish artists of the calibre of Giacomo Aragall and
Jordi Savall with international guests such as the Franz Liszt Chamber
Orchestra and the Choir and Orchestra of the St Petersburg Capella.
WEXFORD
October 20 - November 6
Theatre Royal, High Street, Wexford, Ireland. Tel 0353-53 22144
Elaine Padmore's final season as artistic director brings a classic Wexford
trio of neglected operas: The Demon by Anton Rubinstein, La Boheme by
Leoncavallo and Wagner's Das Liebesverbot. A full concert schedule includes
recitals by Wexford's young singers, operatic scenes and late-night cabaret.
The homely atmosphere belies the fact that serious opera-lovers cross oceans
to sample Wexford's operatic rarities.
