<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Travel (France): Up-country retreats - Practical Traveller /
Nicholas Woodsworth offers some out-the-way alternatives to the heat and
bustle of Provence in summer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS WOODSWORTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
My father-in-law, Rene Luc, is 81 years old, Provencal through and through,
and has never lived anywhere else in his life. A passionate fisherman, he
admits that the region is somewhat short on decent trout streams. Apart from
that, he reckons Provence is just about as fine a place as anyone could want
to live.
But come July and August, the months when visitors from all over the world
crowd into every nook and cranny of Provence, Dordogne and the Riviera, Rene
is rarely to be found at home. For decades now he and his wife Odette have
retreated up-country for their summer holidays, to areas of southern France
that are virtually ignored by French and foreign holiday-makers alike.
It is not just the lack of crowds, cars, stressed waiters and
over-subscribed facilities that attract them there. Like most locals, they
find the northerner's love of sitting in the blazing Midi sun somewhat
potty: Provence is simply too hot in mid-summer to be comfortable.
The places they choose - none more than three or four hours' drive away -
are all cool, green and 1,000m high or more. Here in villages and unspoiled
countryside they get all the sunny character of the Midi in summertime
without the exhausting heat and crowds.
Their second objective is to come away from an enjoyable holiday without
paying an arm and a leg for it. Accommodation up-country might not be as
sophisticated as along the Cote d'Azur but it has its compensations: hosts
that are almost always friendly and hospitable, generous offerings of
high-quality country cooking, and bills that by European standards can be
astonishingly low.
Chambre d'hote and table d'hote - accommodation and food provided in private
homes, usually farms and country houses - are always one possibility. For
longer stays, my parents-in-law generally find auberges located in small
towns and villages more convenient. There are still many such establishments
where demi-pension (accommodation and two vast meals) is offered for little
more than Pounds 20 a day.
Where, then, are these areas? Not long ago I cornered Rene in his garage as
he was digging out trout flies and dusting off his fishing rod in
preparation for the summer season. Here are some of them from his little
black book.
The Cevennes (see above). One of the wildest and least populated areas in
France, the steep hills and valleys of the Cevennes have also discouraged
the development of all but the simplest tourist facilities. But for the
beauty of its landscapes, for its remote stone-built hamlets, rugged walks
and a way of life that has changed little over the centuries, it is well
worth a visit.
The Cevennes is marvellously refreshing when most of the Midi lies hot and
panting. For those seeking comfort, the small market-town of Florac is
probably the best bet. It is also the gateway to the high, lonely plateaux
of the Causses and the spectacular Gorge du Tarn, a descent of which is
inspiring by car, and thrilling by canoe. In Florac, the Hotel du Parc (tel:
66 45 03 05) offers most facilities, including pool, and an excellent
restaurant.
For those prepared to put up in more rustic accommodation, lists of chambre
d'hotes are available in the syndicats d'initiatives, or tourist offices, of
local towns. For a night on a remote Cevenol hillside farm (goats and
donkeys included), nothing could be more genuine than La Deveze in the
Trabassac Valley (prop: Marie-Claude Charbonnier, tel: 66 44 74 41).
L'Aubrac. Less than 100km from the enclosed valleys of the Cevennes, the
Aubrac region, on the border of the departements of Lozere and Cantal, is a
vast sweep of high, open plateaux. Treeless, and stretching to an empty
horizon, it is spectacular and dramatic. Carpeted in drifting snow in
winter, it is an open range for cattle in summer.
The village of Nasbinals, just to the west of these great open spaces, is
the easiest place to stay to take advantage of the walking, lakes and
fishing in the area. The Hotel de la Route d'Argent (prop: Pierre Bastide,
tel: 66 32 50 03) provides comfortable accommodation and a splendid country
kitchen for very reasonable prices.
For those with more sophisticated tastes and thicker wallets, the small town
of Laguiole is only half-an-hour's drive away. In addition to making some of
the best cutlery in France, it is the town chosen by celebrated chef Michel
Bras for the freshness and purity of its products. But beware: his
restaurant here is a favourite summer pilgrimage of Paris politicians and
other luminaries; reservations are often made a year in advance.
Le Queyras. Entirely different again, Le Queyras is an area sitting high up
in the departement des Hautes Alpes, near the Italian border. It includes
the old, picturesque and rather touristy village of Saint Veran, reputed, at
more than 2,000m, to be the highest village in Europe.
But the real attraction is the classic and wholly uncluttered alpine
landscape. Walks here look out on to some of the most spectacular mountain
scenery in France, with few of the crowds to be found in Chamonix, Mont
Blanc or other celebrated places.
You will eat less well and more expensively here than in the Aubrac, but
there are still many establishments offering good value. There are a number
of hotels on the route N-547 leading to the Belvedere de Cirque, a
magnificent place to gaze out on to an alpine giant, the 3,800m Mont Viso in
Italy.
Other good bets include: L'Hotel-Restaurant Les Veyres (tel: 92 45 01 91) on
the road from Guillestre to Ceillac, a pretty little village high on an
alpine plateau, and L'Hotel- Restaurant Le Chamois (tel: 92 45 83 71) in
Moline, on the road to Saint Veran.
Cantal. There is no rural countryside in France quite as peaceful as the
departement of Cantal. These are rolling hills full of old slate-roofed
villages, untold numbers of cows, and restaurants offering some of the most
interesting and ridiculously cheap regional cooking in the country.
There are many picturesque towns to stay in, including Saint Flour, Murat,
and Puy Mary. The most arresting, though, is the old medieval village of
Salers, a place of castles, battlements, old houses and winding streets.
L'Hotel des Remparts (tel: 71 40 70 33) in Salers offers both good food and
lodging. Further south, on the border between Cantal and Aveyron, the Lot
River Valley offers a splendid route eastwards to Cahors and on to the
Dordogne.
Haute Provence. This area offers an alternative to Provence proper. It is
higher, drier, and wilder - only goats, lavender and honey do well in this
harsh and arid climate. But it has many beautiful Provencal villages not yet
spoiled by crowds. From a base in the towns of Sault or Sederon, both with
good hotels, circuits might include Aurel, Montbrun-les-Bains, Aulan with
its Provencal chateau, Banon, reputed for its leaf-wrapped cheese, and the
very scenic Simiane-la-Rotonde.
Rene has no addresses for this area - it is too close to his own home and
his wife's unmatchable Provencal cooking. But I plan to explore it in detail
this summer and report later. Trout streams or no, I recently bought a house
in the hills on the edge of Haute Provence, and think it about as fine a
place as anyone could want to live.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
