<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Food &amp; Drink: A chef chooses chicken - Appetisers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS LANDER, JILL JAMES and GILES MACDONOGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Asked by an inquisitive nine-year-old to name his favourite food, Simon
Hopkinson, chef/partner at London's Bibendum restaurant, replied
immediately: 'Roast chicken'.
Perhaps a mundane choice for such a talented chef. But in his cookery book
Roast Chicken and Other Stories (Ebury Press, Pounds 17.99 230pp) Hopkinson
explains why he adores simple, tasty things and where he has enjoyed them.
Included are a refreshing, sour and salty parsley salad from Berowra Waters
restaurant in Australia; a milk chocolate malt ice cream recipe from San
Francisco; and a recipe for oeufs en cocotte from Lacy's restaurant which
was his first London culinary experience at the age of 18.
Each chapter deals with produce rather than seasons or menus, which allows
Hopkinson to voice his enthusiasm for such a wide range of foods as
aubergines, cod, potatoes and double cream. Lindsey Bareham intelligently
turns Hopkinson's restaurant quantities into easy-to-follow recipes for
four.
* * *
The Athenaeum Hotel and Apartments in Piccadilly, London is seeking malt
whisky - surprising since it stocks 56 varieties already.
James Brown, general manager, wants to carry every malt on the market and is
asking malt house proprietors to write to him directly. The hotel is
undergoing a Pounds 10m renovation and wants to restore the Malt Whisky Bar,
with its club atmosphere and leather armchairs, to its former glory. Tel:
071-499 3464.
* * *
The Gritti Palace Hotel in Venice is offering cookery courses for the 20th
year running. This summer's courses are Apulian cookery (July 18-22);
Milanese Cookery (July 25-29); and Cooking with Cheese (August 1-5).
The courses cost L600,000 (Pounds 250) per person, with five nights in a
double room at L1.025m per person (L1.5m for a single). For further
information contact Laura Fanecco 010 39 041 794611. Fax: 010 39 041
5200942.
* * *
After its successful release of a single cask of 20-year-old Isle of Jura
malt, Invergordon Distillers once again invited a panel of writers and
experts to choose the best old whisky from the Bruichladdich distillery on
the Isle of Islay.
The winner was distilled on November 22, 1972 and aged in a sherry butt,
making it unusually fruity for an Islay malt (Bruichladdich is also one of
the mildest whiskies made on the island). Its strength is 53.4 per cent. The
whisky is available from Invergordon Distillers in Leith. Tel: 031-554 4404.
Fax: 031-554 1531. Price Pounds 42 (inc post and packing).
* * *
For anyone heading to the west of England, there is the Trencherman's Guide
to the West Country listing 33 hotels and restaurants in Devon and Cornwall.
It is available free of charge from the West Country Tourist Board, 60 St
David's Hill, Exeter EX4 4SY, tel: 0392-76351, fax: 0392-420891.
Not in this guide but offering good value cooking is Le Petit Canard, Maiden
Newton, Dorset, tel: 0300-320536, dinner only.
* * *
In London's West End, under the Regent Palace Hotel, there is now open the
Atlantic Bar and Grill, 20 Glasshouse Street, 071-734 4888. Modelled on an
Atlantic liner of the 1920s it is open Monday-Saturday noon-3am and Sunday
11am-4pm.
