<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / How To Spend It: A princess who shops to survive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRENDA POLAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In certain female circles, shopping is a survival mechanism. And its
consequences, in terms of bulging wardrobes, tend to be limited only by how
tough it is to survive, and by resources.
This is not shopaholism. That is directionless, wasteful and leads to
penury. This is shopping therapy. Men do not understand it.
The Prince of Wales does not seem to. He is, according to reports apparently
based on his sieve-like friends, shocked and irritated to discover, thanks
to an audit on behalf of the Inland Revenue, that Princess Diana's 'grooming
bills' add up to Pounds 160,000 a year. It may amount to only one third of
what the Daily Mail last week calculated he spends on clothes, massages,
polo ponies, hunters, Georgian silver, watercolours and Trumpers Extract of
Lime toilet water, but it is a lot of money. It is around 200 times what
Di-look-alikes - the check-out girls, the factory workers and the office
drudges who are Diana's most adoring fans - earn in a long and tedious year.
Yet it is small beer compared to what is spent by many other women of the
international set. The glossy consort, the trophy on the arm demands a lot
of upkeep. In Britain, however, such an investment in appearance, in
clothes, haircuts, cosmetics and therapies, is contrary to the
make-do-and-mend mentality of most women raised in a puritanical tradition.
This is particularly true of the class from which Lady Diana Spencer comes.
Her erstwhile rival in love, Camilla Parker Bowles, is much more typical
with her bare face, bad haircut and crumpled clothes.
There are exceptions, of course, but they are rarely among the ranks of
non-working wives or ex-wives. They tend to be women who are earning their
own money and, if they have a husband, are in a position to lie to him about
what their clothes cost. Most well-groomed and partnered women halve the
true cost and then round it down. It is only kind to do so. British men
think frocks and blonde highlights should come at slave-labour prices. It
distresses them to find out they do not.
It is because most British dependent wives would heartily agree with their
spouses about prices, that Britain's fashion industry, particularly its few
couturiers, limps along for ever on the edge of disaster. For the big
spenders are foreigners. What a Gulf princess or the wife of an Italian or a
Japanese industrialist spends on 'grooming' makes the princess look
economical.
The princess was reported to be embarrassed and contrite and to have set in
train cost-cutting measures. Perhaps, given the political and economic
climate, she was wise, even valorous, to opt for discretion. But if ever a
woman was encouraged to become a spendthrift, it was Diana. She married into
a family which elevated dowdiness to an art form.
Diana's beauty and stylishness (something she had to work to cultivate) sent
the international media hysterical. They bayed for more. More Diana, more
frocks, more jewels, more smiles, more leg, more pictures. And because she
wore British clothes, the British fashion industry benefited. It egged her
on to become an ever more visible, ever more idolised super-mannequin.
Looking gorgeous was perceived as an important part of her function. She did
her best.
One may speculate whether her relentless pursuit of physical perfection
started as a strategy to win the stinted admiration of her husband. It may
have ended as a ploy to prove to him and to the rest of the world what he
had lost. But it has also become a habit, a way of life, and a comfort. She
opted out of work because she felt she needed space and now she finds that
space is empty. Many lonely women fill their days with shopping and beauty
treatments, but a woman does not have to be lonely to understand the value
to her psyche of shopping therapy. It is an affirmation of one's worth if
only in one's own eyes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
