<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / The Nature of Things: Fertility plights - Clive Cookson on
the alarming decline in average sperm counts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In an overpopulated world, a decline in male fertility may at first seem
like good news. But recent reports that the sperm counts of men today are
only half those of their counterparts 50 years ago are causing disquiet in
medical circles, particularly because the leading theory to explain the
decline involves pervasive chemical pollution of the environment.
There has even been bizarre speculation that mass infertility could lead to
the extinction of Homo sapiens by the end of the next century - a scenario
that PD James explored in her recent novel The Children of Men.
In reality, however, all that the latest scientific evidence has
demonstrated convincingly is how lamentably little we know about male
infertility in general and sperm production in particular.
The much-quoted estimate of a 50 per cent fall in sperm counts since 1940 is
based on a thorough analysis by Niels Skakkebaek of Copenhagen University of
studies carried out in 21 countries and involving 15,000 men. Although he
tried hard to correct for changing procedures and standards over the years,
retrospective studies of this sort are vulnerable to statistical attack -
and not everyone agrees that there has been a decline at all.
Another analysis of the data, to be published shortly in the British Medical
Journal, claims that the basis of the Skakkebaek paper was invalid. But a
large French study, accepted for publication in the New England Journal of
Medicine, will provide strong support for him.
In spite of the conflicting evidence, most experts believe that there has
been some decline in sperm production, though perhaps not as much as
Skakkebaek estimated. They suspect that it may be linked to the three-fold
increase in testicular cancer that has undoubtedly occurred in the
industrialised world since 1940. Other male reproductive disorders, such as
undescended testicles, have also become more common.
Our scientific ignorance is so great that no one knows what impact a 50 per
cent decline in average sperm counts would have on male fertility. On the
face of it, a normal man produces a vast excess of sperm: about 100m per
day. During sex he deposits between 100m and 800m (depending on when he last
had an orgasm) in the vagina, although only about 100 sperm reach the female
egg and of course just one fertilises it.
But sexual reproduction has evolved to require a huge number of surplus
sperm. By the standards of the rest of the animal kingdom, humans are
sub-fertile. Richard Sharpe of the Medical Research Council's Reproductive
Biology Unit in Edinburgh says that men produce sperm with only 10 to 30 per
cent of the efficiency of other mammals and, to make matters worse, about
half of human sperm are abnormal in some way, compared to 2 to 5 per cent in
other species.
In Britain infertility affects about one couple in six and the man's sperm
count is believed to be responsible in about a quarter of these cases. But
so little research has been carried out that estimates of male infertility
today vary by a factor of three - and no one knows to what extent, if at
all, the problem is worsening.
Many theories have been advanced over the years to explain declining sperm
counts. An old favourite is that modern men are overheating their testicles
by wearing too-tight underpants and trousers and/or by soaking too long in
hot baths.
Changing diet is frequently blamed too. The organic farming lobby jumped on
the bandwagon earlier this month when a small study in Denmark showed that
men eating only 'organic' food had sperm counts twice as high as the Danish
average. But other researchers said the sample of 30 men was too small to
give scientifically valid results.
However, the explanation receiving most attention at the moment is that
falling sperm counts and increasing reproductive abnormalities are related
to our growing exposure to 'environmental oestrogens'. These are persistent
man-made pollutants which mimic the biological effects of oestrogen, the
female sex hormone.
Natural oestrogen molecules work by fitting into a particular 'receptor'
site on human cells, like a key fitting a lock. For unknown reasons, nature
has not designed the oestrogen lock to tight tolerances and a range of other
molecular keys, including residues of the pesticide DDT and various
industrial chemicals, will also fit it and produce similar effects.
Until a couple of years ago, scientists had assumed that reproductive
problems stemmed mainly from events in childhood, puberty and adulthood. Now
Sharpe and his colleagues believe that the main impact of environmental
oestrogens takes place during the early development of the foetus, when
so-called Sertoli cells, precursors of sperm-producting cells in the
testicles, are formed.
According to the theory, a genetically male foetus exposed to even a little
extra female hormone will grow fewer Sertoli cells - and produce less sperm
in adulthood. If so, there is not much a subfertile man can do to boost his
sperm count by changing to an organic diet.
Evidence to support the environmental oestrogen theory is growing, from
studies of wildlife as well as humans. It may be a false alarm. Or we could
inadvertently be engineering not only a solution to overpopulation but a
barren future for man.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9431 Administration of Public Health Programs.
</IN>
