<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Skiing: Japan is no holiday
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARNIE WILSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Arnie Wilson and Lucy Dicker aim to ski every day of 1994 on a
round-the-world expedition, which has now reached Japan.
After almost a week of grey skies and two days of torrential rain, we have
seen little of Japan's sun - rising or otherwise, writes Arnie Wilson.
The only time we have managed to keep dry has been while skiing indoors.
Less than an hour from Tokyo there are two indoor slopes with artificial
snow, including the recently-completed Ski Dome at Funabashi, the largest in
the world, with runs a third of a mile long, served by two high-speed quad
chairlifts.
The exterior, resembling a huge grey lunar base, is equally impressive.
In nearby Tsudanuma, there is a smaller, older and friendlier version with a
more sedate escalator.
Japan is the only country where we have no transport of our own. Getting
around by Shinkansen (bullet train) and taxi (much slower, especially in the
rush hour) is exhausting and expensive.
Although we have dumped eight of our 14 bags - to be retrieved later - in
Wyoming, Colorado, Austria, France and even here in Japan, changing trains
and walking along Japan's long platforms with a double ski bag and five
other heavy bags is wearisome.
There are no trolleys and taxi drivers do not like trying to manoeuvre 207cm
skis in a ski bag, still dirty and dusty from Delhi, across their immaculate
upholstery.
So after a day's outing to a far-flung ski area, we do not hail a cab to
take us from Tokyo station to our hotel a quarter of a mile away. If it is
raining you cannot get a cab anyway. You just walk. And get drenched. Who
said this was one long holiday?
</TEXT>
<XX>
