<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Motoring: When looks count - Stuart Marshall road tests
BMW's new 7-Series
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STUART MARSHALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Apart from their V8 engines, the latest BMW 730i and 740i are completely new
cars. But they look so little different from the old ones that, at a glance,
only a BMW aficionado might notice.
Does this matter? BMW thinks not. It says people who buy cars in this price
class - and the new 7-Series will cost between Pounds 39,800 and Pounds
46,700 when they arrive in British dealerships next month - are not looking
for anything revolutionary.
According to a senior BMW executive when the new models were launched in
Germany last week: 'We have not designed these cars to do the competition in
the eye but to please our customers. We know they appreciate our kind of
timeless elegance. They like understatement and they certainly do not want a
heavy, Teutonic look.'
The new 7-Series takes over from the models launched in 1986. Then, they
were powered by a five-litre, V12 engine and in-line sixes of three and 3.5
litres, replaced two years ago by V8s of three and four litres.
Longer wheelbase 7-Series saloons, with enlarged 5.4-litre V12 or four-litre
V8 engines, are due to appear for the 1995 model year, priced at Pounds
65,900 and Pounds 52,900 respectively .
BMW knows the flagship 750iL will be chosen by a small minority because even
luxury car owners or users do not relish being suspected of consuming
excessive amounts of petrol. (For that matter, one is tempted to ask: who
needs a 5.4-litre V12 putting out well over 300 horsepower, anyway?)
In fact, by the standards of a few years ago, the new 7-Series V8s are
remarkably economical, with a combined cycle consumption of 25.7mpg (11
l/100 km). This is based on a car spending half its time in traffic with the
other half split equally between driving at constant speeds of 56mph (90kph)
and 75mph (120kph).
The 210 horsepower 740i I drove for a morning accelerated agreeably swiftly
through its five automatic gears and streaked along the autobahn like some
earthbound executive aircraft.
At close to its electronically governed maximum of 155mph (250kmh), I
thought it as quiet as any obvious rival such as the Mercedes-Benz S-Class,
Audi A8 and Lexus LS400.
Off the autobahn, it handled as nimbly as a smaller car. The ride, as one
would expect, is excellent.
Even on an uncharacteristically rough German minor road, the suspension
simply soaked up the potholes and bumps and tyre noise remained muted.
All the new 7-Series cars coming to Britain will have five-speed automatic
transmission. If anyone insists, the 730i can be supplied with a five-speed
manual gearbox and the 740i with a six-speed, although I cannot imagine any
British buyer being unwise enough to want one. BMW dealers are likely to
warn inquirers that manual versions would have a lower retained value than
automatics.
When I tried a five-speed manual 730i after the two-pedal 740i, it was quite
an anti-climax. Both clutch and gear-shift had a long throw and - most
unusually for BMW - smooth changes between first, second and third required
concentration. The manual three-litre accelerated less urgently than the
740i although it felt just as relaxed as an autobahn cruiser.
Inside, the new 730i and 740i have the wood veneer trim now obligatory for
posh cars, to go with leather seats, twin air-bags, 10-speaker sound system,
air-conditioning and computer. This produced a clear central display of
range, fuel consumption, temperature, time and so on. But while modern cars
such as the BMW 7-Series are wonderfully easy to drive, one really needs a
short course to learn how to work all their electronic wonders.
In the 1980s, luxury car sales grew in Europe by 90 per cent to around
240,000 units each year. The recession cooled things down considerably, but
forecasters say it will be up to 260,000 in a year or two. BMW expects its
new 7-Series to take a 20 per cent share.
</TEXT>
<XX>
