<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Lunch with the FT: A writer whose talent bloomed - Michael
Thompson-Noel meets Lisa St Aubin de Teran
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
She is small and exotic. Occasionally, her eyes survey a detail - the light
on the river, a waiter's passing smile - with an artist's calculation. You
wonder what she is seeing. Is she absorbing data, or just enjoying lunch?
This is Lisa St Aubin de Teran, whose novels and short stories have been
translated into a dozen languages, although her poetry has been translated
only into Italian and Norwegian. I ponder that awhile, wondering what a
master of literary impressionism like her - sensitive, evocative,
beautifully controlled - sounds like in Norwegian.
The task is beyond me, so I produce my cigarettes. She studies me
approvingly, and takes out her own pack. 'I am so relieved you smoke,' she
says. 'I was sort of wondering. In Italy' - where she lives - 'there is no
problem with smoking, but in other parts of the world this whole
anti-smoking thing is almost beyond control. I find it so
counter-productive, all this hectoring.' A waiter, watching her keenly,
replaces her ashtray even before she lights up.
'Why this restaurant?' I ask. (For Lunch with the FT, guests can choose any
restaurant they wish.) We are in Cantina del Ponte at Butlers Wharf, on the
bank of the Thames immediately to the east of London Bridge. As part of Sir
Terence Conran's South Bank gastrodome, it occupies what many would rate the
finest restaurant site in London. The food is good: more Pacific rim, claims
The Good Food Guide, than ethnic Italian, as though anyone minds.
Lisa St Aubin de Teran had started with a glass of champagne, then switched
to orange juice, and was eating voraciously - salmon, steak, pudding.
'I just like it,' she said, answering my question. 'I know this restaurant,
though I have only been here at night. I like the view. It's a little like
being in Sydney. I like the river and I like the City, but then I am
extremely fond of London. My favourite city for being in is probably Rome.
For eating in: Paris.'
She was born in Kensington, London, in 1953 and moved, shortly afterwards,
to Wimbledon. She was first married at 16. For seven years, she managed a
sugar plantation in the Venezuelan Andes. She is very widely travelled,
especially on trains, and has lived here, there and everywhere.
She started writing poetry when she was 12, short stories six years later.
Her first novel, Keepers of the House, won the 1983 Somerset Maugham Award
and her second novel, The Slow Train to Milan, the 1984 John Llewellyn Rhys
Memorial Prize.
Now, she lives in a valley in Umbria. In her latest book, A Valley in Italy,
she describes her struggle, since 1988, to rehabilitate the Villa Orsola in
which she and her family live: a Herculean task. The villa was a ruin: no
electricity, no water, no windows, no doors and a serious gap in the roof.
'You must be tough,' I said to her. 'Extremely tough. What possessed you to
take the villa on? How could you write anything with all that noise and
mess?'
'I suppose I am tough,' she replied. 'Buying the villa was partly an act of
real foolishness. I didn't see how derelict it was. People said it would
cost millions to restore. I could see that it wouldn't cost millions, but I
didn't realise how much it would cost - money I didn't have, the energy of
organising people. The effort that went into its restoration was probably
sufficient to run a small country, and it is by no means finished. Two sides
of the villa are all right, the third unfinished and the fourth - the back -
still spectacularly derelict.
'Fortunately, I click on and off as a writer. I spend a lot of time working
things out in my head, so that the time spent actually writing is hardly
more than auto-dictation. This gives me lots of spare time, for music and
opera, say. I love the way opera is much more part of everyday life in Italy
than elsewhere. A performance of Don Giovanni in Italy is a bit like a
football match. If they don't like the soprano, they crank up their football
rattles.
'In view of the money and energy that the palazzo consumed, I've felt a lot
less self-indulgent since starting my lily project.'
This lily project could make her famous in her part of Italy, if she isn't
already. (She speaks Italian fluently, and now understands Umbrian dialect.)
In her part of Umbria, poverty used to be endemic; it still casts a shadow.
Until 1945, the local men had to emigrate or work a six-day week as
labourers, charcoal burners or wood-cutters in the endless forests.
The land, says Lisa, excelled in no single crop, producing only inferior
versions of what neighbouring Tuscany grew. Then tobacco caught on,
providing, from 1953 onwards, a boom which by 1980 had provided every family
in her village, San Orsola, with its own house, a piece of land and at least
one car.
'In the high days, tobacco yielded a profit of Pounds 25,000 per hectare,
far more than maize, for example - Pounds 400 per hectare if the villagers
were lucky.' But tobacco-growing, which is pollutive, entails crippling
drudgery, and the EU subsidies were being slashed. A new crop was needed.
To her intense surprise, Lisa discovered that lilies grew easily in her
Umbrian garden. Perhaps they were the answer. She imported 500 bulbs from
the Netherlands which also, generously, offered technical assistance and
advice. The bulbs did as well as on a Dutch lily farm. Three years ago, she
imported another 8,000 bulbs, raising her stock to about 24,000.
'But I went to Brazil, to make a TV film of a rail journey. On my return, I
found that a herd of pigs had broken in and caused dreadful damage, though I
have probably still got 6,000 lilies flowering this summer.'
'Wild pigs?'
'The offspring of domestic sows and wild boars - the very worst. They are a
terror because they can get into anything. Real kamikazes - they will thrust
their young on to electrified fences, then storm in behind them.'
Despite that set-back, and the tangle of red tape that surrounds any
endeavour in Italy, Lisa is hopeful that lilies will bloom commercially in
her valley. 'People originally thought my scheme truly ridiculous. Now they
are keen.'
Some farmers are ready to try growing them, with her support, and the
rewards could be significant. Rome and its flower markets are two hours
away, Florence and Siena closer.
'You only need a small amount of land to grow lilies. No family would be
able to farm more than  1/2 -1 hectare of lilies and tulips, which also do
extremely well. The villagers could make more from my flowers than from
tobacco.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
