<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: High-powered transaction
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I have been using a high-powered Mercedes car in my small family business. I
intend to replace it with a more economical vehicle for business only. The
Mercedes has been written down for tax purposes to Pounds 3,000 but,
although eight years old, it is in excellent condition.
I propose selling it to my wife for that price, for her private use. When
she eventually sells, would she be liable for capital gains tax on any
profit?
No. It is exempt from CGT by virtue of section 263 of the Taxation of
Chargeable Gains Act 1992. This says: 'A mechanically propelled road vehicle
constructed or adapted for the carriage of passengers, except for a vehicle
of a type not commonly used as a private vehicle and unsuitable to be so
used, shall not be a chargeable asset; and, accordingly, no chargeable gain
or allowable loss shall accrue on its disposal.'
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
