FT  21 MAY 94 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Our daughter is bankrupt
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Three years ago, my husband and I made substantial interest-free loans to
our daughter to set up a small retailing business which has, unfortunately,
made an annual trading loss.
Do you think we would have any chance of claiming these losses against any
possible future gains?
If your daughter is effectively bankrupt, you and your husband can each make
a claim under section 253 of the Taxation of Chargeable Gains Act 1992 for
your respective irrecoverable loans. You must, of course, send your daughter
formal demands for immediate repayment of the loans in part, if not in full.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
