<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Finance and the Family: The need to be flexible - Your
pension / Retirement and after, last of three articles by Eric Short
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SHORT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Q. I am retiring this year and will be receiving a pension from my company's
scheme. Should I transfer into a personal pension, as has been suggested to
me?
A. For employees who are not high net worth executives, the answer is NO.
For the executives, though, transferring before retirement into a personal
pension offers interesting financial possibilities.
Q. What are they?
A. In a nutshell, flexibility of income, opportunities to continue investing
pension cash, and the facility to pass on pension assets to your children
should you die early.
Q. Can you explain more fully?
A. First, consider what happens when you retire from your company. You have
to take the benefits from the company scheme at the time you retire. You
have the options of a pension based on your salary at retirement and years
of service with the company, or a tax-free cash sum together with a reduced
pension.
You have no choice over deferring the payments or varying the amount of each
payment to suit your circumstances.
Q. What happens when I die?
A. Your spouse would continue to receive a pension at around half the amount
of your pension until he or she died, when the payments would cease.
Q. So, the value I get out from my company pension scheme depends on how
long I and my spouse live. If we both die soon after I have retired, we get
comparatively little from the scheme.
A. That is correct. But you must remember that a man retiring in good health
at the age of 65 can, on average, expect to live 14.5 years. And, of course,
the longer a person lives, the more valuable the benefits from the company
scheme.
In any case, since pension payments usually are guaranteed for five years,
your estate would not lose out entirely if you and your spouse died soon
after retirement.
Q. Can I leave the balance of my pension benefits to my children if I and my
spouse die soon after retirement?
A. You can take the tax-free cash sum on retirement, with a lower pension,
and that sum can be invested and left to your children. But the pension
payments die with you, other than those over the five-year guaranteed
period.
Q. How does this compare with transferring into a personal pension?
A. Your transfer value is divided into two parts - the protected rights and
the excess, with the excess being by far the greater value.
Both parts are put into in a personal pension with complete investment
freedom.
You can choose to invest in one or more funds from the range offered by the
life company - UK and overseas equities, fixed-interest, property and cash -
with opportunities to switch funds.
Q. What happens to the protected rights portion?
A. This represents contracting-out of the Serps (the state earnings-related
pension scheme).
When you reach state pension age - now 65 for men and 60 for women - you
must use the accumulated value to buy an annuity on a unisex, uni-status
basis increasing by 3 per cent a year.
If you are transferring at state pension age, you will be required to buy
the annuity immediately on transfer.
Q. What happens to the excess portion?
A. This is where the transfer offers the interesting financial possibilities
mentioned earlier.
With a personal pension, you can take the benefits, wholly or partially, at
any time between your 50th and 75th birthdays.
Up to 25 per cent of the value of the cashed-in benefits can be taken as
tax-free cash; the rest must be used to buy an annuity, with complete
freedom as to which one you choose.
This flexibility means that you can take the benefits from the personal
pension in bits. In other words, you can stagger or phase the cash-in of the
benefits until you reach your 75th birthday.
This process is known in the industry as staggered vesting or phased
annuities.
Q. How does one use this flexibility?
A. Each year, you decide how much income (after tax) you require for the
next 12 months. You assess your existing income from other sources - state
pension, protected rights pension and investment income. You then work out
what the shortfall is, and plug this gap by taking money out of your
personal pension fund.
Three-quarters of the money taken from the fund buys an annuity (which
provides lifetime income); the final quarter (which can be taken as a
tax-free lump sum) is actually earmarked for additional income for the
coming year.
The calculations need only be approximate.
Q. This cash-in process appears complicated. How does it work?
A. Suppose you are 65 and need to take around Pounds 10,000 net of tax from
the personal pension for the next 12 months.
The rate for the required annuity at age-65 is, say, Pounds 1,000 gross for
each Pounds 10,000 cash, and your tax rate is 25 per cent.
If you cash-in Pounds 32,600 of the personal pension, you can take Pounds
8,150 as tax-free cash. The balance of Pounds 24,450 buys a gross annuity of
Pounds 2,445 a year - or Pounds 1,834 after tax. So you have a net income
from the personal pension over the next 12 months of Pounds 8,150 plus
Pounds 1,834 - a total of Pounds 9,984.
The income from the annuity will be paid for the rest of your life. The rest
of your personal pension not cashed-in remains invested and continues to
grow in value.
Q. What happens next?
A. This process is repeated each successive year. Remember that each year
you buy an annuity which is added to your existing sources of income.
Annuity rates increase with your age, so your cash will buy a greater amount
of annuity each year, other things being equal (which they never are). Thus,
you might not need to cash-in so much of your personal pension
Q. What happens to the underlying personal pension fund?
A. During the first few years, the fund will diminish as you draw on it. The
rate at which it diminishes depends on how much you cash in each year.
But, as you build up your annuity, and as annuity rates increase, and if you
achieve a good return on the investments, then you could find the value of
your personal pension increasing until age-75.
Q. What happens at age-75?
A. You must use up the remaining value of the personal pension by taking the
tax-free cash sum and buying an annuity with the remainder. This final
tax-free sum should be regarded as capital rather than income; it will be
the last.
Q. What happens if I die before then?
A. The value in your personal pension is paid over as a cash sum - free of
tax if the personal pension is written in trust. This amount can be passed
to your children if desired.
Q. What about financial provision for my spouse?
A. He or she is provided for from the protected rights. You can buy
annuities with payments continuing to your spouse after your death. And/or
you can pass on the cash sum so that, if you die before 75, your spouse can
buy an annuity. You can tailor in the spouse's benefit to complement your
spouse's income. But, at 75, you should consider buying an annuity that
makes payments to your spouse after your death.
Q. This means, then, that if I transfer out of the company scheme, I can
manage my own affairs up to age-75 and do not lose the value of my pension
benefits if I die early?
A Yes, but it does depend very much on how much you take out of the personal
pension in the early years and the underlying investment performance. By
transferring, you are giving up certainty and security in return for
flexibility and the chance to obtain higher benefits. But you would be
vulnerable, particularly to a fall in investment values.
Q. I am interested in handling my own affairs. How should I proceed?
A. You must give yourself several weeks ahead of your retirement to make the
transfer, which must be completed before your retirement. The Inland Revenue
will not permit transfers to take place on or after retirement.
Most important, if you intend to proceed then you need professional advice
at all stages. The adviser must be prepared to cover all aspects  - income
assessment, investment management, as well as advising on the type of
annuity. In addition, you must be prepared to take time and trouble
assessing your requirements and understanding the adviser's recommendations.
As such, the adviser should operate on a fee basis for work done, not on
commission.
Q. Any final thoughts?
A. Above all, be wary of being offered a staggered vesting package that sets
out your income requirements over the next 10-15 years. It is essential that
you have complete flexibility of action.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
