<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Finance and the Family: Versatile and various - Where your
money goes . . . investment trust / Second in a series by Anthony Bailey on
the true costs of investing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY BAILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investment trusts are a versatile vehicle. They allow people access to a
diverse range of portfolios - from general funds investing across the world
to UK blue chips and higher-risk funds which specialise in a specific
country, region, type of market or type of company. In addition, the range
of shares in split capital trusts allows investors to select those which
fulfil a particular aim.
The actual costs of investing in these funds are not easy to compare with
similar unit trusts. This is because the price of investment trust shares is
determined by supply and demand in the market and not solely by the value of
the underlying investments they hold.
Dealing costs
Since investment trusts are companies listed on the stock exchange, the most
obvious cost for investors is that of buying and selling the shares. What
you pay will depend on which broker you use, his commission, the value of
shares you buy and, if you are investing only a small amount, the minimum
commission.
So, if you invest through a broker who charges 1.5 per cent, the cost of
buying rises to 2 per cent (once 0.5 per cent stamp duty is added) - more if
you invest a small amount and have to pay the minimum commission. A similar
1.5 per cent commission when you sell puts the total cost at 3.5 per cent of
what you invest, or Pounds 35 on an investment of Pounds 1,000.
These, along with the dealing spread (see below), are the figures to compare
with the bid/offer spread of 5, 6 or 7 per cent incurred when you invest in
unit trusts.
Cheap entry
The traditional broker is not the only way to buy investment trust shares. A
number of management companies run schemes which allow investors cheap
entry, either through regular monthly savings of at least Pounds 20 to
Pounds 50, or via single lump sum investments of around Pounds 250 to Pounds
500.
A few schemes make no dealing charge at all, while others have low dealing
commissions of 0.2 per cent and perhaps a flat rate sale charge of Pounds
10. Even those schemes that charge 1 per cent compare well with many
brokers, especially if there is no minimum charge.
The snag with some schemes is that they do not deal every day, or even every
week - so check. You also need to check just how cheap these schemes are. If
you go through a financial adviser rather than directly to the management
company, you might have to 'agree' to pay the adviser commission of up to 3
per cent.
The bid/offer spread
As with all shares, there is a difference between the higher offer price at
which you buy and the lower bid price at which you can sell. This spread
needs to be added to the buying and selling cost of shares to get a true
comparison with the bid/offer spread of unit trusts. With some large,
well-established general trusts, the spread can be narrow. It is 1.4 per
cent with F&amp;C's original general trust, but 3.1 per cent on F&amp;C Germany. On
City of Oxford's warrants, it is 27 per cent.
New investment trusts
There is no brokers' commission or stamp duty when you buy shares in a
newly-launched trust, but that does not mean investing is free. The
prospectus will have details of the launch costs, which could amount to 2 or
3 per cent or more.
The new Fleming Indian investment trust had a launch cost of 4 per cent, so
the starting net asset value of the investment was 96p a share. In practice,
though, measuring the effect of this cost is not straightforward because
what matters to investors is the actual value of the shares in the market
place, not the net asset value.
The management costs
As with unit trusts, the managers of investment trusts charge an annual fee.
In the case of Fleming Indian, the management company gets 1.2 per cent a
year. This sort of charge is roughly comparable with the annual charge
levied by unit trusts.
But as well as paying a fee to the management company, an investment trust
is a company in its own right with its own running costs. These must be
added to the management company's fee to reach a figure for the total cost
to investors - this being money which is not actually placed in stocks and
shares.
The best place to ascertain these costs is to look at the investment trust's
annual report and accounts. Some of the larger, older general trusts may
have overall costs of under 0.5 per cent, but others may be well over 1 per
cent.
One reason why investment trust costs can be lower than unit trusts is that
the former is a closed-end fund. It does not have to maintain a dealing desk
to respond to the constant demand from investors to buy and sell units.
The discount/premium
With a unit trust you are, essentially, paying for the costs of getting a
professionally managed portfolio. So, costs - the money not actually
invested - are an important factor (although, ultimately, it is the skill of
the investment managers and the return in your hands which counts).
Investment trusts are a bit different. One reason is that the price at which
investors buy and sell is determined by market forces and not by a formula
relating to the value of the actual assets held.
Not so long ago, discounts of 30 per cent were common. In other words, you
could buy assets worth 100p for 70p. While this sounds like a bargain, it is
not so wonderful if you have to sell the shares at a 30 per cent discount,
too (although you will have had the benefit of dividends on 100p worth of
assets in the meantime).
Discounts have narrowed, though, and the average discount now is nearer 8
per cent. Some shares are trading at a premium to the trust's net asset
value.
That is one reason why, on average, investment trusts have given investors
better returns than unit trusts. But a narrowing discount is a one-off bonus
 -and discounts may widen again.
Purists would argue that discounts and premiums are nothing to do with the
cost of investing; that they are part of assessing whether an investment
trust share is good value. It is a fair point. But private investors who may
be comparing the relative merits of investment and unit trusts with the same
investment remit do need to be aware of this crucial difference.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
