<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Finance and the Family: Fee rules change
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Investment costs are such a live subject that they are changing even while
this series of articles is being published. This week, the Securities and
Investments Board - watchdog for the industry - altered the rules on unit
trust fees.
Unit trust managers will now be allowed to deduct annual charges from the
capital of funds they manage, and will no longer be limited to taking it out
of the income stream from dividends. This is obviously particularly relevant
for income funds. Some fund managers, such as Schroders, are considering
taking advantage of the rule change. But preliminary discussions on how
yields should be publicised are likely. And industry regulator Lautro plans
to publish guidelines.
Next week, our series moves on to the costs of direct investment in the
stock market: brokers' charges, spreads, and why the size of a company can
alter the cost of buying and selling shares.
</TEXT>
