<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Finance and the Family: Only the best will do - Gillian
O'Connor looks at a trust-picker with teeth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN O'CONNOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investors in the US wanting to have their money managed by the legendary
Warren Buffett used to have two choices. First, they could try to get hold
of shares in Berkshire Hathaway, the company he runs. Or they could buy into
Sequoia, a fund with a similar approach and a hefty chunk of Berkshire
Hathaway shares in its portfolio. Sadly, Sequoia has been closed to new
investors.
British investors can play a similar game with unit trusts recommended by
Fund Research. London is teeming with stockbrokers' analysts researching
individual companies. But only Fund Research makes an equally serious bid to
pick the best of the 1,500-odd unit trusts on the market.
Run by former fund managers, the firm screens the funds exhaustively in
order to winnow out all but the minority which perform well on a consistent
basis. It does not use the normal one, three, five and 10 year performance
tables to select past 'winners'; instead, it looks at each fund over
discrete periods of a year within a longer time span. Only those which are
among the leaders qualify consistently for the second round.
Next, it goes through its short-list with a fine-toothed comb, looking for
such potential problems as excessively high turnover. Then, it grills the
fund managers.
The myth is that Fund Research interviewers always go in pairs, with a
different duo each time in order to minimise the chances of human
misjudgment. ('Not quite true,' says managing director Peter Jeffrey). But
if a fund manager leaves, the new one must endure further close questioning.
The qualitative judgment counts most in the final assessment. The research
is sold to investment managers for up to Pounds 8,750 a year.
As yet, no version of Fund Research's work is available to the UK public
although, in the US, comparable firms such as Morningstar and Value Line
sell their findings to the affluent private investor. But there are two ways
in which British private investors can hitch a ride on the bandwagon.
They can either buy units in a trust called Portfolio Fund of Funds, which
has produced very good results by following Fund Research's recommendations
closely; or they can buy the same unit trusts as Portfolio does.
Portfolio was started, and is managed, by the one of the men who started
Fund Research: Richard Timberlake, former managing director of Fidelity UK.
In the four years to the beginning of 1994, its units had risen by 82 per
cent compared with 61 per cent for the FT-SE-A All-Share index and 24 per
cent for the Morgan Stanley Capital International world index. And, in the
second half of 1993, the units rose by 29 per cent compared with 19 per cent
for the FT-SE-A All Share.
The managers point out that, over the same four-year period, their fund did
better than any of the other 20 funds of funds - that is, unit trusts which
invest in other trusts rather than directly in shares. The average return on
a Pounds 100 investment was Pounds 135 compared with Pounds 178 from
Portfolio.
Timberlake and his associates are notorious for driving a hard bargain on
charges with the managers of the funds in which they invest. The initial
charge on their fund is 5 per cent for investments up to Pounds 4,999, with
lower rates on larger sums. The annual charge is 1 per cent and the minimum
investment Pounds 1,000.
As yet, Portfolio Fund of Funds is a minnow, worth only Pounds 2.5m with
some 150 unit-holders. But the managers are planning to produce an emerging
markets fund run on the same principles.
