<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Finance and the Family: BA set to soar again - The week
ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
British Airways' tradition of near break-even fourth-quarter results has
seen analysts forecasting that full-year pre-tax profits will be about
Pounds 300m, against Pounds 185m, when they are revealed on Monday. But the
tone of the statement could be more important than the headline profit.
The stock has been weak since lower-than-expected growth in traffic figures
for April, and there are concerns about BA's troubled associate, USAir. The
dividend is expected to be in the region of 11p.
Thorn EMI, the music, rentals and electronics group, reports full-year
results on Tuesday, with pre-tax profits expected to be between Pounds 330m
and Pounds 340m, compared with Pounds 286.3m last time - although the 1992-3
figure is expected to be adjusted to take account of FRS 4. Pressure on
margins has caused analysts to lower slightly their profit forecasts for
BET, the business services group which reports annual results on Tuesday.
They now expect pre-tax profits of Pounds 90m, compared with the previous
loss of Pounds 9.8m.
John Clark, the chief executive, has completed his three-year programme of
restructuring and disposals after the group overstretched itself during the
1980s. Having eliminated Pounds 1bn of debt in the process, the City will
want to know where Clark thinks future growth lies.
Marks and Spencer is expected on Tuesday to extend its lead as the UK's most
profitable retailer, with an increase of more than 17 per cent in full-year
pre-tax figures from Pounds 736.5m to Pounds 865m. The tough conditions in
the grocery market and new depreciation policies are likely to be reflected
on Wednesday in a fall in full-year pre-tax profits at Argyll, the UK's
third-largest grocery retailer. The consensus forecast among analysts is
about Pounds 365m - down from Pounds 417m - after a new Pounds 40m
depreciation charge following the group's decision to start writing down its
superstores.
The extent of the recovery in commercial property values will be underlined
on Wednesday when Land Securities, the UK's largest quoted property company,
reports its final results. After three years of steeply falling net asset
values, the company's nav for the year to March is expected to rise from
Pounds 5.04 a share to a figure in the range of Pounds 6.30-Pounds 6.60.
Pre-tax profits are likely to remain static at around Pounds 233m.
Serious watchers of Carlton Communications, the broadcasting and television
services group, are plumping for pre-tax results between Pounds 65m and
Pounds 70m in the half-year, compared with Pounds 55m last time. Analysts
are forecasting pre-tax profits for UK telecommunications group Cable &amp;
Wireless in the region of Pounds 1.05bn, a 27 per cent increase on last year
(Pounds 824m). That would give earnings per share of 22.6p, a 16 per cent
increase on last year (19.4p). However, better-than-expected results
announced last Thursday at Hongkong Telecom, C&amp;W's largest business, might
make that view somewhat pessimistic. It reported turnover 12 per cent up at
HKDollars 24.3bn.
When Trafalgar House announces interim results on Thursday, analysts will be
expecting a marginal decline in its operating performance but no more
provisions. There is a range of pre-tax profit forecasts from Pounds 25m to
Pounds 38m, comparing favourably with last year's Pounds 97.6m loss.
</TEXT>
