<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Markets: The Fed tightens and sets the Dow loose - Wall
Street
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Like the unseasonably wet and blustery weather which struck New York this
week, Tuesday's aggressive tightening of monetary policy by the Federal
Reserve hit Wall Street like a spray of cool rain in the face, awakening the
groggy markets with a jolt.
Not that the Fed's move was unexpected. On Tuesday morning, when the central
bank's Federal Open Market Committee began its meeting, almost everyone was
convinced that the policy-making body would vote to approve another increase
in interest rates. Yet, even though Wall Street saw it coming, the 50 basis
point rise in the federal funds rate to 4.25 per cent and the 50 basis point
increase in the discount rate to 3.5 per cent sent a surge of energy through
the markets.
Minutes after the Fed announced the tightening, a previously becalmed Dow
Jones Industrial Average and 30-year government bond were roaring ahead on a
wave of buying. By the end of the day, the Dow was up 49 points, and the
long bond had climbed two full points, a gain that lowered the yield on the
benchmark government issue from 7.44 per cent to 7.26 per cent.
To anyone familiar with traditional market economics, this might have seemed
a curious reaction. The Fed raised rates for the fourth time in as many
months because it felt monetary policy had been overly accommodating for too
long. It believed that excessively low interest rates were threatening to
provide too much stimulation to the economy, and it was worried that unless
rates were raised to slow the pace of economic activity, inflation would
begin to revive later in the year.
In these circumstances, the stock market might have been expected to react
badly to another Fed tightening. Higher interest rates mean more costly
borrowing for companies and consumers, slower economic growth and lower
corporate profits, and they make other forms of investments more attractive
than equities, so stocks usually fall when interest rates go up. As for the
Treasury market, the Fed's evident concern about the outlook for inflation
would normally alarm investors in instruments that pay a fixed rate of
return such as government securities, so a decline in bond prices would have
been expected.
These, however, were not ordinary circumstances, for two main reasons.
First, traders and investors had already priced a monetary tightening into
stock and bond prices. This discounting meant that by Tuesday morning, when
the FOMC began its meeting, the markets were primed for a rate increase. In
particular, they were expecting an increase of half a percentage point in
both the fed funds and discount rates. Anything different - a smaller rate
increase or no increase at all - and uncertainty about Fed policy would have
returned to the markets. In the end, they got exactly what they expected, so
prices rallied.
Second, the aggressive nature of the Fed's move - 50 basis points on two key
interest rates instead of 25 basis points on just one - suggested to
investors that it might be the last tightening of monetary policy for some
time. This judgment was quickly proved accurate when the Fed, maintaining
its new policy of explaining its actions, issued a statement asserting that
the rate increases would 'substantially remove the degree of monetary
accommodation which prevailed throughout 1993'. In other words, the Fed was
saying it had finished tightening for now.
This was good news for financial markets, which warmed to the prospect of a
summer free from worries about another rate increase. Moreover, among more
forward-looking investors, there was plenty of support for the Fed's
actions. Inflation is low today because special factors in the US economy,
such as rising productivity and excess labour resources, are helping to hold
down prices. These disinflationary forces will not last forever, so it makes
sense for the Fed to slow the economy down, before it becomes too late to
douse the inflation fires.
So, where does all of this leave the stock market? Its impressive
performance this week - the Dow climbed almost 100 points in the first four
days of trading to 3,760 - suggests that the corrective phase of the market
cycle, which took the blue-chip average down 9.5 per cent from its February
high, is over. A floor of 3,600 has been established, and equities are
likely to enter a phase of consolidation, in which share prices rise
gradually as investors turn their attention back to economic and earnings
fundamentals.
This assumes that the correction has also ended in the bond market. But with
the 30-year bond yield declining from 7.6 per cent to 7.3 per cent in the
past 10 days, it is a relatively safe assumption.
