<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / The Lex Column: Lucas Industries
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Reports that substandard Lucas gearboxes have forced US Navy jets to make
scores of emergency landings look wide of the mark. Even so, the company's
embarrassment from the alleged use of non-conforming materials by its Lucas
Western subsidiary in Pentagon contracts is acute. The allegations follow
Lucas' admission earlier this week that AUL, another US subsidiary,
falsified test results on other kit supplied to the US military.
The direct financial damage from the affair - a fine expected to be Dollars
25m or so - is not huge. Moreover, it looks unlikely that Lucas Western will
be debarred from supplying the Navy. It is the Navy's sole supplier of
gearboxes and would be expensive to replace. In fact, the company started
providing the same equipment again only yesterday, following a suspension
which has lasted since July. Nevertheless, with a dented reputation, Lucas
could well find it harder to win future contracts from the US defence
forces.
The affair appears to reflect sloppy management at the US subsidiary and
inadequate control from the centre. Fortunately, the new management  - led
by Mr George Simpson, the highly regarded chief executive - is not tainted
by the failure to exert quality control. It has also acted swiftly to
replace management at Lucas Western and put in place a compliance regime
designed to satisfy the US that similar problems will not recur. The betting
must be that Lucas' current embarrassment will be only temporary.
</TEXT>
