<DATE>940521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Eurotunnel beset by concern
over financing
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Activity was muted with individual stories taking precedence as markets
anticipated Monday's holiday closure.
PARIS eased back with considerable attention being given to the 'Euro
stocks'. The CAC-40 index lost 9.92 to 2,155.43 in turnover of FFr4bn, off
1.5 per cent on the week.
Eurotunnel saw volume of some 5.5m shares in reaction to early reports that
it might have difficulty raising the cash it required from banks, with
consequent effects on its ability to launch a rights issue. The shares
touched a year's low of FFr31.60 before closing down FFr2.05 at FFr32.90.
After end of business the group said that it had secured Pounds 600m from
its banks and expected to close books on the debt next week.
EuroDisney moved in the opposite direction, up FFr33.70, as creditor banks
finally agreed the refinancing package.
ZURICH was helped higher by transactions linked to the expiry on index
futures and options. The SMI index rose 6.9 to 2,732 for a 1.9 per cent rise
on the week.
A study by Bank Vontobel concluded that small Swiss companies would
outperform their medium and large size counterparts over the period to the
year 2000. Mr Beat Philipp said that the study of 62 companies, representing
90 per cent of Swiss market capitalisation, pointed to 12 per cent average
annual earnings growth, with banks, mechanical engineers and light
electronics companies outperforming while insurers, building suppliers,
industrial holdings, the power industry and brewers underperformed.
UBS continued to make headway, adding SFr9 to SFr1,174, taking the rise over
the week to SFr60. However, analysts noted that the stock fell by 30 per
cent from its high for the year on February 4 to the low on May 9, as
switching was seen into German banks.
Roche certificates were steady at SFr6,635 after their bumpy ride earlier in
the week. Natwest Securities said that it had upgraded its forecasts for the
group as a result of the good first quarter results and the expectation that
the Syntex acquisition would enhance earnings from 1995.
FRANKFURT kept its attention directed towards the banking sector as
disappointment over Deutsche Bank results on Thursday continued to ripple
through the market. Activity was dampened by the fact the the market will be
closed on Monday.
The Dax index ended up 1.89 at 2,249.65, little changed on the week.
Turnover was DM7.2bn.
Deutsche Bank finished down a further DM2.70 at DM763.30, while Dresdner,
which reported yesterday that operating profits over the first four months
of the year had been 'satisfactory', went in the opposite direction, up DM3
at DM408.
Lufthansa, up DM4.50 to DM199.50, benefited from a positive note from Hoare
Govett yesterday. This said that with more cost savings to come and an
agreement with United Airlines of the US a significant improvement in
earnings could be expected.
MILAN remained under pressure for the second straight day as foreigners
continued to take profits and local investors showed a reluctance to make
fresh purchases. The Comit index lost 18.05 or 2.3 per cent to 776.45,
taking the fall over the week to 4 per cent.
Fiat was again under pressure after its recent strong performance, losing
L121 to L6,853, and Olivetti dipped L27 to L2,866.
Against the trend, Ciga, the hotels group, surged L64 or 5.5 per cent to
L1,228 in heavy volume of 22.9m shares, provoking renewed speculation about
stake building. A L29 advance to L2,889 in Pirelli was attributed to its
steeper than average falls in recent sessions.
AMSTERDAM slipped back on options expiry and the Aex index ended down 2.76
at 412.77, little changed on the week. Royal Dutch, which went ex dividend,
ended the session down Fl 5.60 at Fl 201.00.
Written and edited by John Pitt and Michael Morgan
