<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / London Stock Exchange: Currency and bond weakness upsets
equities - Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Another nervous and erratic session in UK equities yesterday saw share
prices quickly shedding early gains towards the close as weakness in the US
dollar unsettled sterling and impacted on British government bonds. By the
close, an early gain of nearly 17 points on the FT-SE Index had been cut to
only 4.5 for a final reading of 3,127.3.
The session had started well, with the Footsie moving up to 3,139.7 on the
back of Wall Street's strength overnight and the continued hopes that this
week's determined action on US interest rates by the Federal Reserve would
reinvigorate global bond markets.
Although sterling was unsettled by the announcement that domestic M4 money
supply had risen by Pounds 500m in April, stock markets made no initial
response. But London securities markets were quickly upset later in the
session when US markets began to turn off. By the close of trading in the
London market, the Dow Jones Industrial Average showed a fall of more than 7
points.
While there was no great selling pressure in London - Friday afternoons
often see cautious movements in share prices rather than activity by fund
managers - the weakness in bonds was received badly.
Market strategists, having at first given a favourable response to this
week's sharp rises in US Federal funds and discount rates, had become
increasingly unhappy with the easier trend in the US dollar which should, by
normal market criteria, have responded favourably to higher rates in the US.
The London market, in particular, has shown itself vulnerable to adverse
moves in the UK Treasury financing sectors, and there are now fears that
lower interest rates in Europe may not help UK stocks.
The FT-SE Mid 250 Index, having given ground for the past fortnight, against
the trend of the FT-SE 100 Index, made little progress yesterday, closing a
mere 1.1 ahead at 3,714.6. Seaq volume increased to 708.2m shares from
Thursday's 621.9m, which was worth Pounds 1.52bn in retail business.
By the close of trading last night, the FT-SE 100 Index was showing a gain
of only 8 points on the week, an unimpressive response to the
widely-predicted rate hikes from the Federal Reserve which had been seen as
a potential saviour for global bond markets and, therefore, for equities. UK
share prices have found it difficult to follow Wall Street higher because
dollar weakness has undermined optimism in the bond market.
Once again, share prices found difficulty in establishing a firm trend
yesterday and by the close the picture was more irregular than the Footsie
Index suggested. Pharmaceuticals and banks closed easier and the blue chip
sectors were boosted by gains in a handful of special situations including
BT and British Gas, both still responding to trading statements on the
previous day.
However, store and retail stocks continued to respond well to the view of
the independent Treasury advisers on Thursday that there was no need for
domestic interest rates to rise at present.
Profit-taking in the engineering and motor industry sectors suggested that
this week's gains had been insecurely based and may have reflected little
more than bargain hunting by small investors rather than investment
decisions by the managers of the big pension funds.
</TEXT>
