<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / International Company News: France reiterates resolve to
sell Renault
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The French government yesterday stressed its commitment to the privatisation
of Renault, the state-owned automotive group, but played down reports it was
considering a partial sell-off this year.
'We are studying the Renault dossier with respect to privatisation,' said an
industry ministry official. 'But we have not taken any decisions on how the
sale is to be implemented.'
Speculation on the idea of a partial privatisation this year, with a full
privatisation in 1995, was triggered by a report in the Tribune Desfosses,
the French business daily.
According to the report, the government is considering the sale of between
15 and 25 per cent of Renault's shares as early as this autumn, and could
combine the sale with a capital increase for the automotive group.
The sale could take part in two tranches: one for individual investors
through a public offer for sale, and the second for institutional investors
and industrial partners.
Industry observers said there were several advantages in such a scenario.
For one, it would confirm the government's intention to privatise Renault,
following its omission from the latest list of public companies slated for
sale. The list, announced in March, included Assurances Generales de France
and Groupe Bull, the computer manufacturer.
A flotation of part of the French government's 80 per cent stake in Renault
would also facilitate the reduction of Volvo's 20 per cent holding in the
company. The Swedish group has retained the stake since the collapse of its
planned merger with Renault at the end of last year.
A partial privatisation would allow the formation of a 'noyau dur', a group
of long-term stable shareholders. Lagardere Group, which co-operates with
Renault on the production of the Espace vehicle, and Elf-Aquitaine, the oil
group, are potential long-term investors.
</TEXT>
