<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / International Company News: Paramount costs leave Viacom
Dollars 454m in red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
An after-tax charge of Dollars 332m to cover costs involved in the takeover
of Paramount Communications has left Viacom, the US entertainment group,
with a total net loss of Dollars 454m, or Dollars 3.59 a share, for the
first quarter.
The charge stems from the merger of some of its businesses with those of
Paramount, as well as 'related management and strategic changes', Viacom
said.
Some Dollars 224m of the charge was taken in the entertainment division,
which has been created by bringing together Paramount's movie and television
operations and Viacom's production businesses.
The company said it had adjusted the value of some of its programming
assets, 'based upon new management strategies and additional programming
sources'.
Without the charge, Viacom's net loss for the period would have amounted to
94 cents a share, slightly more than most analysts' expectations.
The first-quarter figures include just one month of Paramount's results. If
Paramount's results for the full period had been included, the net loss
would have been Dollars 332.9m, or Dollars 1.67 a share, before the one-off
merger charge, Viacom said.
The results reflect a poor performance from Paramount's movie division, with
revenues from the company's feature films below expectations. The inclusion
of one month of Paramount figures contributed an operating loss of Dollars
51m, Dollars 35m of it in entertainment and Dollars 15m from publishing.
Viacom's pre-merger businesses, by contrast, reported operating earnings of
Dollars 83m for the quarter, Dollars 66m of it from the MTV and Showtime
networks. MTV continued its growth of recent quarters, with revenues up 30
per cent from a year ago, at Dollars 174m, and operating earnings up 21 per
cent to Dollars 55m.
Commenting on the results, Mr Frank Biondi, president and chief executive,
said: 'The main structural issues and associated costs are clearly behind us
and we are poised for excellent performance and growth.'
The sale of the company's one-third interest in Lifetime Television, for a
pre-tax profit of Dollars 267m, will appear in the current quarter's
figures.
Viacom has already announced it is exploring the sale of other assets in a
move that would reduce the debts taken on with the acquisition of Paramount.
</TEXT>
