<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / International Company News: Dresdner sees no need for
provision against Schneider
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Dresdner Bank has no need to make any provisions against its loans to the
collapsed Jurgen Schneider property group, chairman Mr Jurgen Sarrazin told
shareholders yesterday.
The bank's main involvement was in the financing of two of the group's
projects. Dresdner's loans, concentrated on two properties in Berlin and
Leipzig, were secured against the value of the projects.
Addressing the annual meeting a day after Deutsche Bank announced provisions
of DM500m (Dollars 303m) against its exposure to Schneider, Mr Sarrazin said
both projects would be completed to increase their value.
The bank had taken over responsibility for the sites and paid contractors
and other suppliers for work done. Meanwhile, Dresdner was negotiating over
the conditions under which the projects could be passed into 'other hands'.
After allowing for risk provisions, the bank's operating profits showed
'pleasing' growth in the first four months of this year, Mr Sarrazin said.
Deutsche earlier reported a 10 per cent decline over the same period.
Offering no more details, he said he expected a satisfactory result for the
full year, although it was too early to make forecasts. This was partly
because of uncertainties over the need for provisions against bad debts.
Commenting on progress so far, Mr Sarrazin said although own-account trading
results were markedly down, he expected market activity and prices to
improve during the the year.
On the other hand, risk provisioning had been reduced and interest and fee
income had both increased.
</TEXT>
