<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / International Company News: CRA retains 10% stake in
Pasminco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CRA, the Australian minerals group, said yesterday it was retaining a 10 per
cent shareholding in Pasminco, the Melbourne-based zinc and metals
processing company. It has also undertaken not to dispose of the stake for
at least 12 months, except to a trade buyer or buyers.
The company confirmed it had succeeded in placing the remainder of its large
minority stake in Pasminco.
CRA directors said the company had sold almost 309.2m Pasminco shares,
representing almost 39 per cent of its capital, to a large number of
domestic and overseas buyers through Potter Warburg and Bain Capital
Markets, two stockbroking firms.
The shares, placed at ADollars 1.70 each, raised more than ADollars 525m
(USDollars 383.2m), making the placement one of the largest involving an
Australian company.
The sale included a stake of 19.1 per cent in Pasminco which CRA controlled
through an option agreement with North Broken Hill Peko, another Australian
mining group.
CRA had said it was planning to shed its Pasminco holding earlier this year,
suggesting it would use the funds raised to develop the New Century mine in
Queensland.
At that stage, CRA gave no firm indication of how the stake would be
disposed of, but said it was willing to consider offers for all or part of
the holding.
Yesterday, Mr Peter Barnett, Pasminco's managing director, said he was
pleased that uncertainty over the company's ownership had been promptly
resolved. He believed the wider spread of ownership would lead to
maintenance of its current credit rating.
