<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / International Company News: Veag to invest DM20bn ahead of
sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Veag, eastern Germany's largest utility, will invest more than DM20bn
(Dollars 12.1bn) in modernising and upgrading the region's electricity
infrastructure, Mr Karlheinz Steiner, a board member, said yesterday.
Much of the planned investment programme will involve building brown
coal-fired power stations and installing emission-reducing equipment. Over
11,450 MegaWatts of Vega's total 14,225MW, are generated by brown coal.
The company, which is still under the Treuhand privatisation agency,
increased turnover last year by 2.4 per cent, to DM6.5bn compared with the
previous year, despite the continuing fall in energy consumption throughout
eastern Germany.
However, profits last year were reduced to zero from DM7m in 1992 because of
heavy restructuring costs, including redundancy payments, high investment
commitments, and the transfer of DM4bn in liquid assets to the Treuhand.
Primary energy consumption in the region had been traditionally dominated by
brown coal: it held 68 per cent share of the energy market. However, with
the collapse of manufacturing, primary energy consumption fell from 128.3m
tonnes in 1989 to 83m tonnes in 1991.
Mr Steiner said the company would have to tap capital markets to finance its
investment programme, a move supported by the advisory board, which approved
borrowings of up to DM2.3bn for 1994. The workforce has been cut from 29,000
in 1990 to 13,513 last year, and a further 2,000 jobs are expected to be
lost this year.
Mr Steiner said the company, which has a monopoly in the generation and
distribution of electricity throughout eastern Germany, would be finally
privatised 'around the middle of the year'. It will be sold for an estimated
DM8bn to West Germany's largest utilities, headed by RWE, PreussenElektra
and Bayernwerk.
However, the successful privatisation of Veag remains dependent on the
Treuhand completing the sale of Laubag, the large brown coalfields which
will feed the Veag electricity grid. Laubag will be sold to a consortium led
by Rheinbraun, the coal subsidiary of RWE.
</TEXT>
