<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / UK Company News: W'hampton &amp; Dudley edges ahead to Pounds
17.2m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wolverhampton &amp; Dudley Breweries yesterday reported slightly higher
first-half profits, helped by a 4.8 per cent increase in turnover and a
modest improvement in trading margins.
Pre-tax profits, including a Pounds 12,000 contribution from property
disposals, increased by 3.4 per cent to Pounds 17.2m in the 26 weeks to
April 3.
The comparable figure of Pounds 16.7m included property disposals profits of
Pounds 677,000.
Earnings per share slipped to 17.5p (17.7p) mainly reflecting an increased
tax charge of Pounds 5.6m (Pounds 5.03m). The interim dividend is lifted
from 4.7p to 5.1p. The shares closed 11p higher at 554p.
Turnover increased to Pounds 112.4m (Pounds 107.3m) although total barrelage
slipped by 1.7 per cent mainly because of the run-off of low margin brewing
contracts which came with the Camerons brewery acquisition in late 1991.
Mr David Thompson, managing director, said turnover benefited from a strong
performance by restaurants and managed houses. Covers in the Milestone
Restaurants rose by 3.4 per cent on a like-for-like basis and by 27.6 per
cent in the group's Taverns.
Trading profits increased by 6.3 per cent to Pounds 19.7m (Pounds 18.5m)
highlighting a solid performance by the group's brands, which include
Banks's Mild and Camerons Scotch.
Mr David Miller, chairman, noted that in the north-east good news about the
economy has been rare and the group's customers have not felt any
improvement in their circumstances.
Instead, he suggested 'improvements to trading have been driven more by
uplifts to pubs, acquisition and market share gains in free trade'.
Trading margins improved from 17.3 per cent to 17.5 per cent, mainly due to
improved productivity, higher income from games machines, which grew by 11.4
per cent, but partly offset by higher pub repair costs which rose by 12.7
per cent.
COMMENT
Wolverhampton and Dudley's management is refreshingly honest about the state
of the beer market and the pressures on industry margins. Nevertheless,
these are solid results and a good base to build on. Comparisons in this 52
week year - last year covered 53 weeks - will be made more difficult by the
higher tax charge which is likely to rise from 30.4 per cent to 32.5 per
cent, and by lower property profits. However, pre-tax profits should reach
Pounds 37m for earnings of 37.2p. The shares are trading on a prospective
p/e of 14.9 and look a reasonable buy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Wolverhampton and Dudley Breweries.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
