</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Fleming Indian Investment Trust, the first London-listed trust to
specialise in India, has raised Pounds 84m from a placing and public offer -
short of its original Pounds 100m target.
Mr Patrick Gifford, chairman of Fleming Investment Trust Management, said he
was delighted by the response to the fund against a background of difficult
stock market conditions.
The public offer brought in Pounds 26.4m, of which Pounds 3.4m was an
application on behalf of Robert Fleming Investment Trust. An initial placing
raised Pounds 54.6m, with an additional 2.94m shares taken up as a
consequence of the level of applications in the public offer.
The proportion of the total which came from private investors - either
directly or via intermediaries - was comparatively large for a trust of this
highly-specialised, risky nature.
Shares are being issued at 100p with warrants attached on a 1-for-5 basis.
Separate dealings in the shares and warrants are due to start on May 26.
