<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Little joy in a good news week: Perils may lurk beneath
optimistic forecasts for steady economic growth in the UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This month's UK economic statistics have confounded the Cassandras. Although
yesterday brought news of a fall in bank lending in April, the overall
picture is of an economy that is growing well, with low inflation in spite
of last month's tax increases.
The past fortnight has brought news of rising first-quarter industrial
output, record retail sales last month, a fall of 260,000 in unemployment
over the past year and the lowest rate of underlying retail price inflation
for a generation. Both Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie
George, the governor of the Bank of England, have held out the prospect of
an extended period of steady growth.
'The opportunity that we have now,' said Mr George, 'is to continue the
expansion at or perhaps a bit above its recent rate, bringing a continuing
gradual fall in unemployment, with continuing low inflation, for several
years ahead.'
However, Mr George made clear that 'this won't come about automatically or
of its own accord'. Rosy though Britain's outlook seems, there are some
worries.
In spite of the welter of official figures over the past two weeks and the
plethora of comment that these have generated, Britain is still largely
shrouded in statistical fog. The data that policymakers and markets have
been given on trade, manufacturing output and retail sales are, to varying
degrees, unreliable.
A big question mark continues to hang over Britain's trade figures even
though the Central Statistical Office and the Customs and Excise last week
unveiled the results of a far-reaching review and quality audit of the new
system used to collect trade data in the European Union, known as Intrastat.
The CSO's analysis resulted in only a small upwards revision of last year's
visible trade deficit to Pounds 13.7bn from Pounds 13.4bn previously. But it
has failed to convince many UK economists. The Treasury's independent
forecasters, the so-called six 'wise men', said this week that they 'remain
concerned about the reliability of the trade figures'. Some panel members
still found the figures 'implausible' and suggested that the annual trade
deficit could be understated by Pounds 3bn.
Distorted figures for trade and export prices have potentially serious
implications for our understanding of domestic UK economic activity. Because
industrial production figures are largely computed by adjusting output or
sales data to take account of price increases, any error in the way
Britain's export prices have been measured could have a big effect on the
figures for manufacturing output and economic growth.
Mr Gavyn Davies, chief economist of Goldman Sachs International and a member
of the Treasury panel, believes official statistics could have overestimated
the rise in UK export prices by about 4 to 6 per cent. In that case
manufacturing output could have been underestimated by about 1.5 to 2 per
cent and real economic growth in 1993 by about 0.5 per cent.
In his contribution to the recent discussions of the 'wise men', Mr Davies
observed that UK gross domestic product, instead of growing at an annual
rate of 2.5 to 3 per cent in recent quarters, 'might be revised to show
growth of 3 to 3.5 per cent'.
Such uncertainties make it extremely difficult to forecast the economy and
to assess how much slack remains following the recession. Doubts about the
amount of spare capacity in turn add to the difficulties of assessing how
far the UK is threatened by a rebirth of inflation.
Even the shortest of short-term forecasts of inflation can go wrong. Twelve
days ago, the Bank of England published a projection that the April's annual
rate of underlying inflation, excluding mortgage interest payments, would
move above 2.5 per cent towards 3 per cent. As figures this week showed, it
fell to 2.3 per cent in April from 2.4 per cent in March.
The current low level of retail price inflation is good news. But it
reflects past events and gives no guarantee of future price stability.
It is concern about future inflation that has prompted the Bank of England,
the Treasury and the Department of Employment to sound the alarm about
rising wages. Wednesday's news of a 4 per cent underlying increase in UK
average earnings in the year to March was well above market expectations of
a 3.5 per cent rise. Even though the jump largely reflected higher bonus and
overtime payments, the general level of wage settlements is also moving
upwards.
Rising pay may be starting to chip away at Britain's international
competitiveness. According to Mr Robbie Gilbert, the Confederation of
British Industry's director of employment affairs: 'Earnings are feeding
through into unit labour costs, which are also moving upwards, while those
of Germany and the US are moving down.'
The rise in incomes, together with falling mortgage rates and a run-down of
savings, helps explain the continued strength of consumer demand. The
recovery of the past two years has been remarkable for having been sustained
entirely by growth in consumption. Trade, even allowing for deficient
statistics, is thought to have made a negative contribution to UK economic
growth last year. On balance, the Treasury's panel of wise men expects that
trade will continue to make a small negative contribution to GDP this year
and next, as imports grow slightly faster than exports in volume terms.
There has been little sign so far of an upturn in investment.
However, the trend in investments may be about to turn. The Bank of England
has pointed out that the UK corporate sector came through the last recession
with greater profitability than in the previous two recessions. Although a
minority of companies continues to be burdened by excessive debts, the
overall financial position of UK companies is strong. The Treasury panel
generally expects investment growth of about 5 per cent this year and a
further rise of about 6.5 per cent in 1995.
A revival of investment cannot come too soon if the recovery is to gain in
breadth and strength. There are signs, however, that the reluctance of
companies to spend on plant, machinery and buildings may be part of a bigger
problem of adjusting to the changed economic conditions of the 1990s.
Recent surveys conducted by the CBI and Bank of England indicate that
worries about inadequate rates of return are curbing capital spending. The
Bank has suggested that, after 20 years in which inflation has averaged
nearly 10 per cent, companies have not yet adjusted their horizons to
Britain's new low inflation environment.
Similar adjustment problems affect the population at large. In his speech to
the CBI this week, Mr Clarke lamented that 'the public appear still to
believe we are in a recession' two years into recovery. 'Too many people
still hanker after the go-go growth in living standards they enjoyed in the
years of boom,' he said.
Such news is especially bad for Mr Clarke. While the chancellor underlined
this week that he and Mr George 'share the same aim of low inflation and
sound money', he is acutely aware of the absence of a 'feel-good factor' in
the current recovery when his party is being hammered in the opinion polls
and faces defeat in the European elections.
The divergence of interests between Mr Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr
Clarke, the politician, may explain the nuanced differences with Mr George
on whether to lower interest rates. These emerged when the minutes of their
meeting at the end of March were published this week.
But if Mr Clarke is serious in saying that he 'does not want a boom because
boom gets followed by bust', he may have to get used to a joyless recovery.
And if growth turns out to be faster than recent statistics suggest, he
could be discussing an increase rather than a reduction in interest rates
with Mr George before the year's end.
</TEXT>
