<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: No nasty surprises on exercise of
warrants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ERNEST FENTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Serious Money: 'Robbing Peter to pay Peter' (14 May), discussed points
raised in the latest Credit Lyonnais Laing Investment Trust yearbook. You
added, however, your own point at the end on warrants.
We feel it is important to clarify a recent, and unfortunately misinformed,
view which seems to have arisen concerning warrants; namely that upon
exercise of warrants the net asset value experiences an unforeseen fall,
potentially catching investors unawares.
Investment trust companies which have issued warrants publish two net asset
values; one on an 'undiluted' basis, ie, a valuation of the existing
portfolio, and the other on a 'diluted' basis, ie, a valuation of the
portfolio assuming all warrants in issue have been exercised (increasing the
assets and number of shares).
It is standard practice in the investment trust industry to use the diluted
NAV for valuing the company if warrants are 'in the money and dilution would
occur', ie, if the undiluted NAV is higher than the exercise price of the
warrants, making it likely that warrant holders may exercise. The AITC
follows this practice in monthly information service as does the Financial
Times in its London share service. Discounts published are based on the
lower, diluted NAV.
As a result, investors are not subject to a nasty surprise when the final
exercise of warrants takes place. This is because the lower NAV has been
used when applicable throughout the life of the warrant and discounts
published have reflected this.
The investment trust industry appreciates the importance of ensuring
investors have accurate and meaningful figures on which to base decisions.
The AITC has been careful to ensure best practice in use and publication of
diluted and undiluted NAVs when valuing investment trusts.
Ernest Fenton,
Association of Investment Trust Companies.
16 Finsbury Circus,
London EC2M 7JJ
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
