<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: A non-enterprising legacy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DAN STRANESCU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, It is ironic some western companies are experiencing difficulties as
investors in Romania, for reasons to which they have themselves contributed
during Ceaucescu's years of forced industrial expansion ('Shoddy meets
quality in Transylvania', May 18).
Romania's swollen industries have absorbed for more than a generation large
numbers of impoverished farm workers with few relevant skills.
However low the resulting productivity, the dismally low pay helped achieve
international competitiveness in selected areas, including those which have
benefited Ikea as buyers of furniture 'for more than two decades'.
By the 'western standards' to which Mr Gunnerling (the specialist in turning
around failing companies) refers, Magura Codlea factory was as bankrupt then
as it is now. As such it is a good investment, particularly when the
Romanian furniture industry has adapted well to change over the past three
years and expanded its export markets.
What Ikea must address, however, beyond providing efficient production
facilities, is the cultural bias against true enterprise, an enduring legacy
of the Ceaucescu regime.
Dan Stranescu,
6/38 Arundel Gardens,
London W11 2LB
</TEXT>
<XX>
