<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Chance to turn the political tide: The battle for Germany's
presidency is a test of the coalition government's electoral strength
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chances are that by Monday evening the rather splendidly named Mr Roman
Herzog (his name means Roman Duke in English) will have been elected the
next federal president of Germany.
The bluff Bavarian judge who heads Germany's constitutional court is not the
most popular choice. That would have been Mr Johannes Rau, the former leader
of the opposition Social Democratic party (SPD), and prime minister of the
state of North Rhine-Westphalia since 1978.
Nor is the election all over bar the shouting. The complex arithmetic in the
cumbersome electoral college known as the federal assembly still has
political analysts scribbling alternative scenarios on the backs of their
envelopes.
But the political probabilities are that Mr Herzog will win through in the
third round of voting, where he requires a simple majority, to provide
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and his Christian Democratic Union with a much-needed
psychological boost in a marathon election year.
That is in spite of the fact that he is his own party's second choice of
candidate. Mr Kohl's first runner, the east German, Mr Steffen Heitmann, was
unceremoniously ditched when he proved to be altogether too gauche,
inexperienced and conservative to enjoy any cross-party backing.
It was inevitable that the outcome of the presidential vote would be decided
on the basis of party politics, once it was clear that it would fall in the
middle of no fewer than 18 other federal, state, local and European
elections.
In spite of the fact that the federal president's job is largely powerless
and ceremonial, it is highly symbolic and very visible. Above all at such a
crucial moment in the post-war history of the federal republic, when the
country is struggling with the unique task and expense of reunifying the
former communist east with the capitalist west, it bears a special
responsibility.
President Richard von Weizsacker, the incumbent, has used the post with
considerable success to promote a greater sense of national unity, at a time
of resentment on both sides of the national divide at the cost and pain of
the process. He has also worked tirelessly to reinforce Germany's
international image as a force for reconciliation and stability, and counter
any fears of the revival of an overbearing German national state at the
heart of Europe.
When a rash of racist attacks on asylum-seekers and foreign workers in
Germany threatened to dent that international image, Mr von Weizsacker was
among the first to speak out in condemnation, and urge practical action to
promote better race relations. In attending the funerals of the victims, and
visiting the bereaved, he demonstrated a considerably clearer political
instinct than most party politicians, including Chancellor Kohl himself.
His personal relations with the chancellor have become increasingly frosty,
both because of his publicly stated criticism of the whole party system, and
because of his tendency to preach from a high moral platform. Few close
observers doubt that his personal views are more national-conservative than
those of the passionately pro-European German chancellor.
Yet few would contest that Mr von Weizsacker's 10 years in office have
enhanced both the presidency, and Germany's national image. Everyone agrees
it would have been better not to have a party contest for the succession.
But nobody really knows how it could have been done.
In the event, the polling on Monday in the old Reichstag building in Berlin,
still awaiting refurbishment as the future home of the German parliament,
will be acutely political.
Ironically, the outcome hinges on the voting split not between the two main
parties of right and left - Mr Kohl's CDU and the opposition SPD - but on
the split within the minority Free Democratic party (FDP), the junior
partner in the Bonn coalition, eternal kingmaker of postwar politics, and
currently suffering a disastrous slump in prestige and popularity.
There are 1,324 members in the federal assembly - 662 from the Bundestag,
the directly elected lower house of parliament, and the same number from the
16 state parliaments. The vote is supposed to be secret, but the delegates
reflect the political composition of their respective institutions. That
gives Mr Kohl's CDU and its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social
Union (CSU), 619 members in the assembly, the SPD 502, and the FDP 111.
After them come the Greens, with 44, the Democratic Socialists (the former
east German communists) with 33, and others, including the far-right
Republicans, with 15.
Apart from Messrs Herzog and Rau, there are two other candidates: Mrs
Hildegard Hamm-Brucher, a grand old lady representing the true liberal wing
of the FDP, who was put up by the party when it still looked as if Mr
Heitmann might run; and Mr Jens Reich, the only easterner standing, a
thoroughly independent-minded academic and former hero of the civic
revolution which overthrew the communist dictatorship there. Neither is
likely to dent the big parties' dominance, and the question is only when
they will withdraw from the race.
That would leave Mr Rau picking up pretty well united support from the left
 -still short of an overall majority - and Mr Herzog in the same position on
the right. The balance would lie in the hands of the fractious FDP.
The liberals are divided between Mr Klaus Kinkel, its leader and foreign
minister, who is inclined to back Mr Herzog, and thus the current coalition,
and Mr Jurgen Mollemann, the former economics minister and would-be party
leader, who supports Mr Rau and a future coalition with the SPD. How they
split depends on how they read the political tea leaves in this election
year.
Mr Robert Leicht, editor-in-chief of the respected weekly newspaper Die
Zeit, traditionally SPD-inclined, argues that the FDP can only be truly
liberal by supporting Mr Rau. A vote for Mr Herzog, he says, would be a vote
to hang on to power in the present exhausted coalition at all costs.
Mr Rau has long been seen as an obvious candidate for the presidency, and as
one who could enjoy broad cross-party support. After the refusal of Mr
Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the former FDP leader, to run for the office, it
appeared there could be a broad coalition behind him. But the SPD played its
cards too soon: by putting him up as the party candidate early in the race,
it embarrassed Mr Kohl into looking for his own alternative. Once he had
embarked on that exercise, there was no going back to a cross-party
compromise.
It must be said that Mr Rau is not everybody's cup of tea. He is himself
rather inclined to preach, a la Weizsacker, from his moral position as a
pious northern protestant. His health is also uncertain, since he had a
kidney operation in 1992. And given his former position as SPD party leader,
he is actually the most party political of all the candidates.
Mr Herzog, on the other hand, is very much a southerner in style and
temperament: in spite of his position as the ultimate arbiter of the
country's constitution, he is a humorous and often self-deprecating speaker,
a quality all too rare on the German political scene.
It counts against him in the public perception that he was always a close
ally of Mr Kohl. As a minister in the state government of Baden-Wurttemberg,
where he was responsible for law and order, he enjoyed the reputation of a
strict conservative. Yet since going to the constitutional court in
Karlsruhe, he has been seen far more as a legal liberal, suggesting an
altogether more humanitarian disposition.
Two factors could yet upset the Herzog bandwagon. One is the perception that
he is too conservative. The other is a possible revolt by easterners,
including those in the CDU.
He managed to stir up a controversy with an interview in which he apparently
expressed the view that, while all second- and third-generation foreigners
in Germany should be given every opportunity to take out German citizenship,
those who declined should be encouraged to return home.
Mr Herzog insists he was misunderstood. Most of the interview in question,
in Focus magazine, was devoted to a rather careful and balanced view of
German nationalism. 'I am convinced that the concept of nation, in itself,
is no longer a real force,' he said. 'The idea that we are historically all
of one blood is historical nonsense. Only an old Nazi could believe that.'
The second factor that could make it difficult for Mr Herzog is that his
relaxed southern attitude does not seem to appeal to the embattled
easterners. They are bitter at the failure of the campaign for an electable
eastern candidate, which Mr Kohl had promised. The CDU members in the east,
who won the unification elections in 1990 with ease, now face decimation in
the coming state and national elections. They may feel the need to show
their independence from Mr Kohl and the western establishment.
Those are the dangers, not just for Mr Herzog's candidacy, but also for the
chancellor himself: for he desperately needs a good result to boost his own
re-election prospects.
So far, the political omens seem to be improving for Mr Kohl. His own low
popularity is picking up, the economy is just starting to improve, and the
mood in the country at large, including the east, is gradually moving from
pessimism to optimism. The SPD, led by Mr Rudolf Scharping, is clearly ahead
in the opinion polls, but it is not as far ahead as it needs to be for a
clear victory in the general election in October. Everything is left to play
for.
If Mr Herzog can win the presidential poll decisively, it would be just the
public demonstration Mr Kohl needs to turn the tide.
If he were to lose, it would be politically disastrous: it would show that
the FDP no longer has any faith in its present coalition partners, and that
the chancellor's once-sure political touch has deserted him. It would be the
clearest indication yet of the beginning of the end.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
