<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Hanson to shun British Coal sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, ROLAND RUDD and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hanson, the industrial conglomerate with worldwide coal interests, has ruled
itself out of buying any British Coal mines in the forthcoming privatisation
of the corporation.
It has decided not to make any payments to take part in the
pre-qualification exercise, one of Hanson's financial advisers said.
Companies considering bids must pay the government Pounds 15,000 by
Wednesday for each of the five regions in which they are interested. The
Department of Trade and Industry confirmed yesterday that companies that
failed to do so could not tender.
RTZ, the other large UK company with international coal interests, is
understood to be planning to pre-qualify in all five regions. It is
considered unlikely to make bids but wants to see the details of what is on
offer.
Hanson has often indicated it was an unlikely bidder but other companies
planning tenders had expected it to pay to register for the right to bid, if
only to keep its options open.
Both Hanson and RTZ have been put off by the likely fragmentation of the
industry. Although they would be able to bid for all five regions, the
chances of success in all are slim. The government has said it would
consider selling the whole industry to one bidder, but is keen to inject
competition into the coal market.
Each of the regions is tiny in comparison with RTZ's and Hanson's worldwide
interests and would therefore be un-attractive to them.
Several UK companies, including RJB Mining and Coal Investments, plan to pay
the Pounds 75,000 needed to qualify for all regions. Some will also pay to
qualify to bid for six 'non-core' pits which have been closed by British
Coal and are being offered separately from the regional packages.
Pre-qualification for each stand-alone pit will cost Pounds 5,000.
RJB Mining, led by Mr Richard Budge, is one of the few groups considering
tendering for all five regions. Coal Investments, led by Mr Malcolm Edwards,
former British Coal commercial director, is less likely to seek control of
all regions but wants to see what is on offer. Ryan Group, another coal
company, said yesterday it wanted to pre-qualify for the south Wales region.
It is also, in alliance with others, hoping to bid in north-east England and
Scotland.
Other companies likely to pre-qualify include Mining (Scotland), a
consortium which wants to buy the Scottish region, and Caledonian Mining,
which is interested in the north-east.
The Union of Democratic Mineworkers is considering bidding for the central
and south regions, and management buy-out teams are likely to emerge in
several regions.
The Yorkshire area of the National Union of Mineworkers will have to
re-ballot its members over its proposed transfer of assets to the national
union, the Certification Officer for Trade Unions and Employer Organisations
ruled yesterday, Robert Taylor writes.
The certification officer said he would give the reasons for his decision at
a later date. However, his office said that not all members of the Yorkshire
area had been accorded equal entitlement to vote.
</TEXT>
