<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Heseltine plans to expand training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Proposals to expand youth training credits, to extend the Minis management
information system and to privatise the Civil Aviation Authority's air
traffic control are all expected in the government white paper on
competitiveness to be published on Tuesday.
The document, postponed for a week after the death of Labour leader John
Smith, will be given a high-profile launch by the prime minister and seven
cabinet ministers.
But it is expected to include few policy initiatives and even fewer
financial commitments.
One senior Whitehall official said: 'There is a lot of diagnosis of the
competitiveness problem and a lot of pulling together of existing
initiatives to show that we do have a strategic approach, but there is not
much genuinely new in it.'
The area which receives the most critical analysis is education and
training. The white paper will unveil an extension of career development
loans, provide a new training package for small companies and spell out the
funding details for the new modern apprenticeship scheme, with the
government expected to fund the college-based element of the training.
On youth credits it had been planned to expand the existing experiment, now
covering about 60,000 people, to all training and enterprise councils, which
deliver government training initiatives in England and Wales.
The new proposal embraces people aged 16 to 19, who will be able to use a
credit to buy an academic sixth-form education, technical training at a
further education college or a modern apprenticeship place with an employer.
Funding through credits should help bring more equality of status between
academic and vocational education. But in the past it has been resisted by
the Department for Education and the Further Education Funding Council. It
has been pushed hard by the Confederation of British Industry and will raise
the status of careers guidance officers.
Most of the funding for credits will come from existing budgets. The
government plans to spend Pounds 185m on youth credits and modern
apprenticeships in the current year, rising to Pounds 706m in 1996-97.
The white paper is likely to please most wings of the Conservative party and
business opinion.
Rightwingers will be wary about the broad range of interests being pursued
by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, under the mantle
of competitiveness. But they may also be pleased at the lack of expensive,
interventionist proposals and the aggressively de-regulatory tone in parts
of the document.
</TEXT>
