<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Big advertiser set to make series for ITV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Procter &amp; Gamble, the US consumer-products group and inventor of the soap
opera, is set to make programmes for ITV in the first deal of its kind in
the UK.
The company, which is the world's biggest advertiser, is negotiating the
sale to the ITV network of a game show called Go Bingo. The Independent
Television Commission, which sets out strict rules about the influence
advertisers are allowed to have on programmes, said the show would not be
permitted to push Procter's products.
The deal would go much further than the present sponsorship arrangements
between commercial companies and TV programmes. Procter owns the rights to
Go Bingo. This contrasts with sponsored programmes, which are made
independently, and sponsors are then invited to associate themselves with
the finished programme.
TV sponsorship is becoming increasingly popular: Midland Bank is the latest
company to announce a link with a TV programme. It said on Monday that it
would sponsor Moving Story, a Carlton Television comedy series.
Ryvita, the crispbread manufacturer, is another company which has recently
moved into sponsorship - it will be associated with Swank, a weekly
afternoon fashion programme.
ITV, which confirmed that negotiations with Procter were in progress, said
there would be a straight sale of the bingo programme and there would be no
question of Procter bartering the programme in return for advertising
airtime. Bartering is a common practice elsewhere in Europe. In some
countries advertisers supply programmes complete with advertisements at the
beginning and end of the show.
The ITC said there had been a small number of advertiser-supplied programmes
shown in the UK since new rules made the practice possible in 1991. These
have included a Tina Turner concert made by Pepsi, the soft-drink producer,
and Indy car racing supplied by Texaco, the US oil group. However, it will
be the first time a multinational will have sold a series to the ITV
network.
To comply with ITC rules, Procter will have to state at the beginning and
end of the show that it has made the programme.
Mr Ed Artzt, Procter's chairman and chief executive, recently told a
conference of US advertising chiefs that the company was exploring
alternatives worldwide to conventional TV advertising because of the
increasing fragmentation of audiences and new media developments which mean
that viewers can choose not to receive advertisements.
</TEXT>
