FT  21 MAY 94 / Watchdog renews plea on BBC radio
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Chalfont, chairman of the Radio Authority, the regulatory body for the
commercial sector, yesterday renewed his plea that the BBC should give
promises of performance on its radio services and stick to them.
The decision to turn Radio 5 into a news and sport channel ahead of the
launch of a national speech-based commercial radio network underlined the
need for such commitments, he said.
'This would ensure that the BBC, in line with the commercial sector, could
not make dramatic changes to the character of its services (which could
narrow listening choice) without concern for its listeners as a whole,' Lord
Chalfont says in the authority's annual report.
