<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Demand for new homes still rising
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A further sharp rise in demand for new homes has provided evidence that
consumer confidence has not been derailed by April's tax increases,
according to a survey of more than 400 housebuilders.
The survey published today by the Housebuilders Federation shows a bigger
rise in sales of new homes than in the general housing market.
According to the federation, net reservations of new homes - agreed sales on
which deposits have been paid, less cancellations - increased in every month
this year compared with the corresponding months last year.
The federation said sales of other homes have risen more slowly judging by
recently published estate agents' figures. These were inflated last spring
by sales from the private sector to housing associations and Business
Expansion Schemes.
The federation said that the proportion of builders reporting house-price
increases had risen steadily since the beginning of this year.
Almost a third of builders reported last month that prices had increased in
the past 12 months, with a quarter saying that prices had risen by 1 per
cent to 2 per cent. This compares with 65 per cent reporting static prices
and only 2 per cent reporting price falls.
Sales figures were more impressive with 64 per cent of companies reporting
an increase in net reservations compared with April last year  - 16 per cent
said net reservations had fallen and 20 per cent said they were static.
Four-fifths of builders expected sales to increase this year compared with
1993.
The sales rise has been supported by a big increase in site visitors with 61
per cent of companies reporting a rise in site visits in April compared with
12 months earlier.
The federation said that the proportion of companies reporting sales and
price increases was higher last month than in March.
The strongest growth in site visitors and net reservations was in north-west
England, East Anglia, Greater London and south-east England.
Mr Richard Adamson, the federation's chairman, said the market, after a
dipping a little in the previous month, had bounced back in April with 'new
homes sales leading the housing market as a whole.
'Clearly the anticipation of April's tax increase had more effect on the
market than the reality of the increases, and it's reassuring to see this
reflected in the April figures,' he added.
Halifax Building Society, Britain's largest mortgage lender, has forecast
that house prices could rise by at least 5 per cent this year provided
consumer confidence does not subsequently weaken because of tax increases.
House sales on the same basis could rise by 10 per cent or 15 per cent.
Most observers, however, say it is too early to assess the full impact of
tax increases.
</TEXT>
