<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Business outlook in north 'positive'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The outlook for the majority of companies in the north of England is 'quite
positive', Mr David Cranston, northern chairman of the Confederation of
British Industry, said yesterday.
Speaking after the latest two-monthly meeting of the confederation's
northern regional council, which covers north-east England and Cumbria, Mr
Cranston said many companies had seen a sustained improvement in orders for
some time. The UK and Far East were particularly fruitful markets, although
those in continental Europe remained sluggish. A large number of companies
were planning to increase capacity or considering doing so, he said, and
some businesses represented at the meeting in Gateshead, Tyne and Wear, were
recruiting. There was some concern, he added, at the state of retail demand
because of recent tax increases. But Mr Cranston, also chief executive of
Northumbrian Water, believed the general optimistic picture would lead to a
sustained improvement in fortunes, feeding through to the consumer.
The regional council represents a cross-section of companies. The sectors
include engineering, electronics, chemicals, giftware, construction,
financial services, road haulage and the utilities.
Mr Cranston said the overall mood of the meeting was one of cautious
optimism. 'There was a general feeling that people were looking to the
future and making plans in an atmosphere of confidence.'
</TEXT>
