<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Retail deposits to societies increase sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
April is the kindest month for building society retail deposits, according
to the monthly savings figures produced by the Building Societies
Association.
The net retail funds received by societies in April last year came to more
than the net inflow for the previous three months put together, while last
month's figures represented the first net inflow since October.
Mr Adrian Coles, director-general of the association, said that the
turnaround in April's figures released yesterday to a net inflow of Pounds
385m showed that the outflows in previous months had been caused by a series
of special factors.
These factors included the pre-payment of fuel bills to avoid the imposition
of value added tax, and the success of the pensioners' guaranteed income
bond which was launched in January.
He acknowledged, however, that because of the seasonal nature of the
figures, there could still be some net outflows in the coming months.
However, he added that he did not expect them to be on the near-record scale
of the outflows of Pounds 653m and Pounds 404m in March and February
respectively.
Societies expect the improvements in the public finances to be reflected in
less competition from National Savings products, and believe that the
popularity of unit trusts will also fall away somewhat over the year.
Mr Geoffrey Lister, association chairman, predicted earlier this week that
more funding for societies would come from retail savings in the coming
months, in contrast to societies' decision in the first quarter of this year
to fund their mortgage lending more cheaply through wholesale funds.
Mr Coles said yesterday that the inflow of savings, taken together with the
Pounds 376m interest credited to accounts, was closer to the rise in
societies' mortgage lending than it had been in March.
This was reflected in the smaller amounts of wholesale funding raised, he
added.
</TEXT>
