<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Call on exam standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sales agents in the pensions and insurance industry should be made to sit
examinations invigilated by independent experts rather than their own
companies, according to Mr Martin Broughton, chief executive of BAT
Industries which is one of the UK's biggest insurers, Peter Marsh writes.
Voicing general concern about the standards for training and competence
proposed by the new Personal Investment Authority, Mr Broughton said
external invigilation was one way to assure the public that the industry was
operating ethically.
BAT, which owns the insurers Allied Dunbar and Eagle Star, has still to
decide whether to join the authority, which is due to take over in the
summer as the umbrella regulatory organisation to protect the private
investor.
In recent months BAT had proposed specific suggestions to the authority for
improving its standards on training, but the discussions had come to
nothing, Mr Broughton said in an interview.
Mr Kit Jebens, chief executive of the Lautro insurance watchdog which is to
be subsumed into the new authority, said the idea of external invigilation
was a 'red herring' because many companies had improved their training
standards under Lautro guidance in the past two years.
Critics have said that in the past, sales agents have lacked expertise about
available products and also been under intense pressure to sell because most
of them are paid on a commission basis.
</TEXT>
