<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Chorus of dissent in HK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Anthony Cheung, a founder member of Hong Kong's new coalition Democratic
Party, has been stripped of his post as a Hong Kong affairs adviser to
Beijing just one week before he was due to be formally appointed, Louise
Lucas writes from Hong Kong. China's move has been broadly criticised, even
by pro-Chinese figures. The implication is that those with dissenting views
will not be seen as suitable advisers and Beijing will listen merely to
sycophantic voices. The newly created Democratic Party brought under one
roof Mr Cheung's own party, Meeting Point, and the United Democrats, the
pro-democracy group led by Mr Martin Lee which is considered subversive by
the Chinese.
</TEXT>
