<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Clinton seeks to dismiss sex charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton's lawyers are expected to file a motion in court soon
asking for the dismissal of sexual harassment charges laid against him
earlier this month by a former Arkansas state employee, George Graham writes
from Washington. Mr Robert Bennett, who is acting as Mr Clinton's lawyer in
the case, is expected to argue for the suit to be dismissed because of a
broad presidential immunity to civil charges.
Ms Paula Jones charged in her suit that Mr Clinton pressed her for sex in a
hotel room three years ago, when he was still governor of Arkansas. The
Justice Department's office of legal counsel has been researching the
institutional implications of the case for the executive branch and the
presidency in general, but officials said yesterday that the department had
not yet 'formulated a decision or an opinion'. Officials added that no one
was yet working on a brief, but that it was likely that the judge in the
case would ask for the department's views on whether the president can be
sued.
</TEXT>
