<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Israeli soldiers shot dead by militants: PLO and Israeli
security forces to hold joint patrols in Gaza Strip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The PLO and Israeli security forces are to hold joint patrols in the Gaza
strip following the killing of two Israeli soldiers by radical Palestinian
gunmen yesterday.
The shootings put to the test policing arrangements between Israeli and
Palestinian police for the first time since Israeli military withdrawal.
The gunmen, belonging to extremist Islamic movements opposed to the
Palestinian self-rule agreement, shot the soldiers at a checkpoint a few
hundred metres inside the strip and then fled into the self-rule areas
controlled since Wednesday by Palestinian police.
Under the self-rule agreement Israeli security forces only have the right of
'hot pursuit' into the Palestinian-ruled area, but otherwise must work
through Palestinian police to try and secure the arrest of Palestinian
attackers.
Israel reacted by barring all Palestinians from entering the Jewish state
for nine days saying the closure would enable Palestinian policemen to firm
up security checks and curb further attacks. Since Israel eased a complete
closure last month at least 2,500 Palestinians had been crossing daily into
Israel to work.
The way in which Palestinian police handle their first security test and
take measures to curb violence by Palestinian extremists may well determine
future Israeli-PLO negotiations to expand self-rule to the rest of the
occupied West Bank and ultimately to statehood.
Mr Yossi Sarid, the Israeli environment minister, warned yesterday that
unless Mr Yassir Arafat, PLO chairman, took stiff measures against
extremists he would 'end his career as the mayor of Jericho because that
will be the end of the experiment'.
Palestinian security forces have said they intend to disarm radical factions
like the Hamas Islamic Resistance Movement who have vowed to continue armed
struggle against Israel from inside the self-rule areas. The 10 factions
opposed to the agreement, led by Hamas, have warned such a move could spark
an internal Palestinian civil war.
Major-General Nasr Yousef, head of the Palestinian police force, tried to
reassure Israel after yesterday's attack. 'There is no doubt we shall
exercise our right as the authority. We shall take the necessary measure,'
he said.
Mr Nabil Shaath, a senior PLO official who paid a surprise visit to the Gaza
from Cairo yesterday to bring money to the Palestinian police, said: 'I knew
some incidents would happen. I am very sorry that they happened. We have to
do our best to pre-empt and prevent them from recurring.'
PLO officials said the Palestinian police were not yet ready and would only
be firmly in control within a week. Yesterday's attack coincided with
mounting concern inside Israel about the ability of the PLO to govern the
faction-riven Strip of 800,000 Palestinians packed in teeming refugee camps
and squalid towns. Israeli military officers have warned that the
Palestinian police are underfunded and have failed to take control of law
and order.
</TEXT>
<XX>
