<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / North Korea cleared in arms row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Radioactive fuel rods removed from North Korea's nuclear reactor are still
under the supervision of international inspectors and have not been diverted
to make bomb-grade plutonium, US officials said yesterday.
North Korea's decision to press ahead with the discharge of fuel from its
reactor without making proper inspection arrangements with the International
Atomic Energy Agency constituted 'a serious safeguards violation,' officials
said, but the situation could still be retrieved.
'The IAEA, in fact, has told us that it is confident there is no diversion
of the fuel that has just been discharged,' said Mr William Perry, the
defence secretary, describing this as a hopeful sign.
On Wednesday Mr William Perry, US defence secretary, said the US would
increase the already high 'readiness level' of its troops in South Korea if
it proved necessary to seek sanctions against North Korea.
Tension over the refuelling of the North Korean reactor has centred on the
IAEA's ability to ensure continuous monitoring of Pyongyang's nuclear
facilities.
Inspectors want to be able to reconstruct the reactor's operating history in
order to verify that North Korea did not remove more fuel than it declared
during a previous discharge in 1989.
To do this, they must set aside a precise sample of the fuel rods from the
current discharge for a later analysis to determine the isotopic burn-up,
which would yield proof of North Korea's declarations.
With the discharged rods now in a storage pond, it is still possible to
reach agreement on this sample, but US officials warned that if North Korea
did not suspend the discharge, as IAEA officials have asked, or reach a
quick agreement with the IAEA on the sampling methodology, the opportunity
for this type of analysis could be lost.
'If the fuel is discharged without preserving the opportunity for this kind
of analysis, then it's irrevocably lost,' said Mr Robert Gallucci, who heads
the US policy steering group on Korea.
</TEXT>
