<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Malawi slips at last from iron grip of Banda: Michael Holman
and Nick Young on the end of an era
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN and NICK YOUNG
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dr Hastings Kamuzu Banda, who ruled Malawi from independence from Britain in
1964 until this week was the last of Africa's colonial autocrats.
Popularly known as the Ngwazi (Saviour) he led the former Nyasaland to
independence, consolidated his grip on power by turning the independent
state of Malawi into a one-party fiefdom run with a combination of Victorian
principles and an iron fist.
He once said: 'I do things; let others explain why.' But few have been able
to. He ruled according to his own whims and fancies, managing in the early
years of independence to achieve remarkable economic growth for a deeply
impoverished colonial backwater.
His legacy is one of human rights abuses, belated economic reforms
undermined by a reluctance to distinguish between legitimate personal
resources and state assets, and illusions of grandeur demonstrated by a
string of palaces and presidential retreats around the country, and a
personality cult as destructive as it was colourful.
With fly whisk in hand, and dressed in sombre suit, homburg and dark
glasses, he cut an incongruous figure as he joined the ever present M'bumba,
the redoubtable women who danced in attendance at public gatherings.
He was the product of an extraordinary childhood: the traditional missionary
education was followed by 40 years abroad as a student in the US and medical
doctor in the UK.
Regarded by many as a ruthless tyrant, Dr Banda was a shrewd, hard-working
and calculating politician. Using traditional culture, he set up a
well-oiled party machinery backed by a powerful security service that
controlled almost all aspects of Malawian life.
He personally controlled large parts of the economy 'in the interests of the
nation' including the giant Press Holdings said to account for more than a
third of GDP, until he reluctantly allowed economic reforms pressed on
Malawi by the World Bank to take state resources out of his hands.
A member of the Chewa tribe of central Malawi, Kamuzu Banda was born near
Kasungu in 1906 - although the date has always been the subject of
controversy. It may have been 1898.
He took the name of Hastings after the missionary who baptised him; studied
at the Livingstonia mission school near Lake Malawi and then set out to walk
over 1,000 miles to South Africa. On the way he found a job as a hospital
orderly in Rhodesia.
He studied medicine, history and politics in the US and further did studies
at Edinburgh and Glasgow.
He set up his first practice in Liverpool in 1941 and moved to London in
1946 where he joined the Labour Party and became the representative of the
Nyasaland African Congress, lobbying from his surgery against the British
government's imposition of the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland.
In 1957 he moved to the Gold Coast (now Ghana). When unrest flared in
Nyasaland a year later he was invited back home by local leaders.
On July 5 1964 Malawi was born and Dr Banda, its first premier, said: 'One
leader, one party, one government and no nonsense about it.'
In 1970 he declared himself President for Life. Ministers suspected of
plotting against him were imprisoned or forced into exile. A few died in
suspicious circumstances. In 1983 three ministers, including Dick Matenje, a
potential successor, were killed in a car crash.
Hundreds, if not thousands, of people have been summarily detained over the
years for breaking rank with a ruling party - of which all Malawians had to
be be members - that demanded Unity, Loyalty, Obedience and Discipline. Yet
despite this, his key role in the independence movement, which he never
allowed people to forget, ensured a near-divine reverence.
'Whoever takes over,' said one observer, 'will be a mere mortal.'
Material contributed by Mike Hall, former FT correspondent, Lilongwe
</TEXT>
