FT  21 MAY 94 / Old foes unite to lead South Africa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAPE TOWN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
An apartheid-era justice minister and an anti-apartheid veteran jailed for
fighting the system were chosen to lead South Africa's new multi-racial
Senate at its first meeting yesterday, AP reports from Cape Town.
The 90-member chamber, comprising 10 representatives from each of the
country's nine provinces, will work alongside the 400-member National
Assembly in governing the country for the next five years.
Senators unanimously chose Mr Kobie Coetsee to be Senate president. Mr Govan
Mbeki, who was in prison with Mr Nelson Mandela while Mr Coetsee was rising
through the ranks of the National party, was unanimously chosen deputy
president of the Senate.
The Senate will have the power to initiate legislation and to block bills
introduced by the National Assembly.
