<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Interest rates of 500% fail to revive drachma
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Greek drachma, facing sustained pressure for the past week, slipped
yesterday against the D-Mark despite another sharp rise in short-term
interest rates.
The drachma fell to DM152.5 from DM148.9 on Thursday, triggering speculation
that a devaluation was imminent, before closing at DM150.
The government's claim yesterday that it was 'satisfied' with the drachma's
performance in the week since capital controls were lifted did nothing to
restore confidence among bankers and economists.
There is growing concern that Mr Andreas Papandreou, the ailing socialist
prime minister, is not prepared to let the economy ministry push through new
fiscal measures ahead of next month's European parliament elections.
Mr Papandreou has made no statement on the currency crisis since he
commented that drachma was in 'business as usual' during a parliamentary
debate on Monday, the first day of upheaval on Greek financial markets.
Moreover, Mr Yannos Papantoniou, the new economy minister, has failed to
follow up on promises that the privatisation programme would be expanded to
help close a revenue gap in this year's budget projected at Dr450-500bn.
Mr Papantoniou's insistence that no new taxes would be introduced this year,
appears increasingly unrealistic, given Greece's deepening economic
predicament.
Analysts said that if currency stability is to be restored, the government
must accompany a faster depreciation of the drachma, expected next week,
with a specific package of measures.
To convince the markets that the socialists are serious about reducing the
public sector deficits, these would have to include spending curbs and more
rigorous measures to improve tax collection.
The surge in short-term interest rates, which yesterday reached a record 500
per cent, has failed to protect the drachma following the freeing of
short-term capital movement.
The Bank of Greece was estimated to have spent more than Dollars 300m
yesterday to support the drachma, bringing foreign exchange losses to over
Dollars 700m for the week.
One dealer said: 'If devaluation is to be avoided, depreciation must
accelerate. These interest rates can't be kept up for more than a few days.'
However, while smaller Greek companies faced a cash squeeze because of the
explosion in interest rates, several banks said they were still lending to
corporate customers at less than 40 per cent.
</TEXT>
