<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Scandal casts shadow over autonomy for Bank of Spain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Luis Angel Rojo, governor of the Bank of Spain, should be celebrating
that the institution he has run for nearly two years has gained a
Bundesbank-like independence. Instead he is picking up the broken crockery
caused by the scandal involving his predecessor Mr Mariano Rubio.
'The public seems to think that everyone in the Bank of Spain is under
suspicion,' says Mr Rojo with a stab at humour. The situation clearly
infuriates this intense academic who held the chair of economic theory at
Madrid University before he joined the bank to set up its research
department in the 1970s.
The fallout from the Rubio affair is reflected in the Bank of Spain autonomy
statute that was approved by the Spanish parliament on Thursday. The
legislators introduced amendments to the draft law that subject portfolio
investments by senior central bank officials to strict guidelines and
supervision.
Mr Rubio was coincidently released on Pta15m (Pounds 72,400) bail after
spending two weeks in prison on the same day that the Bank of Spain gained
its independence. He is being investigated for tax evasion and insider
dealing in connection with a Pta115m stock market portfolio that was managed
for him by the failed Ibercorp financial services group in the late 1980s
when he was the central bank governor.
Mr Rojo says that what the public has not fully understood is that the
probity of the bank of Spain as an institution outweighs by far whatever
scams might be conducted by those who sat a given moment might represent it.
'Supposing (the allegations about Mr Rubio) are true; the mechanisms of the
Bank of Spain are such that whatever frailties and temptations its governor
might have will be neutralised,' says Mr Rojo. 'It is extraordinarily
difficult for a senior official to favour a financial institution and get
away with it.'
Mr Rojo argues that the scandal surrounding Ibercorp, a bank which sought
out fashionable wealthy clients, and the former governor, bears out his
point; it was a Bank of Spain inspection of Ibercorp's assets, when Mr Rubio
was still governor, that prevented a proposed merger within the group and
prompted its collapse - and Mr Rubio's ruin.
He concedes, however, that it might take time to restore the bank's
credibility. It irks Mr Rojo that the scandal dominated the headlines last
month just at the time when the central bank was successfully concluding the
rescue of Banesto, the troubled banking group whose board he peremptorily
dismissed on the grounds of gross mismanagement.
Mr Rojo does however have now a golden opportunity to project the Bank of
Spain's virtues as well as his own professionalism. In line with the
Maastricht treaty's provisions for central bank autonomy, the bank has the
responsibility for setting monetary policy and Mr Rojo becomes the effective
guardian of price stability.
It is clear that he relishes the prospect and is undeterred by potential
conflicts with politicians. 'Our basic priority may not necessarily be to
create employment. Our job is to ensure price stability and that is an
objective that hardly anyone in politics is interested in.'
He hopes to raise the bank's image through 'open government' procedures that
will include detailed progress reports on inflation and regular appearances
before parliament's economy and finance committee.
He would also like to follow the example of Bank of England governor Mr
Eddie George and have formal meetings with the economy and finance minister
at which minutes are taken and subsequently made public.
'At the moment the minister and I just talk on the phone and see each other
informally, perhaps twice a week, when we have the time to do so. I like
Eddie George's initiative with the Chancellor of the Exchequer but it
depends on my minister here liking it too.'
</TEXT>
