<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / E Germans win compensation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's lower house yesterday finally agreed on a compensation package for
former owners whose property was confiscated by the Nazis or communists in
eastern Germany.
At the same time, a limited compensation fund has been granted to former
land owners whose property was expropriated by the Soviet authorities
between 1945 and 1949.
The long-awaited decision removes a major obstacle hindering investment in
eastern Germany. It also ends four years of amendments, debates and
divisions within the governing Christian Democratic Union coalition, and
between eastern and western German deputies about how to compensate former
property owners.
Under the terms of the unification treaty, former owners whose land was
confiscated by the Nazis between 1933-1945 and by the communists between
1949-1990 are entitled to restitution or compensation. No similar rights
were extended to the large aristocratic landowners whose property was
expropriated by the Soviet authorities.
The new measures involve the setting up of a DM18bn compensation fund,
issued in bonds. Some DM12bn will be allocated to former owners whose
property was confiscated between 1933-1945 and 1949-1990. The amount of
compensation for each individual will be based on the 1935 value of
property, and multiplied by several factors depending on whether the
property was land or housing. The bonds will not be fully redeemable until
2004.
In addition the Bundestag yesterday put aside DM3.4bn compensation, and will
allow former landowners to buy back a percentage of their property at below
market prices.
A further DM2bn has been granted to east Germans who had suffered under the
Nazis but received no compensation under the communists.
</TEXT>
