<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Eurotunnel confident of raising debt ahead of a rights issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eurotunnel was last night confident of raising almost all the Pounds 700m
senior bank debt which the Channel tunnel operator needs before launching an
Pounds 850m rights issue. This could take place towards the end of next
week.
By yesterday afternoon, commitments had been received from banks for Pounds
580m, still well short of the required sum. But in a remarkable shift from
bleak pessimism to cautious optimism in just 24 hours, the group's bankers
said last night they were confident of 'delivering what the company
requires'.
'There is a whole new mood at Eurotunnel,' said a banker.
The Bank of England has played an important role over the past two weeks in
persuading recalcitrant banks to contribute. It is highly unlikely that
Eurotunnel's four main Japanese bank creditors - Bank of Tokyo, Long Term
Credit Bank, Sanwa and Industrial Bank of Japan - would have agreed to make
contributions to the senior debt without pressure from the Bank.
It also emerged that the refinancing would have failed without the
participation in the senior debt offer of two public sector banks, the
European Investment Bank, which contributed more than Pounds 50m, and
Germany's reconstruction bank, KFW. The 200-bank syndicate hopes to complete
its side of the fund-raising exercise by the middle of next week. The rights
issue would be launched immediately afterwards.
Leading fund managers said underwriting the issue would be extremely
difficult. They will insist on an issue price at a substantial discount to
last night's price of 374p for Eurotunnel units, down 30p on the day.
In a separate development, Mr Richard Morris, Eurotunnel's safety director,
said yesterday he was under instructions to 'meet and cajole' the
Anglo-French Intergovernmental Commission on safety to grant a safety
certificate for passenger services as soon as possible.
While stressing there was no intention of compromising safety, Mr Morris
said he was optimistic that the latest target for the start up of passenger
services will be brought forward from September to late July, in time for
the peak summer period.
London stocks, Page 17; World stocks, Page 23; Lex, Page 26
</TEXT>
