<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 94 / Building society lending declines but savers return:
Strength of consumer demand unclear as new home sales rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH, PHILIP COGGAN and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British savers flocked back to building society accounts last month,
providing a surprise twist to two weeks of growing evidence of strong
consumer demand.
At the same time, April figures showed a drop in net new mortgage
commitments by building societies and a sharp slowdown in bank and building
society lending.
There were signs, however, that tax increases which took effect last month
have so far had only a slight impact on the gradual recovery in the UK
housing market.
Taken together, the statistics published yesterday gave no clear picture of
the UK economy.
The decline in lending and rise in savings implies a lack of confidence on
the part of consumers and businesses.
But the Housebuilders Federation said yesterday that sales and prices of new
homes were rising faster than at any time since the recession began in 1990.
A survey of more than 400 housebuilders showed that the housing recovery,
which slowed slightly in March, resumed its upward progress last month.
The Bank of England meanwhile announced that M4, its broad measure of the
money supply, and bank lending in April were weak. The annual growth of M4
slipped back to 5.7 per cent in April, from 5.9 per cent in March, while M4
lending was just Pounds 500m, compared with the Pounds 2bn expected by City
analysts.
A contributing factor was a Pounds 911m drop in lending by the biggest
British banks. This, according to the British Bankers Association, was the
first monthly decline since December 1992.
Net new mortgage commitments by building societies totalled Pounds 3.1bn
last month - down from Pounds 3.7bn in March but broadly in line with April
last year. The number of new commitments was 54,000 last month, compared
with 50,000 in April 1993, said the Building Societies Association.
Mr Adrian Coles, director-general of the BSA, said the fall in net new
commitments came after a very sharp rise in March which had been linked to
the timing of the Easter weekend. But he emphasised the increase in
societies' net lending compared with this time last year.
The net inflow to societies of Pounds 385m in April ended a five-month
period of withdrawals from the sector and represented the highest level of
deposits since May last year.
Heavy withdrawals resulted in a net monthly outflow of Pounds 653m in March,
the highest since September 1986.
Although, as Mr Coles pointed out, the turnround in the pattern of savings
over March and April was the strongest for several years, the inflow for
April was still weak compared with the Pounds 1.1bn recorded in the same
month last year.
Savers have been turning to investments such as unit trusts or national
savings products. Societies have had to rely more heavily on the interest
automatically credited to accounts, and the wholesale money markets, to
finance lending.
Mr John Wriglesworth, housing analyst at stockbrokers UBS, said that
although competition from unit trusts and national savings products might be
waning, societies were facing more competition from the high street banks
for personal customers.
Although the weak bank and building society lending figures may reflect the
impact of April's tax increases, analysts warned that the figures were
highly erratic.
The Treasury said the recent trend, which showed slow growth in lending, was
consistent with a low inflation environment.
Retail deposits to societies increase sharply, Page 6
No joy in a good news week, Page 9
Currencies, Page 15
London stocks, Page 17 and Weekend FT, Page II
Lex, Page 26
</TEXT>
