<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / (CORRECTED) Survey of Greek Banking and Finance (2):
Disposals put on hold as politics comes back - With the state-controlled
banks slow to modernise, the private sector is making further gains in
market share
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 23rd May 1994) appended to this article.
After a gap of several years, politics re-entered Greek banking when a
socialist government returned to power last autumn, reviving doubts about
the state-controlled banks' commitment to modernising.
Greece's four state-owned banking groups, which control 62.2 per cent of
loans and 73.6 per cent of deposits between them, acquired governors with
close ties to the ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movement (Pasok) but little
recent experience of commercial banking in Greece's increasingly competitive
environment.
Reflecting socialist reservations about their conservative predecessors'
privatisation programme, the state-owned banks' plans to dispose of equity
participations, including sales of subsidiary banks, hotels and insurance
companies - some of them at an advanced stage - have been placed on hold.
The state-controlled development bank, ETVA, burdened both with equity
participations in loss-making industrial enterprises and a high percentage
of non-performing loans, has already received a Dr205bn capital injection
from the government in the form of long-term bonds.
The other state development bank, ETEVA, keen to expand into commercial
banking, is negotiating with the government to acquire the Bank of Crete,
which is still administered by a commissioner from the central bank more
than five years after a Dollars 200m embezzlement scandal there was cleaned
up, without losses to depositors.
The private sector banks, which have invested heavily in information
technology in the past few years and maintain lower staffing levels, now
appear poised to make further inroads into the state banks' market share.
Many routine operations at state-owned banks are carried out manually.
Credit card operations and ATM networks are still underdeveloped by
comparison with the private sector.
The efficiency gap is demonstrated by figures for net profits per employee:
National Bank, the largest state bank, recorded only Dr1.4m per employee in
1992, compared to Dr4.6m per employee for Credit Bank, the largest private
bank. The state banks have also been hardest hit by last year's law which
bans banks from accruing interest on loans left unserviced for more than 12
months. Non-performing loans are estimated to account for more than 14 per
cent of National Bank's loan portfolio, while the figure for Ionian Bank
reached 20 per cent.
By comparison, the average for the eight private banks is less than 3 per
cent.
Yet despite higher provisions and shrinking margins resulting from increased
competition, banks' profits grew steadily in 1993. One banker said: 'Spreads
are still good, whatever anyone says, and even the state banks have been
improving fee and commission-based income.'
However, last year's earnings figures were increased by a requirement for
banks to publish consolidated accounts for the first time.
Conditions may be more difficult this year, with most banks expected to
increase provisions as recession persists. Hopes for growth are pinned on
the socialist government's decision to raise the consumer credit ceiling to
Dr8m. Again, this offers greater opportunities for the private banks, which
are more flexible in developing new products.
If the new managers at the state banks have little to say about
cost-cutting, they are well aware of the challenges ahead. Mr Panagiotis
Poulis, chairman of Commercial Bank, says: 'We have a strong deposit base
and a good branch network, but the range of variety of products, not to
mention quality of services, leaves a lot to be desired.'
Commercial Bank's plans for expansion suffered a setback last year when the
bank was unable to raise more than Dr35bn of a projected Dr50bn rights
issue. Nevertheless it is going ahead with plans to improve its ATM network
and offer a range of new consumer-oriented products. It has also taken a
bold decision - by Greek banking standards - in going ahead with the
liquidation of Investment Bank, a loss-making subsidiary.
Ionian Bank, Commercial Bank's subsidiary and main rival, is planning to
strengthen its balance sheet through a Dr30bn rights issue later this year.
Mr Panayotis Korliras, the bank's chairman, says: 'We have to expand our
fee-based activities quickly to increase competitiveness.'
Ionian has lost considerable ground to Credit Bank, growing steadily as
several years of investment in technology and branch expansion start to
bring results. Following a recent Dr30bn rights issue, Credit Bank is now
the largest Greek bank in terms of market capitalisation. Its aim is to
become a broad-based financial services group which can compete on western
European terms.
Like several of its rivals in the state sector, Credit Bank also sees
opportunities for growth in the Balkans, where Greek companies already
active in trade are starting to make long-term investments. Through its
investment banking subsidiary, Alpha Finance, the bank is setting up a
commercial bank in Bucharest, with equity participation from the European
Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
Meanwhile, Commercial Bank is planning to take a 35 per cent stake in a new
Romanian private bank, Co-operative Bank of Bucharest. Not to be outdone,
Ionian Bank intends to set up a subsidiary bank in Bulgaria, with a group of
Greek businessmen taking a minority stake.
Attica Bank, a small state-owned bank, plans a similar venture in Albania
with Greek companies already active there. The bank will use the branch
network of the Albanian Savings Bank, which will also have an equity
participation. The banks' Balkan ventures are intended to focus on trade
finance, while gradually developing a local currency deposit base.
Mr Korliras says: 'The capital outlay is not great and overheads are fairly
low. Greece is a medium-technology banking country, so its banks can
usefully bridge the gap between the existing Bulgarian system and European
commercial banking.'
But the Balkan ventures are suffering considerable delays - blamed on the
absence of a regulatory framework for banking in all three countries and
difficulties both in finding suitable staff and setting up adequate computer
and communications links with Athens.
