<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / International Company News: Austrian power group lifts
hydro-electric output
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Verbundgesellschaft, Austria's largest electricity and power group, has
reported a 30 per cent rise in profits for 1993, but will keep its dividend
unchanged at 16 per cent.
Group pre-tax profits were Sch1.51bn (Dollars 129m) compared with Sch1.15bn
in 1992. Sales rose slightly from Sch19.4bn in 1992 to Sch19.5bn last year.
Mr Johann Haider, chief executive, said results were boosted by favourable
climatic conditions that helped raise hydro-electricity output and reduce
imports. He added that prospects for 1994 looked good, with
hydro-electricity output rising by 17 per cent in the first quarter.
The company which is 51 per cent state-owned, plans further rationalisations
to improve efficiency. The 5,300 workforce will be cut by 700-800 by the end
of 1997.
It has requested authorisation from the government to raise electricity
prices by 6 per cent, but this is still under review.
It plans to invest Sch5.8bn from cash flow this year, following investments
of Sch4.1bn in 1993.
