<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / BT raises dividend on flat result
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications's final dividend of 10.05p raised its total 7.1
per cent to 16.7p but Sir Iain Vallance, chairman, refused to be drawn on
future dividend growth.
The company announced pre-tax profits of Pounds 2.76bn (Dollars 4.14bn) for
the year to March 31, against Pounds 1.97bn. Leaving aside redundancy
charges, disposals and other non-recurring items, the increase was less than
3 per cent. Operating profits were Pounds 3.53bn (Pounds 3.47bn) before
redundancy charges of Pounds 517m (Pounds 1.03bn).
At Pounds 13.7bn, BT's annual turnover rose 3.3 per cent. Earnings per share
were 28.5p, against 19.8p. Before one-off items the increase was 0.4 per
cent.
Growth was stronger than expected in the UK, but the Pounds 750m of
redundancy charges to be taken in this year's figures were larger than
analysts had anticipated. The high cost, against the past year's Pounds 517m
(down from Pounds 1.03bn), is due to a new emphasis on cutting management
jobs. BT is set to shed a further 15,000 jobs this year.
The company has raised the possibility of regional phone pricing in the UK,
after the introduction of a new charging system next year, which will
replace unit-based prices with per-second charges.
Analysts believe the change has clear attractions for BT in its battle with
competing operators building local or regional networks.
BT's share price has fallen by nearly 20 per cent against the FT-A All-Share
index over the past year amid fears about regulation and strong UK telecoms
competition.
Inland call volumes were 6 per cent up on 1992-93, increasing turnover by
1.9 per cent despite the effects of a price cap agreed with Oftel, the
telecoms regulator, obliging BT to cut its prices by 7.5 per cent after
allowing for inflation. BT is bound by the same price cap this year.
Sir Iain committed BT to vigorous efforts to attract customers back from
competitors who have taken about 11 per cent of the UK market. Mr Hepher
promised an intensification of the marketing campaign aimed at the
residential sector. The objective was to build 'a high phone-usage culture
in the UK'.
BT will make a special Pounds 250m contribution to its pension scheme this
year following a revaluation, after an Pounds 800m special payment last
year.
BT's gearing was down to 9 per cent at the end of March, but will rise
sharply this year if its Dollars 5.3bn alliance with MCI, the US
long-distance carrier, is cleared by US regulators.
Lex, Page 16
</TEXT>
