<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Survey of Greek Banking and Finance (15): Cautious toes dip
into equity markets / Noting a shift from cash to capital markets in fleet
financing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE BRIGGS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Greek shipowners spent almost Dollars 3bn last year on acquiring some 400
secondhand ships, totalling 23m deadweight tons.
The figures sound startling, even by shipping industry standards. What is
more surprising, a high percentage of transactions were in cash, with no
financing raised.
The extent of Greek shipowners' liquidity is proverbial, but it cannot be
accurately estimated, according to bankers. Yet few would dispute a market
rumour that a well-known owner recently came up with enough cash to fund a
new building order for three vessels.
However, Greek owners less well provided with cash are more likely to raise
funds for ship purchases through bank financing, often on more stringent
terms than in the past. Spreads are now higher and loan periods shorter.
Some lenders also attach a requirement to generate fee-paying business for
the bank.
Nevertheless, the unprecedented surge in sales and purchases by Greek owners
in the past couple of years has generated concern about the cost of fleet
renewal. There is growing interest in tapping both domestic and
international capital markets for funds.
So far, the shipowners' efforts to find new sources of financing have
concerned debt rather than equity.
Last year, Eletson Corporation, the Piraeus-based product carrier operator,
launched the first public bond to be issued by a Greek shipping company,
raising Dollars 140m in first preferred ship mortgage notes against six of
its vessels. Priced to yield accrued interest of 9.25 per cent, the 10-year
notes are not redeemable before 1998.
The US offering, underwritten and sold by Citibank Securities, was more than
twice oversubscribed. Credit agencies gave the bond a rating considered
encouraging - BA2 from Moody's and BB from Standard and Poor's - given
institutional investors' suspicions of the shipping industry.
Eletson said it would use Dollars 100m of the funds raised to write down
outstanding ship mortgages and the remainder as working capital. The company
is considered a good risk because of the age of its 17-vessel fleet. With
five new ships due to be delivered over the next two years and seven
disposals of older vessels, the fleet will have an average age of 2.5 years,
compared to an average of more than 10 years for the industry.
However, only a few Greek companies are expected to tap the international
capital market for long-term funding.
Ms Marianna Moschou, general manager of Citibank Shipping Bank in Piraeus,
says: 'Few companies will meet the prerequisites for a public offering, and
even fewer will want to go through the gruelling procedures involved,
including full disclosure and the due diligence process required by the US
Securities and Exchange Commission.'
Shipowners worldwide raised only Dollars 1bn last year in the US market
through public bond offerings, suggesting that they are still a fledgling
instrument for the shipping industry.
Nor are private placements common, although they are sometimes used in
restructuring debt. Adriatic Tankers Shipping, which operates a mixed fleet
of chemicals, product and crude oil carriers, completed a Dollars 80m
private debt placement earlier this year. The 10-year facility, carrying a 9
per cent interest rate, was secured by first preferred mortgages on 20 of
the company's vessels.
Nevertheless, Greek shipowners are also dipping a cautious toe into the
equity market.
The Tsakos Shipping Group, which set up the US-listed Global Ocean Carriers,
a bulk carrier operation for which the group acts as technical manager, now
has another investment vehicle, listed on the Norwegian stock exchange.
Shares in the Maritime Investment Fund, a tanker operation also managed by
Tsakos, started trading on Oslo's small board at the end of 1993.
Another manager, Stelmar Tankers Management, was set up in 1992 with the aim
of going public once it acquires a track record that can attract investors.
Trying to dispel the accepted image of shipping as a high-risk investment,
Stelmar has geared its operation to the requirements of a stock market
listing, acquiring Greece's first-ever ISO 9002 management qualification,
together with its first certification under the International Ship
Management Code.
'Going public is the way to raise money from the market. I'm not in favour
of public debt issued by a private company,' says Mr Stelios Hadji-Ioannou,
Stelmar's owner.
The Athens Stock Exchange, despite its comparatively small size, is starting
to attract passenger shipping companies. Two 'back door' entries were
achieved through the acquisition by shipping concerns of holding groups
already listed.
One, Attica Enterprises, bought and sold a package of shares in Strintzis
Lines, a ferry operator that has since obtained approval for a listing on
its own account, and disposed of a chain of household goods stores before
focusing on passenger shipping. It has placed a Dollars 146m order for two
ro-ro ferries and has an option on building two more.
The other, Cosmos Maritime, is a subsidiary of the Cosmos Group, with
interests in textiles and food processing. It is controlled by Mr Dimitris
Hatzis, a shipowner who has been diversifying in recent years.
Cosmos Maritime indirectly links ocean-going vessels with the Athens
exchange, through a co-operation agreement with the Monaco-based Vlasov
group to handle shipbuilding and repair activities in Greece, together with
bareboat charters on two dry cargo vessels.
However, the Capital Markets Committee, the watchdog for the exchange, is
tightening its regulations to prevent more shipping companies from following
suit. While passenger shipping operators will be admitted to the bourse,
though under more stringent conditions than they might have expected, the
committee is reluctant to permit other shipping concerns to join the market.
Strintzis Lines, which operates passenger ferries in the Adriatic and the
Aegean, as well as a passenger line between Swansea and Cork, had to
restructure its operation, increasing its liabilities, to secure approval
for a Dr5.1bn public offering.
There are problems, too, with Dane Shipping Lines, a joint stock company
with a limited number of shareholders, which wants to raise Dr2.5bn through
a flotation on the bourse. The company, based on the island of Rhodes,
operates passenger ferries in the eastern Aegean islands.
Dane is being forced to restructure after its original application for a
listing was turned down.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GRZ  Greece, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P44   Water Transportation.
    P60   Depository Institutions.
    P61   Nondepository Institutions.
</IN>
