<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Survey of Greek Banking and Finance (12): Tax free era is
over - Mutual funds have room for growth despite recent legislation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MCDONALD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mutual funds in Greece have experienced explosive growth over the past five
years: numbers have have risen from two to more than 70, with a total of
Dr1,320bn under management at the end of the first quarter this year.
This pattern looked likely to continue, when the socialist government
unexpectedly imposed a 15 per cent tax on distributed dividends from the
funds' earnings from previously untaxed sources such as government
securities, capital gains on equities and foreign earnings. A second blow
came when the government decided to tax interest earned on 'repos'  -
fixed-term repurchase agreements - at 15 per cent, too.
Previously, income from government securities had been wholly tax-free,
although interest earnings on bank deposits were taxed at 15 per cent.
Both measures were included in a new fiscal package voted through parliament
last month, intended to raise revenues and curb tax evasion. However, they
are expected to slow down the growth of mutual funds over the next 12
months. Furthermore, according to some fund managers, they could lead to
redemptions.
'Some people will leave as an emotional reaction - rather than a logical one
 -simply because they don't want to pay tax,' says Mr Dimitris Paparistides,
a fund manager with Intertrust.
Other investors may redeem their holdings in order to buy government bonds -
still tax-free for individual investors. However, they are not likely to
take up the five- and seven-year bonds which the state has been selling to
the funds in order to extend its debt profit.
With Greek holdings in mutual funds equivalent to only about 14 per cent of
bank deposits, compared to 60 per cent in France, there is still
considerable potential for growth.
However, the funds have more than 70 per cent of their holdings invested in
government securities, paying real interest rates of 8-10 per cent, while
many of them have been using repos as the equivalent of short-term bank
deposits. Neither will fund managers be able to bypass the new legislation
through ploughing back gains from investments now subject to tax. While
profits from capital gains need not be distributed, dividends and coupon
earnings must be paid in full. Mr Paparistides says: 'Unless government
bonds are also taxed, the rapid increase in the growth of funds will be
halted.'
The cynical view is that the government has decided to tax mutual funds as
part of its drive to reduce tax evasion. There are an estimated 200,000
small- and medium-sized investors with holdings in mutual funds, of which a
sizeable portion derives from the black economy.
At worst, investors may decide to take a tax-free profit by redeeming their
holdings before December 31, when dividends are distributed. According to
the Union of Greek Institutional Investors, this would force the funds to
liquidate large volumes of holdings, with potentially disastrous effects on
the Athens stock market.
Mutual funds took off in Greece as part of the liberalisation of financial
markets at the end of the 1980s, while the lifting of controls on
medium-term capital movements offered the option of making investments
abroad. Both banks and insurance companies have been active in setting up
funds, which are required to have minimum capitalisation of Dr200m and are
managed by independent companies. Large Greek insurance companies are well
placed to market the funds to small investors through their extensive sales
networks.
While the funds can invest freely in Greek or European Union equities and
new issues, no more than 20 per cent of holdings can be invested in stock
markets outside the EU.
Funds are not permitted to invest more than 10 per cent of net worth in a
single company and cannot hold more than 40 per cent of its portfolio in
companies in which it owns five per cent or more.
The maximum stake a fund can take in an individual company is 10 per cent.
The maximum holding in one company by all the funds managed by a single
investment company is limited to 30 per cent. As a result, a parent bank or
insurance company cannot lean on fund managers to shore up prices or
indirectly underwrite capital increases. Before the new tax measures, mutual
fund managers were predicting another year of healthy growth, with total
investment rising to well over Dr2,000bn. The projections have fallen, but
some managers remain optimistic.
'We still believe that funds under management can rise to around Dr1,700bn
this year in spite of the tax,' says Mr Spyros Kriticopoulos, investment
director at Alico Eurobank.
Alico found itself in the uncomfortable position of launching a fixed income
fund just after the new measures were introduced, together with a US dollar
bond fund. While subscriptions for the fixed income fund were considerably
lower than originally anticipated, the bond fund attracted 'a lot of
interest, suggesting that investors are willing to diversify rather than
liquidate their holdings,' Mr Kriticopoulos adds.
</TEXT>
