<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Survey of Greek Banking and Finance (9): A man with his work
cut out - Greece has the EU's highest debt to GDP ratio
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Behind the desk of Mr Nikos Kyriazides, the deputy finance minister, stands
a late 19th century safe - a leftover from a period when Greece declared
itself bankrupt more than once.
It is a sobering reminder for Greece's new debt manager as he addresses a
public debt that has ballooned from 98 per cent of gross domestic product in
1989 to 138 per cent of GDP in January this year.
Greece has the highest debt to GDP ratio of any EU member, almost double the
target for economic convergence under the terms of the Maastricht treaty.
Last year the government borrowing requirement reached 13.9 per cent of GDP
against a target of 7.9 per cent.
What should have been a manageable shortfall in budget revenues turned into
a yawning gap as a result of a burst of pre-election spending by the former
conservative government and the loss of more than Dr300bn in expected
privatisation revenues.
So far, the socialist government is proving no more efficient at collecting
taxes than its conservative predecessor. Unless radical measures are taken
to boost revenues, this year's budget revenue shortfall will bring central
government borrowing up to 17 per cent of GDP, against a target of 12.8 per
cent.
Clearly, Mr Kyriazides, a former executive director of the IMF who has also
served as deputy governor of the Bank of Greece, the central bank, has his
work cut out.
Apart from the problem of financing a mounting deficit at interest rates
approaching 20 per cent, an additional Dr3,600bn of government debt has been
revealed, which will have to be securitised in 1994.
'We managed to cover the end-of-year problem through increased borrowing
abroad,' Mr Kyriazides says. 'The question now is getting interest rates
down to lighten the burden of financing both new and existing debt.'
In addition to raising Y340m on the Japanese market, the government borrowed
Dr200bn from four Greek banks through a seven-year bond issue with interest
at 2.25 per cent above the rate for 12-month Treasury bills.
The newly discovered debt includes Dr280bn in obligations by the state-owned
Agricultural Bank and another Dr350bn in state-guaranteed debt, with the
remainder in claims against the government by the central bank, which must
be recognised under the terms of the Maastricht treaty.
While part of the new debt can be securitised without increasing net
borrowing, the Bank of Greece is demanding market rates of interest on the
government's residual debt, which will add to the government's borrowing
problem.
The government has tried to ease the pressure by extending its debt profile,
issuing three- and five-year bonds which have proved popular with
institutional investors in Greece and elsewhere. However, these offer no
real respite as they carry floating rates linked to that of the 12-month
Treasury bill.
'The policy is now changing: over the next few months, we plan to start
issuing fixed-coupon drachma bonds at longer maturities, now that that the
supranationals have done so,' Mr Kyriazides says.
The successful launch of 'marathon' bonds by the European Investment Bank
and World Bank earlier this year has soothed the government's fears that
fixed-coupon bonds would prove unattractive to investors. While the annual
inflation rate has steadily declined, falling from a peak of 16.4 per cent
in March 1993 to 10.2 per cent in March this year, interest rates on the
12-month bill have moved down more slowly, from 22 per cent in to 18.5 per
cent over the same period.
As a result, real interest rates reached a record 8.3 per cent last month.
They seem unlikely to decline further; the inflation rate is edging up again
and there are signs of fatigue among investors, underlined by last month's
shortfall of about Dr60bn in renewals of Treasury bills.
Real rates must also remain high enough to continue attracting investors
from abroad, while allowing for depreciation of the drachma.
However, the government's unexpected decision to liberalise short-term
capital movements six weeks ahead of the July 1 deadline could alter the
picture dramatically.
The liberalisation was designed to pre-empt speculative attacks against the
drachma in the run-up to July 1 and avert a possible devaluation. It remains
to be seen whether the central bank's policy of hiking interest rates on the
interbank market to record levels in order to protect the currency can be
sustained for more than a few weeks.
There is no doubt that interest rates on government bonds will have to rise
sharply, to buttress the drachma against the likelihood of massive capital
outflows.
Greek bankers predict that devaluation can be held off, at least for the
moment, through faster depreciation of the drachma. Whatever happens, the
prospects for lightening the debt burden this year are fading fast.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GRZ  Greece, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
