<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Survey of World Taxation (4): Governments cling to their
autonomy - The European Union is crawling cautiously towards harmonisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JONATHAN SCHWARZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
People who are sceptical about European tax harmonisation and integration
commonly point to the failure of the Ruding Commission to make any real
impact on European tax systems in the Single Market. They note that various
measures proposed to harmonise corporate income tax in Europe have failed to
be enacted. The Transitional VAT Regime which has been in place since
January 1, 1993 is criticised for its complexity and other shortcomings.
The doctrine of subsidiarity has had a significant impact on tax
harmonisation in the post-Maastricht period.
Under the direction of Taxation Commissioner Christiane Scrivener, the
Commission has changed tack somewhat in relation to its programme. Member
state autonomy has been emphasised and a number of direct tax harmonisation
measures previously proposed no longer form the main thrust of the
Commission's direct tax activities.
The Commission is now focusing specifically on cross-border activities. It
has issued detailed recommendations on how cross-border or frontier
employees are to be taxed in order to avoid arguments about tax
discrimination against employees from one member state working in another.
Other projects include the harmonisation and simplification of procedures
for claims under intra-Community tax treaties relating to repayment of
withholding tax and other reductions of taxes. They are also examining the
improvement of exchange of information procedures in order to counter
cross-border tax evasion.
Neither of these are likely to result in high profile legislative
amendments, but will undoubtedly contribute to the integration of tax
administration and ease of cross-border investment.
The European tax system is indeed developing rapidly and has taken a number
of significant steps forward. Some of these changes receive relatively
little publicity, but nonetheless have an important unifying effect.
The Community Customs Code which came into force on January 1, 1994
consolidates and amends European Customs law in its entirety. It has been
adopted by way of EU Regulation. As a result, it is automatically binding in
all member states and needs no further legislation to make it directly
applicable. Although administration and enforcement is left to member
states, a single accessible body of rules emphasises the singularity of the
Customs Union.
The most significant recent step is the introduction of the Transitional VAT
Regime on January 1, 1993. It is a hybrid system combining both a
'destination' principle for cross-border commercial transactions and an
'origin' principle broadly for non-commercial transactions. Although the
lifting of internal border controls and the doing away of some 60m
administrative documents have been hailed as a success, the introductory
period has not been easy. A fundamental change in the rules has left tax
administrators and payers alike with an enormous task both in understanding
the new system and implementing it. Some have claimed that it merely
replaces one form of bureaucracy by another.
Some of the difficulties raised by the new rules have already been smoothed
out. For example, the so-called Simplification Directive aims at minimising
the tax burden in so-called 'triangular' transactions where delivery of
goods does not follow the same path as legal title.
The fundamental issue is that the current rules are intended to be replaced
by a 'definitive' VAT system by the beginning of 1997. The definitive system
is expected to be based entirely on the origin basis of taxation. Such a
system will clearly favour member states which supply goods and services at
the expense of those in which the goods and services are consumed. Doubts
have therefore been expressed as to whether a 'definitive' system will
emerge and what form it will take.
The year 1997 also marks one of the target dates for direct tax
harmonisation in accordance with the Ruding Committee proposals. Both these
deadlines must be seen in the context of wider European integration. While
the tax integration is intended to follow political and monetary union,
undoubtedly their futures will be tied up with the outcome of that debate.
The Commission's controversial carbon/energy tax proposal for a levy of
Dollars 10 per barrel of oil equivalent has met with considerable
opposition. Nonetheless, the Environment Commissioner, Yannis Paleokrassas,
has suggested a shift overall in the tax burden away from taxes on
employment such as social security taxes to pollution and resources.
He has also suggested a new system of land use and building use and vehicle
taxes to improve environmental and fiscal conditions of cities. He has been
at pains to suggest that this should not increase the overall tax burden.
The Ruding Committee and the Commission have both emphasised the necessity
for completing bilateral tax treaties between member states in order to
minimise double taxation within the EU.
Treaties have been signed between Greece and Luxembourg, and between
Portugal and Ireland. Neither of these are yet in force. Portugal still has
no treaty with the Netherlands, and Greece has no treaty with Ireland or
with Spain.
Some of the most important European Union tax developments have occurred
outside the overt political arena.
The European Court has given judgment on a number of crucial issues
affecting the ability of member states to do as they please in tax matters.
In the Commerzbank case, the European Court found that the UK rules which
allowed only UK residents interest (the 'repayment supplement') on tax
overpayments was discriminatory and contrary to European law.
A similar line has been taken recently by the Advocate General in the
Halliburton case where the Advocate General has issued an opinion condemning
Dutch property transfer tax rules which discriminate against cross-border
corporate reorganisations as being contrary to the law of the European
Union. In each case, disputes have arisen on the validity of the tax laws of
member states not in relation to the taxation directives, but in relation to
the basic European law as set out in the Treaty of Rome.
The European Court has shown no mercy in striking down a miscellany of taxes
imposed by member states which are contrary to European law.
Recent examples include a Portuguese tax on the sales of domestic and
imported paper pulp, Italian annual payments for the registration of
companies, and Italian penalties which discriminate more severely in
relation to cross-border tax offences than offences relating to domestic
transactions.
The Court has examined closely the manner in which member states have given
effect to VAT law, striking down those rules that are not consistent with
VAT Directives.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
