<PROFILE>_AN-EETCSAHAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940520
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Survey of Greek Banking and Finance (3): Climate of mistrust
slowly begins to dissipate - The government is rethinking its ideological
opposition to privatisation in the light of a gaping budget deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Until recently, investment bankers were viewed with suspicion by officials
in Greece's socialist government, who claimed that their conservative
predecessors paid out excessive amounts in advisory fees with little in the
way of results.
The ambitious privatisation programme undertaken by the conservatives
brought many international investment bankers to Athens for the first time.
While a number of mandates were awarded, union opposition and government
in-fighting meant that only a few transactions were completed. Even the
much-vaunted privatisation of OTE, the state telecoms company, fell through
when the government changed.
Faced with a gaping budget deficit and a desperate shortage of funds for
upgrading public utilities, the socialists have been forced to reverse their
ideological opposition to privatisation. However, they have chosen a more
diluted form: partial flotations of a handful of state-owned enterprises on
the Athens stock exchange.
Where the investment banks are concerned, the climate of mistrust is
dissipating slowly as the government examines ways of maximising revenue
from the proposed flotations, scheduled to start this autumn. 'It is
accepted that commissions are going to be slimmer this time and that some
imaginative solutions over share distribution will have to be worked out in
order to bring the unions on board,' says a government adviser.
A dozen investment banks are vying for the lead manager's role in the
flotation of 25-30 per cent of the telecoms company, of which at least half
will take the form of an international tranche to be sold in Europe, the US
and Japan.
Credit Suisse First Boston and J. Henry Schroder Wagg, which have been
appointed global co-ordinators and joint lead managers for the issue's
international tranche by the conservatives, are hoping that willingness to
reduce their commission will overcome lingering political doubts over their
association with the previous government.
Their re-appointment would certainly speed up the flotation from which the
government hopes to raise at least Dr300bn. If successful, it should be
followed by listings of the Public Power Corporation and two state oil
refineries.
Financial advisers from abroad are also in demand for public works projects
as the government assesses bids for projects with a sizeable percentage of
EU funding. Several projects, such as a toll highway through northern
Athens, the new Athens airport to be built at Spata, and a suspension bridge
across the Corinth Gulf, include a self-financing component together with EU
assistance, with little or no contribution from the government's investment
budget.
Arrival of the international investment banks also coincided with the
emergence of corporate finance specialists at Greek banks, who sharpened
their skills while advising on mergers and acquisitions of Greek companies
by European competitors in the run-up to the single market.
This local expertise was tapped by the previous government - both in making
initial valuations of companies scheduled for disposal and in finding buyers
for smaller enterprises.
The OTE (Greek telecom company) listing also offers a large slice of
business for local banks. Like the international bankers, Credit Bank
(Greece's largest private bank) is hoping to be reappointed lead manager of
the domestic tranche of the OTE listing. There will be at least half a dozen
other Greek banks involved in underwriting what will be by far the largest
issue ever made in Greece.
'While we are unlikely to handle a really big deal on our own, our advantage
is that we know the local market, we offer a diversity of skills and we can
accept smaller deals that no international investment bank would be
interested in,' says Mr Panagis Vourloumis, managing director of Alpha
Finance, the investment arm of Credit Bank.
Alpha Finance combines underwriting, corporate advisory and fund management
services under one roof. It is also setting up a bank in Romania, which will
combine commercial and investment banking, with the aim of offering
corporate advisory services to Greek companies active there and in playing a
role in Romania's privatisation programme.
For the moment, however, Alpha Finance, like other local investment bankers,
is focusing on bringing Greek companies to the Athens Stock Exchange.
'Equity business picked up sharply just as privatisation was falling off and
there is now a line of listings stretching to the end of the year,' Mr
Vourloumis says.
The growth of fee-based business in Greece has encouraged Barclays de Zoete
Wedd to set up an Athens-based operation based in the same building as
Barclay's Athens headquarters. BZW Hellas is also handling flotations,
especially those that can also be marketed to institutional investors
abroad.
'There is an increasing amount of financial intermediation going on in
Greece, so it makes sense to have a local presence. We have also been able
to capitalise on existing client relationships,' says Mr Christos Megalou of
BZW Hellas.
The range of business is likely to grow as Greek companies get used to the
idea of calling in an investment banker. Treasury management services and
financial restructuring are two areas where demand is expected to increase.
A new round of acquisitions is also expected as consolidation affects more
sectors, with large Athens-based companies, for example, taking over smaller
rivals in northern Greece. BZW acted as financial adviser last year in the
biggest local acquisition for some time: Veropoulos Supermarkets' Dr4bn
takeover of three rival supermarket chains.
Although there is unlikely to be room for more than two or three
full-fledged investment banks in Athens, several boutique operations have
managed to carve out niches in the market.
'There is a cultural change under way. Companies are looking to corporate
finance specialists to provide the kind of solutions that their local bank
is not equipped for,' says Mr Victor Pisante, of Telesis Capital, a small
investment banking operation which has the support of a brokerage
subsidiary.
</TEXT>
