<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Survey of World Taxation (1): Long arms of the revenue
collectors - National borders are losing their effectiveness as barriers
between tax payers and collecting agencies. Andrew Jack explains the reasons
for the trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tax has never been such an international issue, and never have the domestic
financial affairs of individuals and companies been so affected by
developments in other countries.
The expansion of corporations, the spread of complex new transactions and
the aggressive role of governments and their tax authorities have all been
more evident than ever.
The emergence of a series of regional political and economic blocs - notably
the North American Free Trade Area, the European Union and the European
Economic Area - has influenced the process.
Nowhere has the internationalisation of tax been played out more powerfully
than within the EU. The formal creation of the single European market
brought with it from the start of 1993 a harmonisation of the system of
indirect taxation.
There have been many complaints about the administration of the new system,
and many suggestions about how to handle 'triangular trade' between
companies with operations in a number of different member states.
Yet to a large extent, the teething difficulties have been overcome. Border
controls have been relaxed, new administrative procedures have been put in
place, and there are even some signs of the market beginning to drive down
differentials in value added tax (VAT) rates across borders.
A more important issue for the EU now is whether it will be able to switch
from the current partially 'destination-based' system of VAT to its original
stated objective: a regime in which all goods and services sold across
borders are subject to tax in their country of origin.
There is also the vexed question of greater harmonisation of direct taxes
across Europe. The Ruding Commission, set up to examine the issue, has
apparently been left to gather dust at a time of such political turmoil and
the growing emphasis on subsidiarity.
However, the EU has not entirely given up, with relevant directives being
issued on mergers and reconstructions, withholding tax between parent and
subsidiary companies and transfer pricing arbitration, for example.
Elsewhere around the world, US President Clinton's threat early in his term
in 1992 to clamp down more firmly on foreign corporations suspected of
paying insufficient tax has proved largely hollow.
That is not to say there is any complacency. The US Internal Revenue Service
has long set an example followed by many of its counterparts elsewhere, with
a growing hostility towards perceived evasion and avoidance.
In the UK, this has been reflected in a mammoth finance act - easily the
longest ever at 463 pages in small print - much of which is concerned with
an ever increasing number of general anti-avoidance provisions as well as
specific measures to close loopholes abused in the past.
There have been recent tensions between the US and Japan in particular, with
tax as a battleground in the larger trade war between the two countries. It
has not gone unnoticed that the Japanese government's proposed Dollars 145m
tax adjustment for Coca Cola is almost identical to the refund of Japanese
tax agreed late last year with Nissan.
Equally, eyes remain fixed on the US Supreme Court, and its imminent
judgment on the highly politicised dispute between Barclays bank and the
state of California, which is attempting to levy taxes on a unitary basis on
the company's worldwide profits.
It looks as though the case may turn against Barclays, though the
indications are that this would be unlikely to spark any retaliation by the
UK or other jurisdictions, given that California has since provided
alternatives to unitary tax.
This highlights one of the most important developing issues in international
tax: transfer pricing. While countries in the past were content to leave
charges between related corporate parties across borders at arm's length,
they are now interfering more aggressively to tackle perceived avoidance.
'Among my corporate clients there is a desire not to avoid tax by transfer
pricing but just to get it right,' says Mr Roger White from KPMG Peat
Marwick in London.
One potential solution receiving favourable attention at present may be the
development of advance pricing agreements, such as the long-standing
arrangement in place for Apple Computers between the US and Australia.
Outside the large trade blocs, and eager to exploit loopholes in tax and
company formation legislation, have been the offshore centres - the tax
havens or, as they prefer to be known, the areas of low tax.
The number of centres seeking to attract business and prop up local
economies continues to grow, but the competition between them is
intensifying just at a time when recession in many parts of the world has
reduced the amount of potential business available.
More important, tax authorities are taking a more hostile line towards
regimes that may permit evasion.
On the one hand, double tax treaties with some of the newer developing
states in south America and the former Communist regimes are growing apace.
On the other, after decades in which a network of international tax treaties
between countries has been developed, many existing documents now face the
prospect of being ripped to shreds.
Most significant is the US-Dutch tax treaty, which threatens the structure
of many companies who have traditionally used the Netherlands to take
advantage of differential tax rates.
US officials have already indicated that harsh revisions of other treaties -
such as those with Denmark, Luxembourg and Switzerland - are now in their
sights.
This is one factor driving what Mr Peter Cussons of Price Waterhouse sees as
a new emphasis by companies considering the tax implications of where they
locate - such as the recently announced restructuring of Ford into global
centres.
'We have been talking to a lot of clients in the last 12 to 18 months about
organising on a European regional basis,' he says. 'The historical
structures are out of date.' He sees a move towards a single holding company
able to offset reliefs against profits across its operations.
Globally, there has been a clear trend since the 1980s towards lower
headline rates of tax. That certainly does not mean that the tax take has
actually reduced, but rather that governments have been able to tweak the
fine print.
They have achieved change largely through a shift from direct to indirect
taxation. In addition, allowances, deductions and reliefs in many countries
have been eroded and definitions of profit changed.
Attention is also spreading to new targets for tax. In the UK, in spite of
memories of the poll tax which contributed to the defeat of Mrs Thatcher by
her own party, the government seems to have weathered the controversy over
the extension of VAT to domestic fuel.
In the US, the Clinton administration has singled out tax on tobacco as a
way to fund its planned reforms of the health care system. The EU has
suggested a controversial carbon/energy tax levied on oil, and its
Environment Commissioner has argued for a gradual shift to taxes on
pollution and resources.
Meanwhile, Mr White also highlights the shift in the world towards
self-assessment systems in which the responsibility and costs of tax
collection are increasingly shifted on to individual taxpayers. This is
allowing fiscal authorities to reduce their staff and focus far more on
'auditing' tax returns submitted to them.
Mr John Fairley, partner in charge of the international tax group at Ernst &amp;
Young, says cooperation on investigations between many revenue authorities
has also been growing. 'There has been a significant increase in the
exchange of information since the 1970s.'
As examples he cites the Group of Four - the UK, France, Germany and the US
 -with its own code of practice, and the Pacific Association of Tax
Administrators - comprising Canada, the US, Japan and Australia.
The authorities are providing each other with data on taxpayers and also
launching simultaneous examinations of their tax affairs. His concern is
that this often takes place without the knowledge of the taxpayer, as well
as involving the possible transfer of sensitive information such as trade
secrets.
The restructuring of fiscal authorities is also creating new challenges and
opportunities for the growing number and variety of tax professionals -
including lawyers, accountants and new retail providers of financial
services. Such a shift may well affect how they operate, and how much longer
they escape the currently relatively loose net of regulation that surrounds
them.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
