<PROFILE>_AN-EETCSAG8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940520
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Survey of Greek Banking and Finance (1): A sudden change in
the landscape - The outlook for the banking sector is positive, but hard
economic decisions face the Greek government if it is to close the gap with
the rest of the EU
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's unexpected decision this week to liberalise short-term
capital movement ahead of the EU deadline of July 1, with the aim of
averting a devaluation of the drachma, has suddenly changed Greece's
financial landscape.
Even if the government succeeds in maintaining confidence in the drachma by
keeping interest rates at spectacularly high levels for the next few weeks,
some hard economic decisions will now have to be speeded up.
Instead of converging, Greece is drifting further away from the rest of the
member states in the EU. Recovery is barely visible, with growth in gross
domestic product projected at about 1 per cent this year, against 0.2 per
cent in 1993.
The European Commission has expressed concern over the government's failure
to curb a rising public sector deficit, financed mostly through short-term
Treasury bills, which is fuelling a public debt already equivalent to 138
per cent of GDP.
Yet, there are positive signs too. The black economy - estimated at nearly
40 per cent of GDP - pumps liquidity into capital markets, as a substantial
proportion of untaxed earnings is invested in Treasury bills, mutual funds
and shares on the Athens stock exchange.
And, while the socialist government's latest attempts to address tax evasion
include a 15 per cent tax on both mutual fund dividends and 'repos' -
fixed-term repurchase agreements - there are no plans to introduce a capital
gains tax or to investigate the source of funds entering capital markets.
Moreover, larger Greek companies commanding a comfortable market share are
weathering the recession successfully, some by expanding into neighbouring
Balkan countries where the possibilities of rapid growth in turnover are
seen as outweighing political and economic risks.
Against the odds, too, Greece's banking and financial services industry has
decoupled itself both from gloomy developments in other sectors of the
country's economy and from the uncertainty arising from political tension in
the Balkans as a result of the violent upheavals in the former Yugoslavia.
The 25 domestic banks increased their profits last year by an average 15 per
cent, despite the impact of recession on the smaller businesses which
dominate Greek manufacturing and services, and the negative effect on
balance sheets of the imposition of stricter rules for interest accrual on
non-performing loans.
The foreign banks which compete mainly for corporate and shipping business
are not required to disclose results. But as one foreign banker recently put
it: 'The market may be growing tighter but there are more ways of making
money than there used to be.'
The outlook this year is still positive, although banks will have to
increase provisions because of declining loan quality - the result of a
projected fall in corporate profits and problems business customers are
facing with payments.
Last year's drop in private sector lending by the Greek domestic banks, from
5.9 to 4.1 per cent of gross domestic product, is attributed as much to
increased borrowing abroad by companies keen to take advantage of lower
interest rates as to the recession. Both state-controlled and private banks
are planning to follow some of their corporate clients into Bulgaria,
Romania and Albania, notwithstanding the difficulties according to one
banker of 'setting up in a regulatory vacuum.' So far only Xiosbank, a
private bank, has started operating, (with a branch in Sofia), but other
banks expect to launch Balkan ventures this year.
Another encouraging sign is the improved profitability of seven private
banks established since 1990. Controlled for the most part by Greek
shipowners and insurance companies - and in one case by a Cyprus-based bank
 -the new banks have set the pace in consumer lending, most recently in
devising products to take advantage of a higher loan ceiling of Dr8m.
Although the new banks' combined market share amounts to less than 4 per
cent, they have fewer overheads and more flexibility. They are not
constrained by having a sizeable percentage of deposits tied up in
government bonds, the remnants of the old system of compulsory reserve
requirements.
Their presence also encourages the two big private banks, Credit Bank and
Ergobank, to mount a more aggressive challenge to the four big state banking
groups that control 70 per cent of the market. Following last month's Dr31bn
capital increase, Credit Bank now ranks ahead of National Bank, the
state-controlled giant, in market capitalisation. Its energetic subsidiaries
in fund management, investment banking, leasing and brokerage activities
underline Credit Bank's aspirations to become a European-sized financial
services group.
The state-controlled banks are trying to catch up on automation, as the best
way of retaining market share. Automated teller machines, formerly the
preserve of private and foreign banks, now brighten up the dull facades of
the state banks.
Upgrading dealing rooms and establishing financial subsidiaries, as well as
increasing income, have the additional advantage of providing more jobs
under the pervasive patronage system.
The state banks have become fiefdoms of the governing Panhellenic Socialist
Movement, following a clean sweep of bank governors after last year's
general election.
Its conservative predecessor tried to loosen the state's grip on the banking
system, by persuading Greek bankers working abroad to return to run state
banks, then by abolishing the finance minister's right to a proxy vote for
important shareholders such as state insurance companies and pension funds.
If, in theory, the shareholders now can choose a board headed by a truly
professional banker, there are few signs that the new freedom will be
exercised. Nor are the pension funds yet exploiting the opportunities for
active management of their portfolios - also introduced by the previous
government.
It was left to institutional investors from abroad to increase turnover on
the Athens stock exchange last year. The market shrugged off political
instability in the Balkans, worsening economic indicators and fears that the
socialists would abandon privatisation to become one of the world's more
stable emerging markets. It is likely to acquire depth, with more than 50
flotations and rights issues expected this year, raising the number of
actively traded stocks by about one-third. For growth-minded Greek
companies, a listing on the bourse is becoming an attractive alternative to
bank borrowing.
Privatisation is back on the agenda despite the socialists' initial pledge
to cancel the programme of disposals. However, privatisation no longer
includes sales of banking subsidiaries. Plans to unload four small
state-owned banks through transfers of share packages on the bourse,
following the example of the South Korean Hanwha group's purchase of Bank of
Athens last year, have been dropped.
Even if the socialists oppose dismantling the big state banks, they have
nevertheless embraced the idea of creating a broad share-owning public,
through partial flotations of public enterprises. The first test will be the
flotation of 30 per cent of OTE, the state telecommunications company.
Scheduled for this autumn, it is projected to raise more than Dr300bn.
Even with an international tranche amounting to 15 per cent of the company,
the sheer size of the offering will place tremendous strain on the market's
capacity to absorb an issue five times larger than any to date, not to
mention the underwriting banks' ability to market and distribute shares.
But if the OTE flotation comes off, Greece's financial sector can no longer
be called immature.
</TEXT>
