<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / London Stock Exchange: Willis Corroon retreats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The market's response to acutely disappointing first- quarter figures from
Willis Corroon, the second largest UK insurance broker, was instantaneous as
marketmakers chopped their opening quotations in an attempt to head off any
large-scale selling pressure by institutions.
However, the markdown in the share price failed to stem the selling
pressure, which built up again following what was described by analysts as a
sombre post-figures meeting.
Willis's profits came in at Pounds 42.4m, against estimates which ranged up
to Pounds 59m. Willis shares were eventually down 47 1/2 p, or 20 per cent,
to 191 1/2 p after turnover of 17m, the heaviest recorded in the stock since
the merger with Corroon &amp; Black in October 1990.
Most analysts reduced their current year forecasts, previously around the
Pounds 95m to Pounds 100m mark, to Pounds 70m. Mr Andrew Pitt, insurance
broking specialist at BZW, and a long term bear of the stock, predicted
further downside risk in the stock and said that 'a fair price for the
shares is 180p'.
</TEXT>
