<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / London Stock Exchange: Retail sales figures help an
uncertain market - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further signs of recovery in the domestic economy and favourable comments on
the near-term outlook for base rates helped UK stocks regain some ground
yesterday. Shares closed well below the day's best levels, however, and
trading volume was unexciting.
The mood turned less positive in the afternoon when Wall Street and the US
Federal bond market made an uncertain start to the new session, although the
Dow Average soon turned higher to show a gain of 14 points as London went
home for the day. The final reading showed the FT-SE 100 Index at 3,122.8
for a net gain of 6.3 points.
In early trading, the Footsie had moved up to 3,131.1, helped by news that
domestic retail sales had risen by 0.4 per cent in April to show record
levels for the three-month period. UK government bonds flinched only
momentarily on this news and resumed their upward move as the Bank of France
confirmed expectations of a cut in its intervention rate.
Some nervousness over the US dollar, which has so far failed to respond to
the increase in key rates by the Federal Reserve, marred the second half of
the trading session, although hints of a renewed support operation for the
US currency found no support on the bond trading desks.
Also unsettling were reported views of the president of the Bundesbank that
the interest rate horizon was now clear - translated by market analysts as a
hint that no more cuts in German rates are planned at present.
However, the markets took a favourable view of comments from the panel of
independent forecasters to the British Treasury which said it saw no need
for a rate rise in the UK at present. Gilts closed very firmly and equities
noted that two panel members had wanted a further cut in rates.
The FT-SE Mid 250 Index edged higher by 1.8 to a close of 3,713.5. Seaq
volume was a healthy 621.9m shares, boosted by activity related to trading
statements from a handful of leading British companies. On Wednesday, 722.4m
shares through the Seaq network were worth Pounds 1.66bn at retail level.
The further recovery in gilt-edged stocks, in spite of underlying worries
about the outlook for domestic interest rates, was regarded by market
strategists as favourable for any advance by the equity market.
'The latest Fed move may well usher in a period of stability on short-term
US rates which should provide a more stable platform for global bonds and
equity markets,' commented the global strategy team at NatWest Markets.
At Nikko, strategists looked for the securities markets to take a 'more
considered view' of the Fed's move over the next few days, noting that
currency markets have failed so far to shake off the recent negative stance.
There were signs of significant underlying activity as the institutions
picked up stock in sectors which have suffered over the past fortnight.
Motor industry shares recovered ground, and the investment focus turned back
in favour of the manufacturing sectors.
Support for the consumer-orientated stocks was more selective and centred on
recent trading statements from leading names. Financial sectors were left to
drift as investors sought out opportunities elsewhere, although there was
some interest in property shares, which were again seen as offering
significant recovery potential.
</TEXT>
