<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Strengthening yen puts
check on Nikkei's advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A rise in the yen discouraged investors and heavy selling initially
depressed share prices, before arbitrage buying brought a recovery and left
the Nikkei 225 average moderately ahead on the day, writes Emiko Terazono in
Tokyo.
The index gained 68.61 at 20,221.34 after a low of 20,034.21 and high of
20,302.46. The yen's advance to the Y103 level dampened investor confidence
as many market participants had hoped for a retreat in the Japanese currency
against the dollar after the increase in US interest rates.
Selling by Nomura Securities depressed sentiment during the morning session,
but a later rise in the futures market prompted index-linked arbitrage
buying and small-lot bargain hunting.
Volume amounted to 260m shares, against Wednesday's 290m. In spite of the
fall in activity, some traders were optimistic due to buying support around
the 20,000 level.
The Topix index of all first section stocks was 0.29 easier at 1,634.40,
while the Nikkei 300 closed 0.10 off at 298.78. Declines led rises by 522 to
430, with 217 issues unchanged. In London the ISE/Nikkei 50 index firmed
2.39 to 1,334.47.
Index-linked buying helped banks, which are heavily weighted in the Topix
index. Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank rose Y40 to Y1,990 and Bank of Tokyo Y30 to
Y1,670.
Brokers were also higher, with Nomura Securities up Y20 to Y2,290 and Daiwa
Securities gaining Y30 at Y1,690. The top four brokers reported the first
rebound in earnings since 1989-90 thanks to a rise in brokerage and
underwriting commissions.
Some analysts pointed out that the brokers' own profits forecasts for the
current year to next March seemed too conservative since active cost-cutting
would help profits. 'The companies are still a long way from being truly
healthy, but they are moving in the right direction,' said Mr Mark Faulkner,
banking analyst at SG Warburg.
The rise in the yen upset high-technology stocks. Hitachi, the most active
issue of the day, fell Y18 to Y992 and Sony declined Y100 to Y5,840.
The government's announcement to freeze increases in public service charges
until next year depressed Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, which had been
applying for a rate increase for local calls. The stock dropped Y24,000 to
Y855,000.
In Osaka, the OSE average rose 47.57 to 22,371.42 in volume of 10.9m shares.
Roundup
Profit-taking eroded recent gains in some of the Pacific Rim markets.
HONG KONG encountered profit-taking after Wednesday's strong advance, the
Hang Seng index ending 121.66, or 1.3 per cent, down at 9,354.98. The
underlying mood remained buoyant, however, in response to the revival of
Sino-British talks on Hong Kong's new airport.
Turnover was a strong HKDollars 4.99bn, but down from Wednesday's revised
HKDollars 6.93bn.
HK Telecom, which reported slightly better than expected 1993-94 results,
picked up from a day's low of HKDollars 14.80 to end 20 cents down at
HKDollars 14.90.
Property issues were among the big losers. Cheung Kong fell HKDollars 1.25
to HKDollars 38.50 and Henderson Land slid HKDollars 1.50 to HKDollars 42
but SHK Properties was steady at HKDollars 53.
KUALA LUMPUR was mostly lower, with buying mainly focused on cash-rich
Malayan United Industries (MUI), which announced the acquisition of
additional shares in Hong Kong's South China Morning Post. The composite
index shed 7.29 to 1,002.98.
MUI, which surged 32 cents to MDollars 4.02 in volume of 2.7m shares, has
been aggressively seeking acquisitions since selling its MUI Bank and MUI
Finance in January for MDollars 1.1bn. It bought another 5 per cent of SCMP
to raise its stake in the newspaper concern to 20.6 per cent.
TAIPEI's consolidation went on, with much of the selling aimed at
industrials. The weighted index retreated 38.64 to 5,944.61 in turnover that
fell to TDollars 58.31bn from Wednesday's TDollars 62.8bn.
Late profit-taking was heavy in paper and plastic stocks, which posted
moderate gains during previous advances.
MANILA suffered for the second consecutive day because of anxieties over the
extent of the damage caused by investigations into Bancapital Development
Corporation, an unlicensed investment house that appeared to have closed
leaving a trail of undelivered Treasury bills.
The Composite index declined 43.78, or 1.5 per cent, to 2,855.57 in volume
that fell to 739.97m shares, from 1.88bn on Wednesday.
SYDNEY lost ground as profit-taking and a sharp overnight fall in commodity
prices overshadowed the positive interim results announced by National
Australia Bank.
The All Ordinaries index closed 14.1 down at 2,093.7, but off a low of
2,084.6, in volume of 214.1m shares.
NAB, which posted interim net profits of ADollars 868.8m, up from ADollars
507.3m, finished 2 cents higher at ADollars 12.16 after an early low of
ADollars 12.00.
Westpac, which returned to a ADollars 320.9m net interim profit, against a
loss of ADollars 204.6m, slipped 15 cents to ADollars 4.84.
WELLINGTON gave back most of the gains made on Wednesday, the NZSE-40
capital index falling 30.25 to 2,124.85.
BANGKOK saw foreign demand push the SET index 25.64, or 1.9 per cent, ahead
to 1,351.11 in heavy turnover of Bt8bn.
The property development sector jumped 3.9 per cent, led by Natural Park,
which rose Bt14 to Bt155, and Sammakorn, up Bt13 at Bt149.
SINGAPORE edged higher, with much of the day's attention focused on Neptune
Orient Lines, the shipping group, amid rumours of a bonus issue, the
positive impact of a road show ahead of the listing of its US subsidiary,
and talks of freight rate increases.
The Straits Times Industrial index rose 6.44 to 2,329.60 in volume of
135.99m shares, while NOL closed 19 cents higher at SDollars 2.62 in
turnover of 13.24m shares.
SEOUL saw renewed institutional buying for large-capitalisation
manufacturing issues which sent the composite index 4.86 higher to 951.73.
However, swift profit-taking limited gains in primary blue chips. Posco, the
steelmaker, was unchanged at Won67,300, off a day's high of Won68,800.
JAKARTA moved higher for the fourth straight day, in spite of local
profit-taking towards the close in response to rises in key domestic
discount rates which may herald higher deposit returns. Strong foreign
demand left the Jardine index 1.18 up at 101.67.
