</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / World Commodities Prices: LME copper pulls back from
17-month high - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The London Metal Exchange COPPER market proved vulnerable yesterday
afternoon, settling about Dollars 30 below an early 17-month high and
pulling other metals back with it.
The three months delivery price closed at Dollars 2,252 a tonne, up Dollars
51.50 from Wednesday's official close, but close to levels reached later
that evening. However, with a further big decline in LME stocks expected to
be announced today, the three months delivery price should be able to resume
an advance towards its immediate target of Dollars 2,300 a tonne objective,
traders suggested.
At the London bullion market the SILVER price suddenly leapt 6 cents a troy
announce, pulling GOLD into another challenge of its Dollars 383-an-ounce
resistance just minutes before the afternoon fixing. The yellow metal closed
at Dollars 383.70, up Dollars 1, while silver ended at Dollars 5.62 1/2 , up
7 cents.
Dealers said the markets were turning 'less bearish, if not more bullish',
and were looking to the Commodity Research Bureau index, now at a 3 1/2
 year high, for guidance.
Compiled from Reuter
</TEXT>
