<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Wool at auctions held towards the end of the main selling season, has sold
at prices mostly firm and unchanged. Some of the main market indicators are
up again, with Australia's at 614 cents a kg. compared with 603 a week ago,
but this does exaggerate the rise on a strictly comparable basis. Whatever
the exact market measurement, wool sold very well and clearances in all
primary markets remained good. The problem for those buying it is their own
customers are still showing reluctance in paying the quite substantial
increases from recession low points. Retailers in particular are unhappy at
the prospect of having to raise their own selling prices, or of cutting
present margins. The battle is unresolved but with ho;idays in consumer
markets and recess in wool sales acting as incentives, background buying
interest remains.
</TEXT>
