<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Decision delayed on new bid for
Chilean copper
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID PILLING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SANTIAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Codelco, Chile's state copper company, has postponed for one week a decision
on the troubled El Abra copper project pending fresh information from
Cyprus-Amax, the US company whose recalculated bid it is considering.
A consortium of Cyprus and Lac Minerals of Canada had last year offered
Dollars 555m for 51 per cent of El Abra, one of the world's biggest
undeveloped copper deposits.
Last month, however, Lac pulled out after preliminary tests showed that El
Abra, which the consortium had estimated at an annual capacity of 225,000
tonnes, might be smaller than originally believed.
Mr Juan Villarzu, president of Codelco, denied a newspaper report that
Cyprus had resubmitted a bid of Dollars 350m, compared with the Dollars 240m
offered by the underbidder, a consortium of Magma Copper of the US and
Australia's Broken Hill Proprietary.
A Cyprus official refused to deny or confirm the Dollars 350m figure.
</TEXT>
